label: "Basilica" of San Vitale
description: A church (but not a basilica) in Ravenna, Italy, established by Bishop Ecclesius in 526 AD and consecrated ca. 547 AD.

label: 'Ein-Shadud
description: Small settlement in the Jezreel Valley containing structures dated to the Early Bronze Age I. Salvage excavations were conducted on the site in 1979 prior to its destruction by construction.

label: 'Ir David/Wadi Hilweh
description: The City of David is the name given in the 20th century to an archaeological site located in the Arab neighborhood of Wadi Hilweh, located south of the Temple Mount and the Ophel in East Jerusalem. The site contains pottery from as early as the Chalcolithic Age, and has been proposed as a possible original core of the city of Jerusalem. The Silwa necropolis, a burial site dated to the 9th-7th centuries BCE, is located within this area.

label: (A)Nogyra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 B3 (A)Nogyra

label: (H)Adriaticum/Superum Mare
description: A body of water separating the Apennine Peninsula of Italy from the Balkan Peninsula.

label: (H)Emesa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 C4 (H)Emesa

label: (H)Enna
description: The origins of (H)Enna are unclear. Some sources claim it was founded by Syracuse in 664 B.C. but the archaeological record suggests it is likely a Hellenized Sikel settlement.

label: (Nea) Paphos
description: The legendary birthplace of the goddess Aphrodite, (Nea) Paphos has been a center of activity since the Final Bronze Age when Mycenaeans honored the goddess there. The site was listed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1980.

label: (W)Axos
description: An ancient settlement on the island of Crete.

label: *Altiaia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 I3 *Altiaia

label: *Aquae
description: *Aquae or pagus Aquensis was a bath site located along the Strei river in the territory of Ulpia Traiana Sarmizegetusa.

label: *Argentomagus
description: *Argentomagus was a pre-Roman and later Roman settlement in the territory of the Bituriges tribe.

label: *Athela
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 E4 *Athela

label: *Atura/Vicus Iulii
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E2 *Atura/Vicus Iulii

label: *Aurinia/Saturnia
description: *Aurinia/Saturnia was a settlement in Etruria. Dionysius of Halicarnassus claimed it was founded by the Pelasgians. Saturnia received a Roman colony in 183 BC.

label: *Brocolitia
description: Roman fort near present-day Carrawburgh.

label: *Coriosopitum/Coria
description: A Roman town and fort at present-day Corbridge.

label: *Durovernum
description: Durovernum Cantiacorum, modern Canterbury, was the site of a pre-Roman oppidum and, then, post A.D. 43 of a Roman fort.

label: *Eborolacum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I2 *Eborolacum

label: *Firmidianum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 *Firmidianum

label: *Hydai/*Kydai
description: A ancient settlement in western Anatolia, ca. 8 km west of the modern town of Milas in the Muğla Province. Remains of the ancient settlement are located under and around the modern village of Damlıboğaz.

label: *Mistea/*Klaudiokaisareia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 G2 *Mistea/*Klaudiokaisareia

label: *Mobolla
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 G3 *Mobolla

label: *Nemetodurum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C4 *Nemetodurum

label: *Qubba
description: A monastery constructed in the fifth century CE on the site of a cave previously inhabited by St. Paul the Anchorite.

label: *Ratiatum
description: A site in the Loire estuary that served as a port.

label: *Ricomagus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I3 *Ricomagus

label: *Silina Inss.
description: *Silina Inss. (Isles of Scilly) form an archipelago off the southwestern tip of the Cornish peninsula of Great Britain.

label: *Sosontigi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A4 *Sosontigi

label: *Thallos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 D4 *Thallos

label: *Vercovicium
description: A fort on Hadrian's Wall.

label: *Vertillum?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 B2 *Vertillum?

label: *Zorlanae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 H3 *Zorlanae

label: A(u)xoume
description: Present-day Aksum in Ethiopia. The center of the Aksumite Kingdom, a maritime trading power that flourished from the first to the tenth centuries AD. The city was listed as UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

label: Aardenburg
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D1 Aardenburg

label: Ab(ou)la/Al(a)ba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 C4 Ab(ou)la/Al(a)ba

label: Abakainon
description: A city of the Siculi on the northern coast of Sicily.

label: Aballo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 A2 Aballo

label: Abaton
description: An ancient site designated as the burial place of Osiris-Serapis.

label: Abbazia di San Vincenzo al Volturno
description: An historic Benedictine monastery located in the Province of Isernia, near the source of the river Volturno.

label: Abbazia di Sant'Antimo
description: The Abbey of Sant'Antimo was a Benedictine monastery located in the comune of Montalcino, Italy, about 9 km from the line of the Via Francigena. The abbey grew around the site of an oratory to Saint Anthimus, whose relics may have been relocated here in the eighth century. The site was formerly occupied by a Roman villa.

label: Abbey of Monte Cassino
description: A multi-period hilltop settlement with evidence for ancient terrace construction that now supports an abbey of the Benedictine order.

label: Abdera
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B5 Abdera

label: Abdera
description: Abdera was a coastal city located on Cape Bulustra, near the estuary of the river Nestos.

label: Abellinum
description: Abellinum was a settlement of the Hirpini in Campania.

label: Abia
description: An ancient coastal city of Messenia that modern scholars locate in an area known in modern times as Palaiochora, i.e., in the modern village that now takes its name from the ancient one. Ruins of a medieval (Venetian?) castle are generally assumed to have been built on the ancient site.

label: Abila M.
description: A low mountain overlooking the port of Ceuta in North Africa.

label: Abodiacum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 C2 Abodiacum

label: Abonouteichos/Ionopolis
description: A coastal town of Paphlagonia.

label: Aborras/Chaboras (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 B2 Aborras/Chaboras fl.

label: Abrau (peninsula)
description: The northwestern end of the Caucasus Mountains, forming a short peninsula in the northeastern Black Sea.

label: Abrotonum/Sabratha
description: The westernmost of the "three cities" of Tripolis, Abrotonum/Sabratha was founded ca. 500 B.C. by the Phoenicians. The city was part of the Numidian Kingdom of Massinissa before becoming a Roman city.

label: Abu Ballas
description: A sandstone peak approximately 200 kilometers southwest of the Dakhleh Oasis, containing extensive pottery remains dated from the 3rd millennium BCE through the Roman period. Abu Ballas was likely a way station along a caravan route connecting the Dakhleh Oasis with Gilf Kebir.

label: Abu Sir
description: An Old Kingdom necropolis serving the ancient Egyptian city of Memphis.

label: Abusina
description: Abusina was the site of a Roman auxiliary fort along the Danube, some 30 km SW of Regensburg (at the modern village of Eining).

label: Abydos
description: A city of Mysia located on the Hellespont.

label: Abydos/Ebot
description: Ancient Egyptian city and burial place of its first kings. Primary cult place of the god Osiris.

label: Abū Ẓabī
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Acci/Col. Iulia Gemella
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Acci/Col. Iulia Gemella

label: Acerrae
description: Acerrae was an ancient Oscan city of Campania, perhaps originally named Akeru. The Romans granted it civitas sine suffragio in 332 BC.

label: Achaea/Achaia (region)
description: An ancient Greek region on the northern coast of the Peloponnese.

label: Achaia (province)
description: A Roman province of the early empire, comprising the Peloponnese, central Greece, Euboea, most of the Ionian islands, and other adjacent areas.

label: Achaia (province, late)
description: A late Roman imperial province, having been diminished in extent during the second century CE and reorganized by Diocletian within the diocese of Moesia.

label: Acharnai (N)
description: Acharnai (N) was the largest deme of ancient Attika, the sole inland deme of the tribe Oineis.

label: Acharnai (S)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B2 Acharnai (S)

label: Achelous (river)
description: A river of Western Greece. Its floods were noted by Herodotus.

label: Acium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G3 Acium

label: Acrae
description: Akrai, an ancient city of Sicily, originated as a colony founded by Syracuse in 664 B.C., making it the first of the city's three colonial foundations.

label: Acrillae
description: A Greek colony founded in Sicily ca. 598 B.C., Acrillae was an important economic center. In 213 B.C., the Roman consul M. Claudius Marcellus fought an engagement against the Syracusans there.

label: Acropolis of Athens
description: The acropolis of the ancient city of Athens in Greece.

label: Actium
description: Site of an ancient temple of Apollo near which Octavian erected a monument to commemorate his naval victory over M. Antonius in 31 BCE.

label: Acumincum
description: Acumincum (modern Stari Slankamen in Serbia) was a settlement of the Scordisci that was later conquered by the Romans. During the Flavian period, the Cohors I Britannica equitata and II Adjutrix were based there.

label: Ad Flexum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E2 Ad Flexum

label: Ad Turrem
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 A3 Ad Turrem

label: Ad Tygrem/Amida
description: Modern Diyarbakir in Turkey.

label: Adada
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 E2 Adada

label: Adana/Antiochia ad Sarum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 G3 Adana/Antiochia ad Sarum

label: Adane/Athenae/Eudaimon Arabia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 C3 Adane/Athenae/Eudaimon Arabia

label: Addua (river)
description: The Adda river is a river in northern Italy and a tributary of the Padus fl. (Po river).

label: Adedou Kome
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 B3 Adedou Kome

label: Adiabene
description: Adiabene was an ancient kingdom in Assyria situated between the Upper Zab (Lycus) and the Lower Zab (Caprus) rivers. Its capital was at Arbela.

label: Adonis (river)
description: The Abraham River of Lebanon.

label: Adora
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Adora

label: Adranon
description: Adranon was a settlement founded ca. 400 B.C. on the western slopes of mount Aetna.

label: Aecae
description: An ancient town of Apulia that in legend was reported to have been founded by Diomedes. In the third century B.C. the Roman general Quintus Fabius Maximus captured the town after the battle of Cannae.

label: Aegaeum Mare
description: The Aegean Sea is the largest body of water between Greece and Asia Minor and an embayment of the Mediterranean Sea.

label: Aegates (islands)
description: The Egadi Islands, a small group of mountainous islands northwest of Sicily.

label: Aegina (island)
description: An island in the Saronic gulf that is surrounded by Attica, Megaris, and Epidaurus.

label: Aelana/Aila
description: The city of Aqaba on the Red Sea.

label: Aenaria/Pithekoussai (island)
description: Aenaria/Pithekoussai Ins. (modern Ischia) is a volcanic island located in the northern part of the Bay of Naples.

label: Aenus (river)
description: The Inn river is a right tributary of the Danube.

label: Aeoliae (islands)
description: A volcanic archipelago in the Tyrrhenian Sea composed of eight islands.

label: Aere
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 D3 Aere

label: Aesernia
description: An ancient settlement (modern Isernia in Italy)

label: Aesis
description: An Umbrian town that became a colonia civium Romanorum under the name of Aesis in 247 B.C.

label: Aesis (river)
description: Aesis fl. (modern Esino river) is a river of the Marche region of Italy and flows into the Adriatic Sea.

label: Aethusa (island)
description: One of the Pelagie Islands in the Mediterranean Sea, used as a naval base by the Romans during the Punic Wars.

label: Agatha
description: Agatha (modern Agde), also known as Agatha Tyche, was a colonial foundation of ca. 525 B.C. The colony was founded by Phocaean Greeks from Massilia.

label: Agedincum
description: A settlement located at the Yonne-Vanne confluence in the territory of the Senones.

label: Aghtamar
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 F2 Aghtamar

label: Aginnum
description: Aginnum (modern Agen) was the capital of the Nitiobriges in Gaul.

label: Agora of Athens
description: The marketplace of the ancient city of Athens in Greece.

label: Agrinion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 A3 Agrinion

label: Agudo
description: A Spanish village located in the west of the province of Ciudad Real that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Aguntum
description: Aguntum was an ancient settlement of Noricum that received municipal status under Claudius.

label: Agyrium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F3 Agyrium

label: Aharawan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 C2 Aharawan

label: Aiane
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 A4 Aiane

label: Aigai
description: An ancient settlement of Achaia in the Peloponnese. Modern Akrata.

label: Aigaion
description: A mountain range in eastern Crete, known today as Dikti (Dicte).

label: Aigeai
description: An ancient settlement most noted for the discovery, in 1977, of Macedonian royal tombs at the site.

label: Aigeira
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C1 Aigeira

label: Aigiale
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B4 Aigiale

label: Aigina (settlement)
description: The primary ancient settlement on the Aegean island of the same name.

label: Aigion
description: A city-state of ancient Achaea that numbered as one of the 12 Achaean cities. The city was located 30 stades from Rhypae, and 40 stades from Helice.

label: Aigosthena
description: Aigosthena was a fortified city of in the Megaris that served as one of Megara's ports. In the Hellenistic period, it became an autonomous city.

label: Aigousa (island)
description: Aigousa Ins. - meaning 'goat island' - is an island west of Sicily that was the scene of a major naval engagement of the First Punic War.

label: Ain Amour
description: A small oasis lying about 60 km north west of Kharga, on the escarpment outlining the depression. It was the only water source along the Darb Ain Amur, one of the two tracks that linked Kharga and Dakhla. The archaeological remains consist of a Late Period stone temple and a large cemetery. Surveyed between 2006 and 2011 by the North Kharga Oasis Survey project.

label: Ain Dara
description: Ain Dara, located northwest of Aleppo, Syria, is noted for the remains of an Iron Age Syro-Hittite temple.

label: Ainos
description: An ancient city located at modern Enez in Turkey, Ainos was probably an Aeolian colony sent from Mytilene or Cyme in the seventh century BCE.

label: Aixone
description: Aixone was an ancient coastal deme of the phyle Kekropis, located on the west coast of Attica south of Athens in the area of modern Glyphada.

label: Ajanta Caves
description: The Ajanta Caves are among the earliest Buddhist cave monuments and date from the second and first centuries B.C. During the Gupta period (fifth and sixth centuries A.D.), additional decorated caves were added to the group.

label: Akdamar Island
description: The second largest of the four islands in Lake Van, in eastern Turkey.

label: Ake/Ptolemais
description: The Phoenician city of Akko was re-founded by Ptolemy II Philadelphos from ca. 285-246 B.C.

label: Akragas/Agrigentum
description: Akragas/Agrigentum was an ancient city of Sicily and is now known as Agrigento. The Archaeological Area of Agrigento was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

label: Akrai?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B3 Akrai?

label: Akrokorinthos
description: Akrokorinthos (Acrocorinth) was the acropolis of ancient Corinth.

label: Al(l)ifae
description: An ancient town of either Oscan or Samnite origin situated in the Volturno river valley.

label: Alalie/Aleria
description: A city of Corsica with significant pre-historic, Greek, Etruscan, and Roman phases.

label: Alalkomenai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 E4 Alalkomenai

label: Alauna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 E2 Alauna

label: Alauna/Alione
description: A Roman fort at present-day Maryport. Part of Cumbrian coastal defenses.

label: Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium
description: Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium (modern Ventimiglia) was the main settlement of the Ligurian tribe of the Intemelii. In the 2nd century BC, it came under the control of the Roman Republic. Albintimilium became a municipium in 89 BC in the tribus Falerna. In the same period, the city walls were built, with several towers. The city flourished in the early Imperial period, with baths, an aqueduct, and a theater. In the 6th and early 7th century, it was a Byzantine kastron, coming under the control of the Longobards in 641. During the 7th and 8th centuries, the Roman city was slowly abandoned in favour of a smaller hilltop settlement focused around the Cathedral.

label: Alba Fucens
description: A town of the Aequi along the Marsic frontier where the Romans established a Latin colony in 304/3 B.C. Alba Fucens was a significant center of the middle republican period and became a place where Rome kept state prisoners, including Syphax of Numidia, Perseus of Macedonia, and Bituitus, king of the Arverni.

label: Alba Helviorum
description: Alba Helviorum was the capital of the Helvii in Gallia Narbonensis.

label: Alba Longa
description: Alba Longa, located in the Alban Hills southeast of Rome, was the chief city and founder of the Latin League. Conflict with Rome caused Alba's destruction in the seventh century B.C. The legendary history of Romulus and Remus connects them to the royal lineage of the city. The ancient city is probably to be located at and around the site of modern Castel Gandolfo.

label: Alba Pompeia
description: Alba Pompeia (modern Alba) was a Celtic and Ligurian settlement that entered into the Roman sphere during the late Republican period. In Imperial times, Alba was the birthplace of Pertinax.

label: Albanus L.
description: A volcanic lake in ancient Latium at the foot of Albanus Mons, Albanus Lacus (Alban Lake) is connected with the site of the city of Alba Longa and, later, with imperial properties of the Flavian house.

label: Albanus M.
description: The second highest summit of the Alban Hills, Mons Albanus is an extinct volcano with an elevation of 950 m (3,117 ft). In the middle of the first millennium B.C. there may have been volcanic activity as noted by the historian Livy. The mountain was sacred for Latin peoples who held important festivals there and a major shrine to Iuppiter Latiaris stands on the mountain top.

label: Albiga
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H2 Albiga

label: Albinia (river)
description: The Albegna is a river of southern Tuscany and flows from Monte Amiata to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

label: Albona
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Albona

label: Albufera
description: Once a Spanish city, Albufera is today located in the south of Portugal, in the region of Algarve. It belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X (XIII century). Its modern Portuguese name is Albufeira.

label: Albulae/Praesidium Sufative
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 29 D1 Albulae/Praesidium Sufative

label: Alcala de Guadayra
description: A Spanish village located to the east of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Alcalá de Guadaíra.

label: Alea
description: An ancient settlement in Arcadia that flourished from the Classical to Roman periods.

label: Alebaece Reiorum Apollinarium/Apollinaris Reiorum/Reii
description: Alebaece Reiorum Apollinarium/Apollinaris Reiorum/Reii was the capital of the tribe of the Reii. Modern Riez in France's Alpes-de-Haute-Provence department.

label: Aletrium
description: A Hernican hill town that formed part of a sixth-century B.C. defensive league against Volscian and Samnite aggression and allied itself to Tarquinius Superbus. Rome eventually took Aletrium in 306 B.C.; by the first century B.C., the site was a Roman municipium.

label: Alexandria
description: The ancient port city in Egypt's Nile Delta, founded by Alexander the Great in 332/331 BCE.

label: Alexandria Ariorum/Artacavan/Harey
description: Alexandria Ariorum/Artacavan/Harey (modern Herat, Afghanistan).

label: Alexandria ad Issum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 C3 Alexandria ad Issum

label: Alexandria/Alexandropolis/Cufis
description: Now Kandahar in Afghanistan, Alexandria/Alexandropolis/Cufis is an ancient site founded by Alexander the Great ca. 330 BC. The indigenous people of the Hellenistic period were likely the Pakthas.

label: Alexandria/Kapisa
description: "Alexandria in the Caucasus", an Achaemenid town re-established by Alexander the Great at modern Charikar, near Bagram in Afghanistan.

label: Alipheira
description: Pausanias notes that Alipheira was mostly abandoned when Arcadians were merged into Megalopolis.

label: Allas-les-Mines
description: A Gallo-Roman villa.

label: Allava
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C4 Allava

label: Allègre
description: The site of sulphur springs that also revealed evidence for a sanctuary that included 24 altars, so of which carried dedications either to nymphs or mother goddesses. A number of Roman artifacts indicate activity at the site from the Flavian to the Antonine period.

label: Almaden
description: A Spanish village located in the south of the province of Ciudad Real that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today known as Almadén.

label: Alpes Maritimae (late Roman province)
description: The post-Diocletianic province of Alpes Maritimae according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324). It was assigned to the diocese of Viennensis.

label: Alpes Maritimae (province)
description: A Roman province established in the early days of the empire and persisting, with changes, into Late Antiquity.

label: Alphe(i)os (river)
description: The longest river of the Peloponnesus.

label: Alsietinus lacus
description: The Alsietinus lacus, modern Lago di Martignano, is a small volcanic crater-lake in southern Etruria. The lake was the source of the Augustan aqueduct aqua Augusta Alsietina that served non-potable water to the Transtiberim and Ianiculum.

label: Alsium
description: Alsium served as a port for Caere, together with Fregenae.

label: Altar of Hieron II
description: A monumental altar built around the third century B.C. that was probably dedicated to Zeus Eleutherios. Remains of the altar are located in the archaeological area of Neapolis in Syracuse, Sicily.

label: Altava
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 29 D2 Altava

label: Altrier
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G3 Altrier

label: Alvand/Orontes/Oroandes M.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 92 D2 Alvand/Orontes/Oroandes M.

label: Alyke
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 D3 Alyke

label: Amanium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F2 Amanium

label: Amaras
description: An ancient settlement and early Christian site, now occupied partly by an Armenian Apostolic monastery and its 18th century church.

label: Amarna
description: A new capital for Egypt founded by Akhenaten during his reign as pharaoh during Egypt's Eighteenth Dynasty.

label: Amarynthos
description: An ancient coastal settlement on the island of Euboea, located at modern Palaiokhoria/Kato Vathia (just east of the modern Amarynthos).

label: Amaseia
description: Amaseia (modern Amasya) was a naturally fortified settlement in the Pontic mountains near the Black Sea. It served as the capital of the kingdom of Pontus from ca. 300 BC to 183 BC.

label: Amastris/Sesamos
description: An ancient settlement on the Black Sea coast in Asia Minor, modern Amasra in Turkey.

label: Amathe/Epiphaneia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 C3 Amathe/Epiphaneia

label: Amathous
description: Amathous, an ancient royal city of Cyprus.

label: Amberd
description: A 10th-century fortress located on Mount Aragats in modern Aragatsotn province, Armenia.

label: Amblada
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 G2 Amblada

label: Ambrossos
description: An ancient Greek settlement in Phocis. Modern Distomo.

label: Ameria (Umbria)
description: Ameria, claimed by Cato the Elder (quoted by Pliny) as the oldest town in Umbria, was an important center that may have gained Roman municipal status as early as 338 B.C., following the Latin War.

label: Amestratus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Amestratus

label: Amisus/Peiraieus
description: A colony of Miletus that eventually came to be part of the kingdom of Pontus.

label: Amiternum
description: Amiternum was an ancient settlement of the Sabines that Rome captured in 293 BC. The settlement was situated at the intersection of four Roman roads: the Via Caecilia, the Via Claudia Nova, and the two branches of the Via Salaria. The historian Sallust was born at Amiternum in 86 B.C.

label: Amman/Philadelpheia
description: An ancient settlement in northwest Jordan (modern Amman) received a Macedonian settlement and the name of Philadelphia from Ptolemy II Philadelphos (285-246 BC). The modern Amman, Jordan.

label: Ammodios/Amouda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 C3 Ammodios/Amouda

label: Ammon
description: The Siwa Oasis was, in antiquity, the site of the oracular temple of Amun (Zeus Ammon).

label: Ammonos Balithonos Akra/Caput Vada
description: This promontory, known today as Ras Kaboudia, is the easternmost point of the coast of Tunisia.

label: Amol
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 H4 Amol

label: Amorgos (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B4 Amorgos Ins.

label: Amphiareion
description: The Amphiareion of Oropos was an ancient sanctuary dedicated in the fifth century BCE to the hero Amphiaraos and located in the hills southeast of the port of Oropos.

label: Amphikleia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D3 Amphikleia

label: Amphipolis
description: A Greek city in Thrace located on the east bank of the Strymon river, Amphipolis was originally founded as an Athenian colony.

label: Amphissa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 C3 Amphissa

label: Amphitheater of Alba Fucens
description: A first century A.D. amphitheater at Alba Fucens built during the reign of Tiberius.

label: Amyklai
description: Amyklai was an ancient settlement located near Sparta in the plain by the Eurotas river to the east of the Taygetus mountains.

label: Amélie-les-Bains
description: Remains of a Gallo-Roman bath complex are now incorporated in a modern spa at Amélie-les-Bains-Palada in the French department of Pyrénées-Orientales.

label: Anabucis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 37 E2 Anabucis

label: Anagnia
description: Anagnia was a Hernican town that sided with Rome against the Volscians and later became civitas sine suffragio. By Cicero's time it received the status of municipium.

label: Anaphe
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B5 Anaphe

label: Anaphe (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B5 Anaphe Ins.

label: Anaphlystos
description: A coastal deme of the tribe Antiochis in Attika, located on Anavyssos Bay.

label: Anatho
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 C3 Anatho

label: Anazarbos/Caesarea/Ioustin(ian)oupolis
description: Anazarbos or Anazarbus was an ancient city of Cilicia; its extensive multi-period archaeological remains are located adjacent to the modern village of Dilekkaya in the Kozan district of Turkey's Adana province. Anazarbos became the capital of Cilicia Secunda in the later Roman empire. The city was rebuilt in 527 following an earthquake and destroyed by Mamluk forces in 1374.

label: Ancient Egypt (region)
description: The ancient kingdom(s) and region of Egypt as understood by the Egyptians themselves, their neighbors, and their successors. Individual administrative districts, provinces, nomes, and the like have separate place resources in Pleiades.

label: Ancon(a)
description: A port city founded by colonists from Syracuse in 387 BC.

label: Ancyra (Galatia)
description: An ancient settlement and later fortified settlement that served as the seat of the koinon of Galatia and capital of the subsequent Roman province. Modern Ankara in Turkey.

label: Andance
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 D3 Andance

label: Andania
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B3 Andania

label: Andautonia
description: A Roman settlement and municipium near the Sava river, on the location of the modern village of Šćitarjevo, Croatia, south of Zagreb, near Velika Gorica.

label: Andematunnum
description: A Gallo-Roman city and the capital of the Lingones.

label: Anderitum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 A4 Anderitum

label: Andes
description: Andes is said to be the birthplace of the Latin poet Vergil.

label: Androna/Andarna
description: Modern Al Andarin, a ruined late-antique / early Byzantine walled city located in modern Syria, about 75km south-southeast of Aleppo.

label: Andros (island)
description: The northernmost island of the Cyclades.

label: Andros (settlement)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A4 Andros

label: Andusia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 B1 Andusia

label: Anemurium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 B4 Anemurium

label: Angitiae Lucus
description: Angitiae Lucus refers to the grove of Angitia, a divine figure of the Marsi tribe.

label: Anisa
description: Anisa was an ancient settlement of Cappadocia that was inhabited in Hellenistic, Roman, and Byzantine times.

label: Anopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Anopolis

label: Anteae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 B2 Anteae

label: Anthedon
description: A port city of northern Boeotia located in the foothills of Mount Messapion on the Gulf of Euboea.

label: Anthemous
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D4 Anthemous

label: Anthemous (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D4 Anthemous fl.

label: Antigoneia/(Col. Augusta) Alexandria Troas
description: An ancient city of the Troad, founded as Antigoneia by Antigonos Monophthalmos. Lysimachos renamed the city Alexandria after 301 BCE. The city became part of the kingdom of Pergamon and, later, the Roman Empire.

label: Antikyra
description: Antikyra was a port city located east of Kirrha. Pausanias identifies it with the Homeric Kyparissos.

label: Antikythera (island)
description: Aigila (Antikythera) is an island in the Aegean Sea located between Crete and the Peloponnese. BAtlas was confident in also associating the attested name Ogylos with Antikythera, but New Pauly is less confident, listing Cythera as an alternative.

label: Antimachia
description: An ancient settlement on the island of Kos.

label: Antinoopolis
description: An ancient city in Egypt established by Hadrian in A.D. 122 in honor of Antinous. The city stood on the east bank of the Nile, opposite Hermopolis.

label: Antiochia Arabis/Antoninopolis/Tella/Constantia/Maximianopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 B3 Antiochia Arabis/Antoninopolis/Tella/Constantia/Maximianopolis

label: Antiochia ad Cragum
description: Antiochia ad Cragum is a city founded in 170 B.C.

label: Antiochia/Theoupolis
description: A city founded ca. 300 BC by Seleucus I Nicator, a successor of Alexander the Great. Antioch was a great trading center and numbered as one of the four cities of the Syrian tetrapolis. Justinian I renamed the city 'Theoupolis' in the sixth century AD.

label: Antiphellos/Habesos
description: Antiphellos/Habesos was an ancient settlement in Lycia.

label: Antipolis
description: Antipolis (modern Antibes) was founded as a colony from Massilia in the fifth century BC and emerged as a key trading center. In the late first century BC the city was incorporated into the Roman province of Gallia Narbonensis.

label: Antipyrgos
description: An ancient place, cited: None

label: Antissa
description: An ancient settlement on a promontory on the island of Lesbos sometimes referred to as "Ovriokastro". Antissa was destroyed by Roman forces in 166 BCE. The visible archaeological remains derive mostly from a later Genoese fortress.

label: Antium
description: Antium ranked as one of the most important and most powerful centers of Latium and was captured by Rome at the close of the Latin War in the fourth century B.C. Imperial Antium was well known for its number of coastal villas.

label: Antonine Wall
description: A series of fortifications approximately 63 km in length, spanning the breadth of modern day Scotland between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde. The Antonine Wall was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2008.

label: Anvers
description: Antwerp in Belgium began as a small Gallo-Roman vicus.

label: Anxanum
description: City of the Frentani, situated on a hill about 5 miles from the Adriatic Sea, and 8 miles from the mouth of the river Sagrus or Sangro in Italy.

label: Aous (river)
description: A river that flows from the Pindus mountains to the Adriatic Sea; the modern Vjosë or Aoös.

label: Ap(p)enninus M.
description: The Apennine Mountains extend ca. 1,200 km (750 miles) along the length of peninsular Italy.

label: Apa Phoibammon (monastery)
description: The seventh-century monastery of St. Phoibammon was built on the upper terrace of the temple of Hatshepsut at Deir el-Bahri-

label: Aperopia (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 E3 Aperopia Ins.

label: Apesas (mountain)
description: Mount Aphesas, now Mount Phoukas, separated the territory of Kleonai from the Corinthia. It is connected with the myth of the Nemean lion and was the site of an ash altar sacred to Zeus in use from the Geometric period to the fourth century B.C.

label: Aphrodisias
description: Aphrodisias was a Greek city located in Caria. It is notable especially for the state of its archaeological preservation. The site was inscribed on UNESCO's World Heritage List in July 2017.

label: Aphrodision
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 D2 Aphrodision

label: Apollonia
description: An ancient settlement in the modern S. Fratello commune in northern Sicily.

label: Apollonia
description: An ancient road station and settlement along the Via Egnatia in Mygdonia, between Amphipolis and Thessaoniki. Located near the modern municipality of Nea Apollonia in the Thessaloniki province of Greece. Possibly at a location now called Polina (Papazoglou) or a site between Nea Apollonia and Kokkalou excavated by Hatzopoulos in the early 1990s.

label: Apollonia Pontica/Sozopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 E6 Apollonia Pontica/Sozopolis

label: Apollonia/Sozousa
description: Apollonia was an ancient city in the Cyrenaica and a port of Cyrene. The city was one of the five cities of the Libyan Pentapolis in Cyrenaica.

label: Apollonia/Sozousa
description: Apollonia/Sozousa was a coastal town located between Jaffa and Caesarea. It should not be confused with the similarly named ancient site located in Cyrenaica.

label: Apollonopolis Magna
description: The city of Apollonopolis Magna was located on the west bank of the Nile, south of Thebes. As the seat of Horus, Greeks regarded it as a site connected with Apollo. It served as the capital of the second nome of Upper Egypt.

label: Apta Iulia
description: Once the most important town of the Gallic Vulgientes, Romans destroyed the site ca. 125 BC and Iulius Caesar re-founded it as Apta Iulia.

label: Aptera
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Aptera

label: Aquae *Arnemetiae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 F1 Aquae *Arnemetiae

label: Aquae Bormiae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 C3 Aquae Bormiae

label: Aquae Calidae
description: Aquae Calidae was an ancient spa depicted on the Peutinger Map. Modern scholarship associates it with archaeological remains found in modern Vichy (France).

label: Aquae Granni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G2 Aquae Granni

label: Aquae Helveticae
description: Aquae Helveticae was a Roman vicus on the river Limmat.

label: Aquae Mattiacorum
description: Aquae Mattiacorum (modern Wiesbaden) was the capital of the Civitas Mattiacorum.

label: Aquae Neri/*Neriomagus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H2 Aquae Neri/*Neriomagus

label: Aquae Segetae
description: An ancient settlement at modern Sceaux-du-Gâtinais in France (BAtlas 11 C4 Sceaux-du-Gâtinais)

label: Aquae Sextiae
description: Aquae Sextiae (modern Aix-les-Bains) was a vicus of the city of Vienna.

label: Aquae Sulis
description: An ancient Roman thermal spa and site of the Temple of Sulis Minerva.

label: Aquae Terebellicae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D2 Aquae Terebellicae

label: Aquilaria?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 G2 Aquilaria?

label: Aquileia
description: An ancient Roman city initially founded ca. 181/180 B.C., Aquileia is especially important in Late Antiquity and the Middle Ages.

label: Aquilonia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 B2 Aquilonia

label: Aquincum
description: An ancient city of Pannonia, Aquincum is now located within Budapest, Hungary. The ancient site was first settled by the Eravisci and later served as a Roman castrum along the frontier.

label: Aquinum
description: Aquinum was a municipium by the time of Cicero. It was thought to be the place of birth for the satirist Juvenal and the emperor Pescennius Niger.

label: Aquitania (Roman province)
description: A Roman province formed in 27 B.C. by Augustus. According to Strabo, it incorporated the territories of the Aquitani and 14 other peoples whose territories were located between the Garumna and Liger rivers.

label: Arabia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 G5 no. 56 (Arabia)

label: Arabia (late Roman province)
description: The post-Diocletianic province of Arabia according to the Verona List (ca. AD 303-324). It was assigned to the diocese of Oriens.

label: Arabicus Sinus/Erythr(ae)um/Rubrum Mare
description: Arabicus Sinus/Erythr(ae)um/Rubrum Mare (The Red Sea) is an inlet of the Indian Ocean located between Africa and Asia.

label: Aracena
description: A Spanish village located in the north of the province of Huelva that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. The Roman sites of Arucci and Turobriga are located nearby.

label: Arachnaion (mountain)
description: A mountain of the Argolid with a higher western peak (Profitis Ilias, 1199 masl) and a lower eastern peak (Mavrovouni or Arna, 1139 masl). Material from the Mycenaean, Archaic, and Classical periods has been found on the western peak and identified with altars of Zeus and Hera described by Pausanias. Aeschylus mentions its use as a signal station.

label: Arachosiorum Oppidum/Alexandria
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 B3 Arachosiorum Oppidum/Alexandria

label: Arados
description: Arados (modern Arwad, Syria) is located on Ruad Island in the Syrian Sea. The island was first settled by Phoenicians in the second millennium BC.

label: Arae Flaviae
description: Arae Flaviae (Rottweil) was founded as a Roman municipium in A.D. 73. by Cn. Pinarius Clemens.

label: Arae Philaenorum
description: A site located near the bottom of the Great Syrtis which marked the boundary between the territories of Carthage and Cyrene, and later between Tripolitana and Cyrenaica.

label: Aramaua
description: An ancient settlement located in the modern Wadi Ramm (Wadi Rum, Jordan): BAtlas 76 G2 Aramaua

label: Araphen
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 D2 Araphen

label: Araura/Cessero
description: Araura/Cessero was originally a Celtic oppidum and, later, a road station on the Via Domitia.

label: Arausa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C6 Arausa

label: Arba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B5 Arba

label: Arba (island)
description: Rab island in the Adriatic Sea.

label: Arbeia
description: A Roman fort at present-day South Shields.

label: Arbela
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 C4 Arbela

label: Arbela/Arba-ilu
description: An ancient Mesopotamian city located between the two Zab rivers (modern Erbel/Erbil in Iraq).

label: Arbor Felix
description: Arbor Felix was a Roman settlement and fort where the emperor Gratian was based from A.D. 378 until 401.

label: Arbēla
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Arcadia
description: The ancient region of Arcadia comprised the highlands at the center of the Peloponnese.

label: Arch of Constantine
description: The Arch of Constantine at Rome, a triumphal arch dedicated in A.D. 315.

label: Arch of Trajan at Benevento
description: A triumphal arch built in honor of Trajan at Beneventum; it marks the Trajanic extension of the Via Appia.

label: Arcidava
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D4 Arcidava

label: Arco di Trevi
description: An opus quadratum monument with an arched gateway perhaps marking a boundary between the territory of the Equi and the Hernicans.

label: Arcos de la Frontera
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E5 Arcos de la Frontera

label: Ardabil
description: [Ardabil] was an ancient city in Iranian Azerbaijan.

label: Ardashir-Khurra/Gur/[Firuzabad]
description: Ardashir-Khurra/Gur/[Firuzabad] was an ancient Persian city. Alexander of Macedonia destroyed the original settlement of Gōr, which was later revived by Ardashir I, founder of the Sassanid dynasty.

label: Ardea
description: Ardea was an ancient settlement of the Rutuli in Latium.

label: Ardotalia (Zerdotalia)
description: A Roman fort of the first and second centuries A.D. at present day Melandra Castle.

label: Areni
description: The so-called "Areni-1 cave complex" is an archaeological site located near the Areni village in southern Armenia along the Arpa River. The site shows evidence for both ritual and occupational activity in the late Chalcolithic to Early Bronze Age.

label: Areth(o)usa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 C4 Areth(o)usa

label: Argithea
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B2 Argithea

label: Argolis
description: Argolis (also known as 'the Argolid') occupied the eastern part of the Peloponnese; comprising primarily the Argolid peninsula and the coastal region lying to the east of Arcadia, and north of Laconia.

label: Argos
description: Argos was a city of ancient Greece that reached its cultural highpoint under Pheidon in the seventh century BC.

label: Argos Orestikon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 D3 Argos Orestikon

label: Aricia
description: Aricia was an ancient Latin settlement and a member of the Latin League.

label: Ariminum
description: Ariminum (Rimini) is a Roman colony founded on the Adriatic coast in 268 BC.

label: Aris (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C3 Aris fl.

label: Aristanis
description: A Byzantine site in western Sardinia, made important by the location of a bishopric there by Torcotorio in AD 1070; now the modern city of Oristano.

label: Arkesine
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B4 Arkesine

label: Arkonnesos (island)
description: An island, known today as Kara Ada, that lies between ancient Halicarnassus (Bodrum, Turkey) and the Greek island of Kos.

label: Arles Amphitheatre
description: The Arles Roman amphitheater or Arènes d'Arles was built ca. A.D. 90 and could seat over 20,000 spectators.

label: Armenia (Roman province)
description: A Roman province formed under Trajan in 114 CE, but given up by Hadrian in 118 CE.

label: Armenion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D2 Armenion

label: Arnon (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 71 B3 Arnon fl.

label: Aroche
description: A Spanish village located in the north of the province of Huelva, near Portugal, that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Arpadda
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources. It has been identified modern Tell Rifʿat, which is about 25 km north of Aleppo.

label: Arpinum
description: An ancient center that originated as early as the seventh century B.C., which became a civitas sine suffragio in 305 B.C. Arpinum was the birthplace of Caius Marius and Marcus Tullius Cicero.

label: Arquiellos
description: A Spanish village located in the north of the province of Jaén that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X and is today known as Arquillos.

label: Arrabona
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E2 Arrabona

label: Arrapha/Karkha de Beth Seluk
description: The name of the ancient city of Arrapha is first attested in the time of the Neo-Sumerian empire. It later became part of the Akkadian empire. Its location is thought to be that of modern Kirkuk in northeastern Iraq.

label: Arretium
description: Arretium (the Etruscan Aritim) was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae and described by Livy as one of the "Capitae Etruriae". The Romans captured the city in 311 B.C. and it became a station on the via Cassia.

label: Arsia (river)
description: Arsia fl. is a river of Istria that became the boundary between Italy and Illyricum.

label: Arsinoe?/Ammochostos?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 D2 Arsinoe?/Ammochostos?

label: Artace
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Artace

label: Artaxata
description: An ancient city located on and around the hills known today as Khor Virap. This location is near the Armenian village of Lusarat, which is about 8 km south of modern Artashat.

label: Artemision
description: The possible site of the temple of Artemis Proseoa beneath the Ag. Georgios chapel, Artemision (Kourbatsi) Euboea.

label: Artiaca
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E4 Artiaca

label: Arunda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E5 Arunda

label: Arzhan
description: An early Scythian burial mound located in what is now the Tuva Republic of Russia.

label: Arènes de Lutèce
description: The Roman amphitheater of Lutetia (modern Paris).

label: Asa Paulini
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 D2 Asa Paulini

label: Asculum
description: Asculum (modern Ascoli Piceno) was the principal city of the Piceni.

label: Asea
description: Asea was a town of Arcadia, located in the district Maenalia. Lying near the frontier of Laconia, Asea was to be found along the road from Megalopolis to Pallantium and Tegea. Asea participated in the foundation of Megalopolis and many of its inhabitants relocated there.

label: Ashdod/Azotos (Mesogeios)
description: An ancient settlement of the Philistines.

label: Ashqelon/Ascalon
description: Ashqelon/Ascalon was an ancient city in coastal Palestine, located midway between Azotus and Gaza. It became independent in 104 B.C. and remained the only free city in Palestine. Strabo refers to it, while Pliny calls it a free city (oppidum libera).

label: Asia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 E4 no. 20 (Asia)

label: Asia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 M4 Asia

label: Asia (Roman province)
description: The Roman province of Asia, located on the eastern coast of the Aegean Sea. The region was bequeathed to the Roman Republic by Attalus III of Pergamum in 133 BCE. It was divided into seven smaller provinces by Diocletian in the 4th century CE.

label: Asia Minor
description: An ancient region, coincident with a peninsula of the continent of Asia. It is bounded on the south by the Mediterranean Sea, on the west by the Aegean Sea, and on the north by the Black Sea. Today it is part of the territory of the modern country of Turkey.

label: Asinaeus/Coronaeus Sinus
description: Asinaeus/Coronaeus Sinus (the Messenian Gulf).

label: Asine
description: Asine was an ancient Greek city of Argolis.

label: Asisium
description: A Roman settlement built atop an earlier Umbrian one on a western foothill of the Apennines, Asisium received municipal status and was assigned to the Tribus Sergia. Totila destroyed most of the city in A.D. 545.

label: Asopos
description: An ancient settlement located in a protected bay on the west coast of the Parnon peninsula (Peloponnese), now occupied by modern Plitra. The modern town that now carries the name "Asopos" lies some 5 kilometers north of ancient Asopos (modern Plitra).

label: Aspadana/(I)Spahan/Gay/Gabai?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 92 G4 Aspadana/(I)Spahan/Gay/Gabai?

label: Aspendos/Primoupolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 F4 Aspendos/Primoupolis

label: Aspronisi
description: A volcanic island that formed on the southwestern edge of the Santorini archipelago following a major volcanic eruption that occurred ca. 1625 BC.

label: Asse
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E2 Asse

label: Asseros
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D3 Asseros

label: Assorus
description: Assorus was a settlement of the Siculi in interior Sicily that never received a Greek colony.

label: Assos/Apollonia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Assos/Apollonia

label: Assos?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C3 Assos?

label: Astakos (Acarnania)
description: An ancient city of Acarnania, established in the 5th century BCE, the site of Astakos lies approximately 2 kilometers north of the modern town that now bears its name. Ancient Astakos was succeeded in Byzantine times by a settlement named Dragamestos.

label: Asteria (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C5 Asteria Ins.

label: Astigi/Col. Augusta Firma
description: Now the modern Ecija on the Genil river, Astigi was the capital of one of the four conventus of Baetica and became an Augustan colony after 27 B.C.

label: Astron
description: An ancient settlement mentioned by Ptolemy and thought to have been located in the vicinity of the modern coastal town of Paralio Astros. The prominent remains of the castle immediately above the town date to the 17th or 18th century CE and are unrelated to both the ancient settlement and the Aeginetan fortification mentioned by Thucydides that some scholars associate with ancient Astron (RE).

label: Astura (river)
description: The Astura is a river of Latium that flows from the Alban Mount to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

label: Asturica (Augusta)
description: Asturica (Augusta) was the capital of the Conventus Asturum. An Augustan colony was established in 14 B.C.

label: Astypalaia (island)
description: An Aegean island that still carries its ancient name.

label: Astypalaia (settlement)
description: Homonymous ancient settlement on the Aegean island of Astypalaia.

label: Atax (river)
description: The Aude river.

label: Aternum
description: Aternum (modern Pescara) was a settlement at the mouth of the Aternus River.

label: Ateste
description: Ateste was a city of northern Italy, located in the interior of Venetia.

label: Athenae
description: A major Greek city-state and the principal city of Attika. Modern Athens in Greece.

label: Athenaion (fortification)
description: A fortification in Arcadia that was built and destroyed during the Hellenistic period and is mentioned in ancient sources. The site, located on a hill locally called Chemos and near the modern Greek town of Skortsinos, was used in the late medieval period for a castle.

label: Athies
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C3 Athies

label: Athis/Neocaesarea
description: A first- through tenth-century CE settlement located on the right bank of the Euphrates River in Syria's Aleppo Governorate, the site of Dibsi Faraj was excavated in the 1970s ahead of the Tabqa Dam project which eventually inundated the area. The excavations were jointly organized by Dumbarton Oaks and the University of Michigan under Richard Harper, following initial work by the Syrian culture ministry. The site was shown to be a heavily fortified one with Roman and Byzantine phases. It came to be abandoned after ca. 859 CE.

label: Athos (mountain)
description: The Greek "holy mountain" of Athos, which occupies the southeastern tip of the northern peninsula of the Chalkidiki.

label: Athos/Akte (peninsula)
description: A peninsula of Greece, projecting from the larger Chalcidice peninsula in the Aegean Sea.

label: Athribis (Lower Egypt)
description: An ancient city of Lower Egypt located at present-day Tell Atrib to the northeast of Benha on the hill of Kom Sidi Yusuf.

label: Athribis/Triph(i)eion
description: Athribis/Triph(i)eion in Upper Egypt, located outside modern Sohag, was the site of a temple built for the goddess Repyt (Triphis) in the Ptolemaic period.

label: Atina
description: Atina was a Volscian settlement located at the source of the river Melpis. Atina was located on the via Latina between Casinum and Sora.

label: Atina
description: A Lucanian settlement located on the river Tanagro, now Atena Lucana.

label: Attalea
description: Now the modern Antalya, Attalea was established in 150 B.C. on the coast of Pamphylia by Attalus II.

label: Attica
description: Historical region of Greece, centered on the Attic peninsula.

label: Atuatuca
description: Atuatuca (modern Tongeren, Belgium) was also known as Aduatuca Tungrorum or Atuatuca Tongrorum and served as the capital of the Civitas Tungrorum.

label: Au(n)edonnacum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E2 Au(n)edonnacum

label: Augers-en-Brie
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D4 Augers-en-Brie

label: Augila
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 C4 Augila

label: Augusta
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 40 C3 Augusta

label: Augusta (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 F6 Augusta fl.

label: Augusta Praetoria
description: Augusta Praetoria (modern Aosta) was a settlement of the Salassi conquered by Rome in 25 B.C. From 24 B.C. a colony of 3,000 Roman military veterans occupied the city of Augusta Praetoria Salassorum and it became the capital of the province Alpes Graies from 11 B.C.

label: Augusta Suessionum
description: Augusta Suessionum (modern Soissons) was a Gallic site captured by Iulius Caesar and re-established as a Roman city.

label: Augusta Taurinorum
description: Augusta Taurinorum (modern Turin), the settlement of indigenous Celto-Ligurian peoples, was re-settled as a Roman veteran colony in 28 BC.

label: Augusta Vindelicum/Aelia Augusta
description: Augusta Vindelicum/Aelia Augusta (modern Augsburg, Germany) was the capital of Raetia. The city was established in 15 BC by Drusus and Tiberius.

label: Augusta Viromanduorum
description: Augusta Viromanduorum was a Roman settlement that replaced a pre-Roman oppidum of the Viromandui.

label: Augustobona
description: Augustobona Tricassium stood at a key highway hub on the Via Agrippa.

label: Augustodunum
description: Augustodunum was an Augustan foundation located at the point where the river basins of the Loire, Saône, and Rhône rivers meet. Modern Autun.

label: Augustodurum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 F2 Augustodurum

label: Augustomagus
description: Augustomagus (modern Senlis) was located along the road between between Caesaromagus and Suessona.

label: Augustonemetum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I3 Augustonemetum

label: Augustoritum
description: Augustoritum (modern Limoges, France) in Gaul was founded as a Roman city ca. 10 B.C.

label: Aulaiouteichos/Agathopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 E6 Aulaiouteichos/Agathopolis

label: Aulon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B3 Aulon

label: Aulon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 B3 Aulon

label: Aulon/Alonion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 C2 Aulon/Alonion

label: Aurelium Cananefatium/Forum Hadriani
description: Aurelium Cananefatium/Forum Hadriani (modern Voorburg) was the northernmost Roman city on the European continent. It was destroyed ca. AD 270.

label: Aurgi/Orongis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Aurgi/Orongis

label: Auso
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Auso

label: Autessiodurum
description: Autessiodurum was a town of the Senones in Gallia Celtica.

label: Autricum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B4 Autricum

label: Avaricum/Biturigae
description: Avaricum/Biturigae, located at the confluence of Auron and Yèvre river, served as the capital of the Bituriges Cubi.

label: Aveia
description: Aveia was a settlement of the Vestini in the valley of the Aterno river.

label: Avenches Roman amphitheater
description: The Avenches Roman amphitheater.

label: Avennio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 D2 Avennio

label: Aventicum
description: An ancient settlement of the Helvetii, located between Aare and Lake Geneva. Modern Avenches in Switzerland.

label: Aventinus mons
description: One of the seven hills of Rome. Until the reign of the emperor Claudius, the hill lay outside the pomerium of the city.

label: Avernus (lake)
description: A volcanic crater lake located in the Phlegraean Fields, Lake Avernus served a major ritual role for ancient Romans and Greeks as they viewed it as an entrance to Hades.

label: Avila/Obila?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 G4 Avila/Obila?

label: Axima/Forum Claudii Ceutronum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 H2 Axima/Forum Claudii Ceutronum

label: Azoros
description: Azoros was a city belonging to the tripolis of the Perrhaebi.

label: Azuru
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is Azor, Israel.

label: Ašnakkum
description: Town in the Khabur River basin in Northern Syria, now known as Chagar Bazar. First settled in the Neolithic Period, the town appears to have been abandoned during the Early Bronze Age. It was resettled in the Early Dynastic period, becoming an administrative center of the Old Assyrian Empire.

label: Ašḫāni
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is Ḫān Šayḫūn.

label: Babylon
description: An ancient fortified city of the Nile Delta of Egypt, located at Babylon in the area today known as Coptic Cairo.

label: Babylon
description: The ancient city of Babylon began as an Akkadian city-state founded by Amorites in 1894 B.C. The city was also the seat of the Neo-Babylonian Empire from 608 to 539 B.C.

label: Babylonia
description: An ancient region in Mesopotamia.

label: Bac (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 F3 Bac fl.

label: Baclanaza
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 83 B3 Baclanaza

label: Bactra/Zariaspa
description: An ancient city of what is now northern Afghanistan. Bactra/Zariaspa (modern Balkh) was a center of Zoroastrianism.

label: Badajoz
description: The Castillian city of Badajoz was an Islamic foundation under the Muladi nobleman Ibn Marwan who established the city ca. 875. Badajoz was eventually invaded by (and captured by) Christians under Alfonso VI of Castile. Alfonso X established a bishopric and began work on the Cathedral of San Juan Bautista.

label: Baena
description: A Spanish village located in the southeast of the province of Córdoba that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Baeça
description: A Spanish village located in the northeast of the province of Jaén that once belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Baeza.

label: Bagacum
description: Bagacum was an ancient city located in Gallia Belgica and a capital of the Nervii.

label: Bagdata
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 F4 Bagdata

label: Baiae
description: A Roman seaside community on the Bay of Naples that included thermal springs.

label: Baiae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 C3 Baiae

label: Balagrae
description: Balagrae (modern El Beida or Al Bayda, Libya) was an ancient settlement of Cyrenaica and is perhaps best known for its Asclepium.

label: Balaruc-les-Bains
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 B3 Balaruc-les-Bains

label: Balochistan (region)
description: A desert and mountainous region located between the Plateau of Iran and the Indian subcontinent, comprising the modern regions of southeastern Iran (Sistan and Baluchestan province), western Pakistan (Balochistan province), and southern Afghanistan (Nimruz, Helmand and Kandahar provinces). The region's name is derived from the Baloch people, who have inhabited the region since at least the ninth century CE. In antiquity, the southern part of the region, along the coast of the Arabian Sea, was known as Maka in the Achaemenid period and Gedrosia in the Hellenistic period.

label: Balsa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 C4 Balsa

label: Balyra (river)
description: A river of Messenia mentioned in ancient sources. The Balyra corresponds to the modern Mavrozoumena in Greece, in particular to a section stretching from modern Neokhori to a confluence with the Pamisos.

label: Balāwāt
description: Balāwāt is the site of the ancient Assyrian city of Imgur-Enlil. A place from the TAVO Index.

label: Bam
description: An ancient settlement in Iran, whose remains today are known as The Citadel of Bam (arg-e Bam). Located in the modern city of Bam, arg-e Bam was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2004.

label: Banabasi
description: A settlement in south India that has served as a regional administrative and sacred center since at least the beginning of the first millennium CE.

label: Banadedari
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 37 D2 Banadedari

label: Banasa
description: Colonia Iulia Valentia Banasa was one of the three colonies founded by emperor Augustus between 33 and 25 B.C. in Mauretania Tingitana.

label: Bandar-e ʿAbbās
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Barat de Vin Gallo-Roman villa
description: A Gallo-Roman villa dating to the third through fifth centuries. There are well-preserved elements of a bath complex.

label: Bargylia
description: An ancient city of Caria, now known in Turkish as Varvıl. The site is located near the modern Turkish village of Boğaziçi in Muğla province.

label: Baris
description: BAtlas was an ancient settlement in Pisidia.

label: Baris?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 79 D4 Baris?

label: Barium
description: A city of the Peucetii that came under Roman control in the third century BCE.

label: Baron-sur-Odon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 F2 Baron-sur-Odon

label: Barrington Atlas feature labeled 47
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E2 no. 47 (Chavagné)

label: Basilia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 E2 Basilia

label: Basilica of San Clemente al Laterano
description: The eleventh-century Basilica of San Clemente al Laterano is a Roman Catholic basilica dedicated to Clement I. It sits atop a three-tiered series of architectural remains stretching back to the Republican period. The earliest phase is represented by the foundations of a building destroyed by the fire of A.D. 64.

label: Batavi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 G4 Batavi

label: Batavodurum/(Ulpia) Noviomagus
description: An ancient settlement of the Batavi. Modern Nijmegen in the Netherlands.

label: Bauli
description: Bauli (near modern Bacoli) was an ancient settlement of the Campi Phlegraei.

label: Bawtry Roman fort
description: Site of mid- to late-fourth century Roman fort.

label: Bazira
description: The site of an Indo-Greek settlement dating to the reign of King Menander I in the second century BC. This Hellenistic settlement covered some 30 ha at its peak. Earlier settlement phases have been identified, including a village dating ca. 1100-1000 B.C. in addition to Chalcolithic pit structures (ca. 1700 B.C.)

label: Bedriacum
description: Bedriacum was an ancient town of Cisalpine Gaul located between Verona and Cremona that was the site of two battles during the 'Year of the Four Emperors' (A.D. 69).

label: Beer Sheva/Berosaba
description: Tel Be'er Sheva is an archeological site in southern Israel that is believed to be the location of the remains of the biblical town of Beersheba.

label: Begorritus lacus
description: Lake Vegoritida, once known as Lake Ostrovo, is a large natural lake located in western Macedonia, northern Greece.

label: Beirut
description: An ancient Phoenician city, known by various names in antiquity, in what is now Lebanon.

label: Beit Shemesh
description: City 30 km west of Jerusalem inhabited from the Bronze Age until its destruction in 701 CE.

label: Belbina (island)
description: A small island in the Saronic Gulf, some 10 miles from the promontory of Sounion.

label: Belbèze
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G2 Belbèze

label: Bellunum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 E3 Bellunum

label: Ben Shemen Forest
description: Ben Shemen Forest is the largest forest in Central Israel and it contains several archaeological sites, including Bir a Shemi, Tel Gimzo, Tel Hadid, and several Hasmonean-period tombs.

label: Bene Beraq
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F1 Bene Beraq

label: Beneventum/Maleventum
description: Beneventum/Maleventum (modern Benevento) was an ancient city of Campania of Samnite origin.

label: Beni Hasan
description: A Middle Kingdom cemetery known for its rock-cut tombs of local officials.

label: Ber(r)oia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 B3 Ber(r)oia

label: Berenice
description: Berenice was a coastal city of western Cyrenaica, located at modern Benghazi in Libya. Founded in the third century BCE, it replaced the earlier Greek colony of Eusperides, which had been centered a short distance to the northeast. Berenice was named in honor of Berenice of Cyrene, the queen of Ptolemy III Euergetes.

label: Berenice/Berenike
description: An ancient port city on the west coast of the Red Sea in modern Egypt, Berenice/Berenike was founded in 275 BCE by Ptolemy II Philadelphus, who named it after his mother, Berenice I of Egypt.

label: Bergomum
description: Originally a center of the archaic Golasecca culture, Bergomum became a municipium of the tribus Voturia. In 452, Attila captured and razed the city.

label: Bern
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 E3 Bern

label: Beroia
description: The ancient city of Aleppo, located in modern Syria, where extensive elements of Hittite, Hellenistic, Roman, Byzantine, Ayyubid, and Umayyad architecture are incorporated into the urban fabric of the modern city. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

label: Besinum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 Besinum

label: Bethlehem
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Bethlehem

label: Bigorra Castrum
description: An oppidum of the Bigorra enclosed by a rampart.

label: Bilbeis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 F4 Bilbeis

label: Bilitio
description: Bilitio (modern Bellinzona, Switzerland) is an ancient settlement in proximity to both the Po and Ticino rivers. A Roman settlement was established there during the Augustan period.

label: Bingium
description: Bingium was the site of a Roman settlement situated on the right bank of the river Nahe (the ancient Nava) where it joins the Rhine river.

label: Biriciana
description: Biriciana is the site of a Roman fort along the Raetian limes and connected with the ala I Hispanorum Auriana. The archaeological site is located in Weißenburg, Germany.

label: Bisanthe/Rhaidestos
description: Bisanthe/Rhaidestos was a city of Thrace located on the Propontis.

label: Bithynia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 N3 Bithynia

label: Bithynion/Claudiopolis/Hadriana
description: An ancient settlement in Bithynia, modern Bolu in Turkey.

label: Blandiana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 F3 Blandiana

label: Blandona
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C6 Blandona

label: Blatobulgium
description: A Roman fort at present-day Birrens, cited: BAtlas 9 D5 Blatobulgium

label: Blauto/Blavia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E3 Blauto/Blavia

label: Blera
description: Blera was a significant Etruscan settlement in the vicinity of Tarquinii. It lay along the line of the Roman Via Clodia. It received Roman municipal status and was enrolled in the tribus Arnensis. The city flourished in the sixth and fifth centuries BCE.

label: Bobium
description: A small city of northern Italy with Roman origins.

label: Bodhgaya
description: A town in India traditionally identified as the place in which Gautama Buddha attained enlightenment. One of the four main Buddhist pilgrimage sites, it is home to the Mahabodhi Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

label: Boeotia
description: A region of central Greece inhabited since prehistoric times.

label: Bolbitine
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 C2 Bolbitine

label: Bolkar Dağları
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Bolkar Dağları
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Bollendorf
description: Roman villa rustica in Bollendorf

label: Bonna
description: Bonna (modern Bonn, Germany) began as a Roman military outpost in Germania Inferior ca. 11 BC.

label: Borsippa/Burs
description: An ancient city of Sumer, southwest of Babylon, on the east bank of the Euphrates River. Modern Birs Nimrūd in Iraq.

label: Bosa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 48 A2 Bosa

label: Bosana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 E4 Bosana

label: Boscoreale
description: A settled area of Campania, especially well known for the Roman country villas of the first century BCE, which were destroyed by the eruption of Vesuvius in 79 CE.

label: Boscotrecase
description: Located on the southern slopes of Vesuvius, Boscotrecase is a Campanian site destroyed by the eruption of Vesuvius in AD 79. Numerous opulent villas are known in the area by way of archaeological exploration.

label: Bosham Harbour
description: A natural harborage used by Claudian forces during the invasion of Britain and described by Ptolemy.

label: Bosphorus
description: A strait that forms part of the boundary between Europe and Asia.

label: Bostra/Col. Nova Traiana Alexandriana
description: The ancient city of Bostra (modern Busra in Syria), where extensive ancient Nabataean, Roman, Byzantine and Umayyad structures still visible. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

label: Botrys
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 A5 Botrys

label: Botti(ai)a/Emathia
description: A district surrounding Pella in Macedonia. Its extent seems to have shifted over time.

label: Boukolonpolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 A4 Boukolonpolis

label: Bouthroton
description: Modern Butrint (Butrinti) in Albania, ancient Bouthroton was an ancient Greek and later Roman city located in Epirus. The city became an important bishopric by the sixth century. The site was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1992 because of its archaeological remains, which date from prehistoric times down through the late Middle Ages.

label: Bracara Augusta
description: With settlement from the Neolithic onwards, Bracara Augusta was established as a civitas in 20 B.C. In the third century A.D., Diocletian advanced the settlement to the capital of the administrative area known as Conventus Bracarensis, forming part of the Roman province of Gallaecia.

label: Brattia (island)
description: Brattia Ins. (Brač, Croatia).

label: Brav(o)niacum
description: A Roman fort at present-day Kirkby Thore.

label: Bremenium
description: A Roman fort at present-day High Rochester.

label: Brigantium
description: Brigantium (modern Bregenz) was a Celtic settlement from at least the fifth century B.C. and came under Roman control in the first century B.C.

label: Brigetio
description: Brigetio was a legionary camp, cannabae, and municipium along the Pannonian limes.

label: Britannia (province)
description: A province of the Roman Empire at the Death of Trajan (117 CE).

label: Briva (Curretia)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G3 Briva (Curretia)

label: Brivas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 A3 Brivas

label: Brixia
description: An ancient settlement. Modern Brescia in Italy.

label: Brocavum
description: A Roman fort at modern Brougham in the United Kingdom (sometimes called Brougham Castle Roman Fort).

label: Brundisium/Brentesion
description: A Greek and Roman port, terminus of the Via Appia.

label: Bulla Regia
description: A center for Numidian royalty, Bulla Regia first became an oppidum liberum in the reign of Augustus and then a colony under Hadrian. The site, which boasts significant archaeological remains, lies in modern Tunisia, about 5km north of the modern city of Jendouba. The site was reportedly known in the 19th century as Hammam-Darradji. Today, a small modern settlement named Aïn Babouch abuts the site (not to be confused with Babouch, which lies further north along the border with Algeria).

label: Burdigala
description: Burdigala (modern Bordeaux) was a Celtic center of the Bituriges Vivisci. The Romans lost a battle at the site in 107 BC, with consul Lucius Cassius Longinus being killed in the action. Rome eventually controlled the area ca. 60 BC.

label: Burgos
description: A Spanish city located in the north of Spain that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Burgus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E3 Burgus

label: Burnum
description: From ca. 6 B.C. Burnum was the site of a Roman legionary camp (Legio XI; Legio XI Claudia Pia Fidelis - Legio IIII Flavia Felix and Legio VIII Augusta), as well as an auxiliary camp. By the Hadrianic period it had become the civil settlement of Municipium Burnistarum.

label: Byblos
description: Occupied since the Neolithic period, historical Byblos was originally a major Punic center called Gebal.

label: Byrsa
description: Walled citadel in Carthage built in the early first millennium BCE. The site was destroyed during the Third Punic War in 146 BCE by the forces of Scipio Aemilianus. The hill became the site of the city's forum in the Roman period.

label: Byzantium
description: An ancient Greek settlement at the southern end of the Bosphorus, where modern-day Istanbul, Turkey, now stands. It flourished and grew throughout the Greek and Roman periods. The city was renamed Constantinopolis (q.v..) and much expanded by the fourth-century emperor, Constantine, and his successors.

label: Būr Saʿīd
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Cabellio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 E2 Cabellio

label: Cabilonnum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 B3 Cabilonnum

label: Caecina (river)
description: The Cecina river flows through Etruria and empties into the Tyrrhenian Sea near Vada Volaterrana. The river course passed through the ancient territory of the Etruscan city of Volterra.

label: Caelius Mons
description: The Caelian Hill in Rome.

label: Caere
description: Caere (also known as Cisra or Cerveteri) was a major Etruscan polis located ca. 50 km north-northwest of Rome in southern Etruria.

label: Caerphilly Roman fort
description: Site of a late first century CE Roman auxiliary fort between Cardiff and Gelligaer.

label: Caesarobriga
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A2 Caesarobriga

label: Caesarodunum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F1 Caesarodunum

label: Caesaromagus
description: Caesaromagus was the civitas capital of the Bellovaci.

label: Caesena
description: An Umbrian and Etruscan city on the Savio River that passed into Roman control in the third century B.C.

label: Caetobriga
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B3 Caetobriga

label: Caiatia
description: A Samnite town that eventually became a Roman municipium of the tribus Falerna ca. 89 B.C.

label: Caicus (river)
description: The modern Bakırçay river, a river of southwest Asia Minor that flows from the Temnos mountains to the Elaitic Gulf.

label: Caieta
description: Caieta was a town of ancient Latium located on the Tyrrhenian Sea coast between Tarracina and Formiae.

label: Caino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F1 Caino

label: Calacte
description: An ancient Sicilian city located on the northern coast of the island, founded by Ducetius in 446 B.C.

label: Calagorris
description: Calagurris Convenarum (modern Saint-Martory, Haute-Garonne, France)

label: Calama
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 G4 Calama

label: Cale
description: Cale was the site of an ancient city located at the mouth of the Durius fl. The Roman colony Portus Cale was established there in 136 BC.

label: Callatis
description: A Greek colony and port on the west coast of the Black Sea, modern Mangalia in Romania.

label: Calpe (mountain)
description: The Rock of Gibraltar.

label: Camaracum
description: Camaracum was the capital of the civitas of the Nervii.

label: Camarina
description: Camarina was founded by Syracuse in 599 B.C., but subsequently destroyed in 552 B.C. The city was re-founded by Gela in 461 B.C. Carthage razed the site in 405 B.C., but Timoleon restored it in 339 B.C. From the late third century B.C. the town fell under Roman administration.

label: Cambodunum (Raetia)
description: Cambodunum was a Celtic settlement of Raetia. A Roman presence began under Tiberius (first century AD) when a Roman garrison was stationed at the site.

label: Camp de César
description: The place known as "Camp de César" or "Caesar's Camp" is an ancient town covering some 18 ha that was occupied from the fifth century BCE until Late Antiquity. Built fortifications augment the site's natural defensibility.

label: Campania
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 J3 Campania

label: Campi Phlegraei
description: The Campi Phlegraei (Phlegraean Fields) is a large caldera (13 km wide) in the Bay of Naples region of Italy. In total, the the area comprises 24 craters, although a good portion of the caldera now lies under water. The area was important in Greek and Roman times; the Greeks established their first mainland colony at Cumae within the Campi Phlegraei.

label: Campus Martius
description: The Campus Martius or "field of Mars" is the name given to the level ground between the slopes of the Capitoline, the Quirinal, and Pincian hills, and the Tiber river.

label: Canopus
description: An ancient Egyptian city of the Nile river delta. Canopus was located in the seventh nome (Menelaites) on the western bank at the mouth of the westernmost branch of the Nile.

label: Cantilia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I2 Cantilia

label: Canéjan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E4 Canéjan

label: Capena
description: An ancient urban center in Faliscan territory adjacent to Etruria, Capena was sacked by the Romans in 390 BC.

label: Capidava
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 F4 Capidava

label: Capitium
description: Capitium was an ancient settlement in the Monti Nebrodi of Sicily.
