label: Capitolinus Mons
description: The smallest of Rome's hills and one of its most important, the Capitoline Hill served as the citadel (arx) of the city and as the site of its poliadic temple.

label: Capitolium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Capitolium

label: Cappadocia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 P4 Cappadocia

label: Capreae
description: Settlement on the island of Capreae.

label: Capreae (island)
description: An island of the Bay of Naples off the Sorrentine Peninsula that has, since the time of the Roman Republic, been a popular seaside resort area. The emperor Tiberius maintained twelve villas on the island.

label: Capsa (Iustiniana)
description: Capsa (Iustiniana) was an ancient city of Byzacium in north Africa.

label: Capua
description: An important ancient city of Campania with Villanovan and Etruscan origins.

label: Caracoticum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 G2 Caracoticum

label: Caralis
description: A city with its origins in a Phoenician settlement of the seventh century BC, Caralis comes under Roman control in 238 BC during the Punic Wars. Florus refers to it as urbs urbinum, or capital of Sardinia

label: Carbula
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E4 Carbula

label: Carcas(s)o/Col. Iulia
description: A fortified Roman and Medieval site with occupation beginning from the fourth millennium B.C.

label: Carmel (mountain)
description: A coastal mountain range in northern Israel.

label: Carmo
description: Carmo was a town in Hispania Ulterior.

label: Carnuntum
description: A Roman army camp on the Danube River in Noricum; after the first century CE Carnuntum served as the capital of Upper Pannonia.

label: Carpentorate/*Forum Neronis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 E1 Carpentorate/*Forum Neronis

label: Carsulae
description: An ancient settlement originating the late fourth or third centuries BC and lying along the route of the Roman Via Flaminia.

label: Cartana/Karnasa/Tetrogonis
description: The site of Cartana/Karnasa/Tetrogonis remains unlocated, although scholars have advanced various theories as to its location.

label: Carteia/Calpe/Karpessos
description: A Phoenician and Roman town in Spain located on the Bay of Gibraltar. The site played a strategic role in the Punic Wars, and was given the rights of a Latin colony in 171 BC.

label: Carthago
description: The ancient city of Carthage, located in modern Tunis (Tunisia). Carthage engaged the Roman state in a series of wars conventionally referred to as the Punic Wars by scholars.

label: Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia
description: Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia (modern Cartagena, Spain) was originally an indigenous settlement that was subsequently refounded first as a Punic site Qart Hadasht ("New City") in 228 BC and later as a Roman city.

label: Cas(s)inomagus
description: Located in Transalpine Gaul, Cas(s)inomagus is included on the Peutinger Table. It lies along the road from Mediolanum Santonum (Saintes) to Ausritum, Augustoritum (Lirnmoes), some 25.5 Roman miles from Limoges.

label: Casinum
description: A Volscian hilltop settlement that became a Roman colony in 312 B.C.

label: Casius Mons
description: Mount Kasion or Kasion Oros as described by Herodotus.

label: Castellum Menapiorum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C2 Castellum Menapiorum

label: Castellum Tingitanum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 30 B4 Castellum Tingitanum

label: Castelnau-Montratier
description: A Gallo-Roman site located in the Barguelonne valley that covers some 4,000 square meters. Excavation (1962-1964) suggested the site was likely a rural sanctuary that included a theater and baths.

label: Castle of Bominaco
description: A castle at Bominaco in Italy that originally dates to the twelfth century.

label: Castra Mefaa
description: A site that originated as a Roman castrum and developed into a town from the fifth century onward. Archaeological remains date from the Roman, Byzantine, and Early Muslim periods.

label: Castro del Río
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A4 Castro del Río

label: Castronuovo di Sicilia
description: A modern location in Sicily that has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Krastos.

label: Castrum Divionense
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 C2 Castrum Divionense

label: Castrum Minervae/Athenaion/Limen Aphrodites
description: An ancient settlement of the Sallentini in Apulia. Legendary history held that this was the spot where Aeneas first landed in Italy, thus the assignation 'Limen Aphrodites' or 'Portus Veneris'.

label: Castrum Rauracense
description: A Late Roman fortress located on the southern bank of the Rhine adjacent to Augusta Raurica.

label: Castulo
description: An Ibero-Roman settlement of Baetica that was inhabited beginning in the Neolithic period. It is noted for the silver mines of the Sierra Morena.

label: Cataracta Quinta
description: The Fifth Cataract of the Nile river is located near the confluence of the Nile and Atbarah Rivers.

label: Cataractonium
description: The remains of a Roman fort and settlement located at Catterick, North Yorkshire.

label: Cauca
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 G3 Cauca

label: Caudium
description: A city of Samnium located between Capua and Beneventum. In 321 B.C. the Samnites under C. Pontius encamped there before defeating the Romans at the battle of the Caudine Forks.

label: Cauterets
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E3 Cauterets

label: Caztalliella
description: Now modern Cazalilla, Caztalliella was a Spanish village located in the north of the province of Jaén that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Celeia
description: Celeia was an important settlement in Noricum.

label: Cemenelum
description: An oppidum that was the capital of the Vediantian Ligures; later became a municipium of the tribus Claudia.

label: Cenabum
description: Cenabum was an oppidum of the Carnutes tribe.

label: Centum Cellae
description: Centum Cellae (modern Civitavecchia) was an ancient coastal settlement in Tyrrhenian Etruria. The emperor Trajan rebuilt the harbor at the site in 106/7 and Pliny the Younger mentions its name, Centum Cellae. Saracens destroyed the city in A.D. 812.

label: Centuripae
description: A city of the indigenous Sikels, Centuripae allied itself with Athens during the expedition against Syracuse.

label: Cephallania (island)
description: The largest of the Ionian islands.

label: Cephaloedium
description: An city founded on an imposing promontory on the northern coast of Sicily.

label: Cercina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 H3 Cercina

label: Cervaria
description: A promontory on the Mediterranean coast of modern France, at the Spanish border. It was described by Pomponius Mela as marking "the boundary of Gallia" in Roman times. Modern Cap Cerbère.

label: Cetium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 I4 Cetium

label: Cetona
description: The present town of Cetona grew around the rocca (fortress) of the tenth century A.D., although occupation at the site reaches back to the Paleolithic when a number of caves show evidence for human activity. There are also indications of an Etruscan phase of occupation.

label: Ceuclum
description: Vicus on the Meuse river along the road from Noviomagus to Atua(tu)ca.

label: Chaeronea
description: An ancient settlement of Boeotia, Chaeronea was a subject of Orchomenus and a member of the Boeotian League. From the late fifth century BC, Chaeronea belonged to one of the 11 Boeotian districts.

label: Chalcedon
description: Chalcedon was an ancient maritime city of Bithynia.

label: Chalcis
description: Chalkis was a settlement on Euboea, inhabited from the sub-Neolithic period, which played an important role in Greek colonisation of the Mediterranean in the 8th century BC. It was part of the Delian League in the 5th century BC and the Second Athenian Sea League in the 4th century BC. In Hellenistic times it was one of the three 'fetters of Greece' used by Macedon to control Greece. It came under Roman control in 197 BC.

label: Chalcis ad Belum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 C2 Chalcis ad Belum

label: Chalia
description: Theopompus mentions Chalia as a town of Boeotia. It is also attested epigraphically and may have been a member of the Boeotian league. Fossey locates the city in the vicinity of the church of Agios Minas in modern Drosia. Archaeological finds in the area indicate human activity from as early as the Bronze Age.

label: Chalke Island
description: An island west of Rhodes (modern Halki).

label: Chalkedon (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 53 B3 Chalkedon fl.

label: Characmoba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 71 B3 Characmoba

label: Charadros (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B1 Charadros fl.

label: Chemery
description: Chemery (modern Chémery) was the site of an important Gallo-Roman productive center for sigillate pottery. It was, in fact, the principal pottery of Saturninus and Satto.

label: Chersis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 A2 Chersis

label: Chersis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 D1 Chersis

label: Chersonesos Pr.
description: The promontory now known as Capo Teulada.

label: Chillon
description: A Spanish village located in the south of the province of Ciudad Real that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today knowh as Chillón.

label: Chios (island)
description: Chios is the fifth largest of the Greek islands.

label: Chios (settlement)
description: The principal ancient city on the Aegean island of Chios.

label: Chrysea (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 E3 Chrysea Ins.

label: Chrysopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 53 B2 Chrysopolis

label: Chyt(h)roi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C2 Chyt(h)roi

label: Château-Porcien
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E3 Château-Porcien

label: Châteaubleau
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D4 Châteaubleau

label: Cibalae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F4 Cibalae

label: Cilicia (Roman province)
description: A Roman province, first established in 102 BCE coincident with the region of the same name on the southern coast of Asia Minor, which by Roman times at least was said to be bounded by the Taurus mountains to the north, the river Melas in the west, and the Amanus mountains in the east.

label: Ciliza/Urmagiganti
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 E3 Ciliza/Urmagiganti

label: Cilurnum
description: Cilurnum is the site of a fort dating to A.D. 123 on Hadrian's Wall that guarded a military bridge along the Roman road. It is now known as Chester's Roman Fort.

label: Ciminius (lake)
description: A caldera lake of northern Latium.

label: Circesium/Qarquza/Habora/Phaliga?
description: A Roman limes fortress located in Mesopotamia, along the Khabur river, near the point where it flows into the Euphrates.

label: Cirta/Constantina
description: The capital city of the ancient Berber Kingdom of Numidia.

label: Civitas Namnetum/Kondeouinkon?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 D1 Civitas Namnetum/Kondeouinkon?

label: Classis
description: A military port near Ravenna, established by Octavian by 12 B.C. as headquarters for the Roman fleet in the Adriatic Sea.

label: Clysma
description: Clysma was an ancient port city at the northern end of the Gulf of Suez (modern al‑Qulzum in the city of Suez).

label: Cnidus (Tekir)
description: An ancient settlement located at Tekir on the western tip of the modern Datça peninsula in Turkey (ancient Knidia), which extends from the southwest corner of Asia Minor. In the later fourth century BCE, it grew markedly, succeeding the site at Burgaz as the political center of the peninsula and attracting the name Cnidus to itself. It is often referred to as "New Cnidus" in recognition of this change.

label: Col. Aquae Sextiae
description: Col. Aquae Sextiae (modern Aix-en-Provence) was founded by Caius Sextius Calvinus, who placed the colony on the territory of the indigenous confederation of the Salluvii in 122 B.C.

label: Col. Arausio
description: Founded as Colonia Iulia Firma Secundanorum Arausio in 35 B.C.

label: Col. Augusta Raurica
description: Col. Augusta Raurica (modern Augst) was a Roman colony on the south bank of the Rhine established by Iulius Caesar and L. Munatius Plancus in 44 B.C.

label: Col. Augusta Treverorum
description: The chief ancient city (civitas) of the Treveri. Modern Trier in Germany.

label: Col. Baeterrae
description: Colonia Julia Baeterrae Septimanorum is located where the Via Herculia crosses the Orb river. It is now modern Béziers, France. The site has been inhabited at least since 750-650 B.C.

label: Col. Barcino
description: Colonia Iulia Augusta Paterna Faventia Barcino (Barcelona) was a Roman settlement in Tarraconensis founded by Augustus.

label: Col. Caesaraugusta
description: Colonia Caesaraugusta (present-day Zaragoza, Spain) was established as a planned Roman colony of the Augustan period (ca. 14 BCE). Military veterans of the Cantabrian wars were settled there.

label: Col. Camulodunum
description: Col. Camulodunum (Colchester) was the pre-Roman capital of the Trinovantes; it received a Roman city after the annexation of Britannia.

label: Col. Dea Vocontiorum
description: An Augustan colony in Gallia Narbonensis located in the valley of the Drôme river; an important cultic center of the Vocontii.

label: Col. Forum Iulii
description: Col. Forum Iulii (modern Fréjus) was a Roman military colony, most likely founded by Iulius Caesar, that served as a major naval base.

label: Col. Glevum
description: Site of a Roman legionary fortress (ca. 67 A.D.) and later colonia (founded ca. 97-98 A.D.) at modern day Gloucester.

label: Col. Iulia Equestris/Noviodunum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 D3 Col. Iulia Equestris/Noviodunum

label: Col. Lugdunum
description: Lugdunum (modern Lyon in France) was a Roman military colony from 43 B.C. and a major center in Gaul. Marcus Agrippa was involved in its expansion and two Roman emperors, Claudius and Caracalla, were born there.

label: Col. Narbo Martius
description: Col. Narbo Martius (modern Narbonne) was established in Gaul in 118 B.C. as a Roman colony.

label: Col. Ulpia Traiana/Tricensimae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G1 Col. Ulpia Traiana/Tricensimae

label: Col. Valentia
description: A settlement of the Segovellauni in Gallia Narbonensis.

label: Col. Vienna
description: A settlement of the Allobroges in Gallia Narbonensis that became a Roman colony in 47 BC.

label: Colmier-le-Bas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 B2 Colmier-le-Bas

label: Combley Roman villa
description: The site of a Romano-British villa of the winged corridor type, probably late 3rd century CE in date.

label: Compitum
description: A multi-period sanctuary near Anagnia.

label: Complutum
description: Complutum (modern Alcalá de Henares in Spain) was an ancient oppidum founded in the first century CE and largely re-fashioned in the third century.

label: Comum
description: Comum (modern Como) was a key city of regio XI of ancient Italy. The Celtic site received a Roman colony (Novum Comum) under Iulius Caesar in the first century BC.

label: Condacum?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E1 Condacum?

label: Condate
description: A Roman road station, attested in ancient sources. It is probably to be localized in the modern commune of Cognac (Charente)

label: Condate Redonum
description: The primary center of the Redones tribe. Modern Rennes in France.

label: Condercum
description: A fort and associated vicus on Hadrian's Wall.

label: Confluentes
description: Confluentes (Koblenz) was a Roman military outpost established by Drusus ca. 8 BC.

label: Congavata
description: A Roman fort on Hadrian's Wall, cited: BAtlas 9 D6 ‘Congavata’

label: Consentia
description: The capital city of the ancient Bruttii in Calabria.

label: Consoranni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G2 Consoranni

label: Constantia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 B2 Constantia

label: Constantinopolis
description: Capital city of the Eastern Roman Empire, the Latin, and the Ottoman Empires founded by Constantine I in AD 330.

label: Coptos
description: An ancient settlement on the Nile river (modern Quft/Qift in Egypt) that flourished from pre-dynastic times through late antiquity.

label: Cora
description: A Latin center in the Monti Lepini that was already a Roman municipium by 211 B.C.

label: Corcoras (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C4 Corcoras fl.

label: Corcyra (island)
description: An island located in the Ionian Sea. Modern-day Corfu, Greece.

label: Corcyra (settlement)
description: The eponymous settlement of the island of Corcyra (modern Korfu).

label: Cordes-Tolosannes
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G2 no. 34 (Cordes-Tolosannes)

label: Corduba/Col. Patricia
description: Corduba/Col. Patricia (modern Córdoba, Andalusia) is an ancient site where prehistoric, Punic, Roman, Visigothic, and Muslim phases of occupation are known. The city's historic center was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1984.

label: Corfinium
description: Corfinium was the principal city of the Paeligni in the valley of the Aternus river. The site becomes the capital of the breakaway Italic groups that oppose Rome during the Social War.

label: Coriallum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 E2 Coriallum

label: Corinth Canal
description: The Corinth Canal cuts across the Isthmus of Corinth, connecting the Gulf of Corinth to the Saronic Gulf and the Aegean Sea. Several abortive attempts in antiquity were made at creating the canal, although its final (and functional) realization occurred in modernity.

label: Corinthiacus Sinus
description: The Gulf of Corinth.

label: Corinthus/Korinthos
description: The ancient Greek and Roman city of Corinth, located in the Peloponnese, Greece. Also known today as Archaia Korinthos and not to be confused with the nearby modern town.

label: Coriovallum
description: Coriovallum (modern Heerlen, The Netherlands) was a Roman military settlement along the frontier (limes) in Germania Inferior.

label: Cornacum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 G4 Cornacum

label: Corniclanum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 B3 Corniclanum

label: Corsica/Kyrnos (island)
description: The island of Corsica, in the Mediterranean Sea.

label: Cortona
description: An Umbrian city that, under Etruscan influence, expanded and came to be called 'Curtun'. Later it became the Roman colony of Cortino.

label: Cortoriacum
description: A vicus of the civitas Menapiorum.

label: Cosedia/Constantia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 E2 Cosedia/Constantia

label: Coulanges
description: A site with evidence for large-scale pottery production.

label: Cremona
description: Cremona is a city of Cisalpine Gaul located on the Po river. The Romans established a colony of 6,000 settlers there after 225 B.C. Cremona was the first Latin colony placed north of the Po river.

label: Creta
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 L4 Creta

label: Creta (island)
description: The island of Crete is the largest of the Greek islands and the fifth-largest island in the Mediterranean Sea.

label: Croto(n)
description: An Achaean colony in Magna Graecia established in 710 BC by the oikist Myscellus from the city of Rhypes in the Peloponnese.

label: Ctesiphon
description: An imperial capital of the Arsacid and Sasanian empires, this large ancient city originated as early as the third century BCE and declined in the eighth century CE. It was located on the left bank of the Tigris River 35 km south of what would later become modern Baghdad in Iraq. It was part of a complex network of settlements in the area, among which Seleucia (modern Vēh Ardašīr) also featured prominently. It was attacked, and sometimes occupied, by Roman forces multiple times.

label: Cuenca
description: The site of Cuenca, Spain, was first occupied by Muslim Arabs in the eighth century who fortified a location between the Júcar and Huécar rivers that became known as Ḳūnka. The fort was ceded by means of treaty to Alfonso VI of León and Castile in 1080. By the thirteenth century, Cuenca was part of the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Cuicul
description: A Berbero-Roman town of North Africa (modern Djémila in Algeria). Sometimes labeled on maps and in travel information as "Curculum".

label: Cularo/Gratianopolis
description: Cularo/Gratianopolis was a city of Gallia Narbonensis in the territory of the Allobroges on the Isère River.

label: Cumae/Kyme (Campanian)
description: An ancient settlement of Campania, Cumae was the first Greek colony established on the Italian mainland in the eighth century BC.

label: Cunetio
description: Cunetio was a Roman town located on the River Kennet adjacent to the modern town of Mildenhall, Wiltshire. It was occupied from the second century to the early fifth century A.D. Its fortification wall seems to have been built in late third to earth fourth century. The archaeological site was first identified in 1940 via aerial photography.

label: Cupra Montana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Cupra Montana

label: Cures
description: Cures (also Cures Sabini) was a Sabine city in the Tiber River valley along the Via Salaria. The Romans conquered Cures in 290 B.C. under M'. Curius Dentatus and granted it status as a municipium in the tribus Sergia.

label: Curia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 B3 Curia

label: Curia Iulia
description: Construction of the Curia Julia was begun by Julius Caesar and completed by Augustus in 29 BCE. It replaced the former senate house, the Curia Hostilia.

label: Curicta (island)
description: A large island in the Adriatic Sea.

label: Cyclades Islands
description: An island group in the Aegean Sea composed of over 200 islands.

label: Cydnus (river)
description: A river of ancient Cilicia.

label: Cymiza/*Balaleisa/‘Balouos’
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 E2 Cymiza/*Balaleisa/‘Balouos’

label: Cyprus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 N4 Cyprus

label: Cyprus (Roman province)
description: The Roman province.

label: Cyprus (island)
description: Cyprus is the third largest island in the Mediterranean Sea.

label: Cyrene
description: An ancient Greek city founded in eastern Libya ca. 630 B.C., Cyrene later became part of the Roman Empire (ca. 74 B.C.). The site was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1982.

label: Cythera (island)
description: An Aegean island located off the southeastern peninsula of the Peloponnese. It appears frequently in Greek and Roman literature beginning with Homer.

label: Cyzicus
description: An ancient city of Mysia in Anatolia, perhaps founded by the Corinthians in 756 BC and then again by the Milesians ca. 675 BC. Its advantageous position in the Propontis made it a major commercial centre. In the 5th century BC it was part of the Delian League and in the Hellenistic Age it was close to the Attalid kings. In the Imperial period, it became an assize centre (conventus) of the province of Asia.

label: D(o)ura/Europos
description: An ancient settlement on the Euphrates river in modern Syria.

label: Dacia
description: Dacia was a region inhabited by the Dacians or Getae. A Dacian kingdom existed from ca. the early first century BC until the Roman conquest under Trajan in AD 106.

label: Dacia (province)
description: A province of the Roman Empire at the death of Trajan (117 CE).

label: Dacia Inferior (province)
description: A province of the Roman Empire, created under the emperor Hadrian.

label: Dalmatia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 K3 Dalmatia

label: Dalmatia (province)
description: A province of the Roman Empire at the death of Trajan (117 CE).

label: Dalmatia (region)
description: Dalmatia is an historical region of present-day Croatia, located to the east of the Adriatic Sea.

label: Damascus
description: The ancient city of Damascus, located in modern Syria, with some 125 monuments dating back to the Roman period. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

label: Dan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 C3 Dan

label: Dani
description: The Dani were a North Germanic tribe inhabiting parts of southern Scandinavia.

label: Daphnos (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 C3 Daphnos fl.

label: Dara/Anastasioupolis
description: Dara/Anastasioupolis was a fortified Roman city of northern Mesopotamia located on the border with the Sassanid Empire.

label: Darioritum
description: The primary city of the Veneti in Gallia Lugdunensis (modern Vannes).

label: Darnis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 D1 Darnis

label: Daskalio
description: An island of the Cyclades that is now uninhabited. The Cambridge Keros Project identified a large Bronze Age settlement on the island.

label: Daskyleion
description: Daskyleion (modern Hisartepe at Ergili in Turkey) was the capital of the Persian satrapy of Phrygia from the sixth century BC until the conquests of Alexander the Great.

label: Daskylitis Limne
description: Also called "Aphnitis Limne" in antiquity, according to Strabo. Modern Lake Kuş/Lake Manyas in Turkey.

label: Daulis
description: Daulis was an ancient city of eastern Phocis.

label: Dazimon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 B4 Dazimon

label: Decem Pagi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 G4 Decem Pagi

label: Decetia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I2 Decetia

label: Dedan/al-'Ula
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 83 C5 Dedan/al-'Ula

label: Deir el-Medina
description: The workers' village of the artisans who worked on the New Kingdom tombs in the Valley of the Kings.

label: Dekeleia
description: Dekeleia was an inland deme of the tribe Hippothontis, in Attica, located 120 stades from Athens. In myth, Dekeleia ceded its autonomy under Theseus to form the city-state of Athens.

label: Delos (island)
description: The Aegean island of Delos, part of the Cyclades island group.

label: Delos (settlement)
description: The ancient settlement of Delos, located on the Aegean island of the same name.

label: Delphi
description: The ancient panhellenic sanctuary of Delphi in Greece, seat of the oracle of Apollo.

label: Demetrias (Magnesian)
description: This ancient city, located near modern Volos in Thessaly, was founded by Demetrios Poliorketes in the third century BCE and abandoned in the 6th century CE. Continuous human activity in the area can be traced back at least as early as the Neolithic.

label: Dertona
description: A city founded in the second century B.C. at the junction of the Via Postumia and Via Aemilia Scauri which merged to become the Via Julia Augusta.

label: Deru/Beth Daraya/[Badra]
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 92 A3 Deru/Beth Daraya/[Badra]

label: Derventio
description: A Roman fort at present-day Papcastle, cited: BAtlas 9 D6 Derventio

label: Derventum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H2 Derventum

label: Deva
description: Deva or Deva Victrix (modern Chester) was a legionary base in Britannia. It was originally founded by the Legio II Adiutrix in the AD 70s and completed by the Legio XX Valeria Victrix.

label: Dezful/[Qantara al-Rum]
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 92 D4 Dezful/[Qantara al-Rum]

label: Dia/Diospolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 B2 Dia/Diospolis

label: Diana Veteranorum
description: Diana Veteranorum was a vicus in Numidia founded for veterans of Legio III Augusta. It became a municipium in A.D. 162.

label: Dianium/Hemeroskopeion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 F3 Dianium/Hemeroskopeion

label: Didyma/Branchidai/Ioustinianopolis
description: The ancient sanctuary of Apollo near Miletos (modern Didim, Turkey).

label: Didyme (island)
description: One of the Aeolian Islands with Greek occupation from the fourth century B.C.

label: Digentia (river)
description: A stream in the ager Sabinus.

label: Dikaiarcheia/Puteoli
description: A maritime city of Campania situated on the Phlegrean Peninsula. The settlement started as a Greek colony and became a Roman colony under the name Puteoli in 194 B.C.

label: Diluntum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E6 Diluntum

label: Dinia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 B1 Dinia

label: Dinogetia
description: Dinogetia, a Roman castrum located in the province of Moesia.

label: Diocaesarea
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 D3 Diocaesarea

label: Diomedeae Islands
description: An Adriatic archipelago north of Mons Garganus. Modern Isole Tremiti.

label: Dion
description: Dion was a settlement of Pieria located on the border between Macedonia and Thessaly. It was held, traditionally, as the place of Orpheus' death and burial. In the Roman Imperial period, it became a Roman colonia. The adjacent modern village, now known as Dion, is sometimes also referenced by its earlier modern name Malathria.

label: Dionysiades (islands)
description: An island grouping off the north coast of Crete, opposite Siteia. Known today also as the Yanisades Islands.

label: Dionysias
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 C2 Dionysias

label: Diospolis Magna/Thebai
description: Diospolis Magna/Thebai was known in ancient Egypt as Waset, "City of the Sceptre". The site was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

label: Diospolis Mikra
description: The capital of the seventh Nome of Upper Egypt, located on the west bank of the Nile.

label: Diria?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 F3 Diria?

label: Dispilio
description: Dispilio is an archaeological site with the remains of a Neolithic lake-side settlement near the modern village of Dispilio on Lake Orestiada.

label: Divodurum/Mettis
description: Divodurum/Mettis was a Celtic capital oppidum of the Mediomatrici tribe and was captured by Iulius Caesar in 52 BC.

label: Divona
description: Divona (Cahors) was the capital of the civitas of the Cadurci throughout the Roman period. It takes its name from a sacred spring (likely the Fontaine des Chartreux) and a ford on the Lot river.

label: Dodona (Epirus)
description: An ancient site of northwestern Epirus, Dodona was home to one of the most ancient oracular traditions of the Hellenic world.

label: Dohuk
description: Dohuk is the capital of Dohuk Governorate in Iraqi Kurdistan. The modern city is located around the ancient site; the University of Dohuk campus is situated on top of the ruins of the ancient city (name not known).

label: Doliche
description: An ancient city of Asia Minor (modern Dülük in Turkey).

label: Doliche
description: An ancient settlement of the Thessalian Perraibia. Precise localization of Doliche has a complex scholarly history. It was long assumed to be located in the vicinity of modern Dolichi/Duklista in Greece's Larisa regional unit (thus RE and BAtlas). Following the discovery of an extensive settlement site at Sarantaporo (8.5 kilometers west of modern Dolichi) in the 1990s, the excavators argued that it should be identified with ancient Doliche and this view has been widely repeated (e.g., New Pauly). More recently, the site of Kastri Livadiou (only about 4 km west southwest of modern Dolichi; 8.5 km southwest of modern Livadi) has been excavated. Here, a Late Antique walled settlement with three basilicas have been identified, together with inscriptions (found in conditions of reuse) attesting to an earlier temple of Herakles and, crucially, mentioning Doliche as a polis. The site at Sarantaporo may represent the original, Classical-to-Roman location of the polis, and the site at Kastri a later, fortified successor.

label: Dolichiste (island)
description: Dolichiste Ins. (Kekova) is a small island of Ionia.

label: Dongola
description: The late antique capital of the Nubian state of Makuria, Dongola remained an important center of trade through the medieval period.

label: Donousa (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B3 Donousa Ins.

label: Dorion
description: A fortified hilltop settlement overlooking the Soulima Valley in northern Messenia. Dorion appears in the Catalogue of Ships in Homer's Iliad.

label: Doriskos
description: An ancient Thracian settlement, located west of the Hebrus river.

label: Dorylaion
description: Dorylaion was an important city in the north of Phrygia (modern Eskişehir in Turkey).

label: Dos Barrios
description: A Spanish village located in the east of the province of Toledo that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Dosbarrios.

label: Doubios
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 88 C4 Doubios

label: Drabeskos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B3 Drabeskos

label: Drepanum
description: Drepanum, the modern Trapani, Sicily, is an ancient port city. The archaeological remains of the ancient city are meager. During the First Punic War, Hamilcar fortified the site. The Roman Republic lost a naval engagement near Drepanum in 249 B.C. but then prevailed in the battle of the Egadi islands in 241 B.C. The city was likely of censorial status thereafter.

label: Drobeta
description: Drobeta is a Dacian settlement that was conquered by the Romans in A.D. 101-2. Trajan's engineer Apollodorus of Damascus built a bridge here that spanned the Danube in 103-5. This bridge, supported by 20 stone pilings and extending 1,135 m connected Drobeta to Pontes (on the right bank of the river).

label: Drymaia
description: An ancient settlement. Its archaeological remains lie just to the southwest (pace NP) of modern Drymaia.

label: Drymos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D4 Drymos

label: Durno(no)varia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 E4 Durno(no)varia

label: Durobrivae
description: Roman town at present day Rochester, cited: BAtlas 8 H3 Durobrivae

label: Durocatalaunum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E4 Durocatalaunum

label: Durocortorum
description: The capital of the Remi in Gallia Belgica, now Reims.

label: Durostorum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 E4 Durostorum

label: Dyrr(h)achium/Epidamnos
description: A city founded in 627 B.C. by colonists from Corinth and Kerkyra.

label: Dystos
description: An ancient settlement of Euboea, its acropolis subsequently became the site of a Venetian tower.

label: Dāna
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is ad-Dāna.

label: Ebla
description: An important Bronze Age city and the capital of the three Eblaite Kingdoms.

label: Eboda
description: Known today as Avdat, this ruined city was founded by the Nabateans in the Negev desert in what is today southern Israel. It flourished into Byzantine times. Along with three other ancient settlements, it was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005.

label: Ebora
description: A Roman city with likely Celtic roots and a long, subsequent architectural history, the historic center of modern Évora in Portugal was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1986.

label: Eburacum
description: The site of a Roman legionary fortress, municipium, and colonia at modern-day York, England.

label: Eburobriga
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 A1 Eburobriga

label: Eburodunum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 G4 Eburodunum

label: Eburodunum
description: Eburodunum, located on the Thièle river, was the site of a Roman vicus and fort at the southern end of Lake Neuchâtel.

label: Eburum
description: Eburum (modern Eboli) was an ancient Lucanian settlement.

label: Ebusus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 G3 Ebusus

label: Ebusus (island)
description: Ebusus Ins. (modern Ibiza) is an island in the western Mediterranean Sea.

label: Ecbatana/Hagmatana/Achmeta/Epiphaneia/Ahmadan
description: The capital of Astyages (Istuvegü), captured by Cyrus the Great in 549 BC. The site served as a summer residence for both Persian and Parthian kings.

label: Echzell
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 B2 Echzell

label: Edessa (Macedonia)
description: An ancient settlement in Macedonia.

label: Edessa/Antiochia ad Callirhoem
description: Edessa/Antiochia ad Callirhoem was an ancient settlement of upper Mesopotamia, refounded by Seleucus I Nikator.

label: Egnatia/Gnathia
description: Egnatia/Gnathia was an ancient city of the Messapii in southern Italy.

label: Egra/Meda'in Salih
description: An ancient settlement located in the Hejaz of modern Saudi Arabia.

label: Eileithyiaspolis
description: Eileithyiaspolis is a city of Upper Egypt on the eastern bank of the Nile river. The site was occupied from the Neolithic period onwards. Its ancient name was most likely Nekheb.

label: Elaiousa (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C4 Elaiousa Ins.

label: Elateia
description: Elateia was an ancient Greek city of Phocis, and numbered as the most important place in that region after Delphi. The remains of the ancient site are located to the northeast of the modern town.

label: Elektra (river of Messenia)
description: An ancient river mentioned only by Pausanias who describes it, along with the Koios, as lying between Andania and Kyparissia in Messenia. RE declines to identify it with a specific modern river. BAtlas 58 labels a river stretch corresponding to the middle course of the modern Mavrozoumena river as mapped and named in OpenStreetMap, but in BAtlDir the corresponding modern name / location is given as "Chouchlotos", which does not appear in GeoNames, OpenStreetMap, Wikidata, or elsewhere on the web.

label: Elephantine
description: A fortified settlement located just before the First Cataract of the Nile. During the Second Intermediate Period, Elephantine marked the southern border of Egypt.

label: Eleusis
description: An ancient settlement, mentioned by Ptolemy, on the Aegean island of Thera. Scholars tentatively locate it in the vicinity of modern Βλυχάδα (Vlychada) on the island's southern tip.

label: Eleusis
description: Eleusis, located some 22 km west of Athens, was the site of the cult of Demeter and the sanctuary where the Eleusinian Mysteries were celebrated from the Bronze Age to the Roman Imperial period. It was a coastal deme of the Hippothontis tribe and the site of a military garrison in the Classical and Hellenistic periods.

label: Eleutherna
description: Eleutherna was an ancient polis on Crete, some 25 km from Rethymno.

label: Elewijt
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E2 Elewijt

label: Elimberrum
description: Elimberrum was the capital of the civitas of the Auscii.

label: Elis (city)
description: Elis was an ancient Greek city of the northwest Peloponnese that served as the capital of the district of the same name.

label: Elis (region)
description: An ancient region of the northwest Peloponnese.

label: Elslack Roman Fort
description: Also known as Burwen Castle, this site in North Yorkshire has produced evidence for a succession of two superimposed Roman forts. One or both of them are probably to be identified with the name Olenacum, preserved in ancient sources.

label: Elst
description: In the village of Elst, located between Arnhem and Nijmegen, the remains of two quadrangular Romano-Celtic-type temples were discovered beneath the parish church following World War II.

label: Elusa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 Elusa

label: Emerita Augusta
description: An ancient settlement (modern Mérida, Spain).

label: Emona
description: The ancient city of Emona (now modern Ljubljana).

label: Emporiae
description: A major economic center in the Iberian peninsula, Emporiae (modern Empúries) had indigenous origins but would be the site of a large Greek colonial city.

label: En Rimmon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F3 En Rimmon

label: Engaddai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G3 Engaddai

label: Enosis (island)
description: The Isola di San Pietro is one of the principal islands of the Sulcis archipelago.

label: Entella
description: Entella was an ancient city in the interior of Sicily, situated on the left bank of the river Hypsas.

label: Eordaia
description: A region of Macedonia

label: Epamanduodurum
description: Epamanduodurum was a Roman settlement along the road to Vesontio.

label: Ephesus/Arsinoe(ia)
description: Ephesus/Arsinoe(ia) was the most important ancient metropolis of Ionian Asia Minor.

label: Epitalion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Epitalion

label: Epora
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A3 Epora

label: Eporedia
description: A Roman military outpost during the Roman invasion of the Dora Baltea ca. 100 B.C., Eporedia was assigned to Regio XI.

label: Eratyra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 D3 Eratyra

label: Ercavica
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 C5 Ercavica

label: Erebuni
description: Erebuni was a fortified city of the ancient kingdom of Urartu located in what is now Yerevan, Armenia.

label: Erechtheion
description: The Erechtheion is a temple on the north side of the Athenian Acropolis dedicated to Athena Polias and other deities and heroes; the temple is of the Ionic order with several distinctive features, including its famous caryatid porch.

label: Eresos
description: An ancient settlement on the island of Lesbos (modern Skala Eresou), reputed birthplace of the poet Sappho. Strabo describes it as being built on a hill (presumably the modern Vigla) and extending down to the sea.

label: Eretria
description: Eretria was an ancient polis located in Euboea.

label: Eretria (Thessaly)
description: An ancient settlement, destroyed by Philip of Macedon.

label: Eridu
description: Eridu was an ancient city of Sumeria and perhaps one of the first true cities. The site is settled from ca. 5300 B.C. onward. Eridu was located approximately 12 km southwest of Ur and was the southernmost of a conglomeration of Sumerian cities that grew up around temple complexes.

label: Erikodes/Ericusa (island)
description: One of the Aeolian Islands; the island is the site of the extinct Montagnola volcano.

label: Erineos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B1 Erineos

label: Eriza
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 B1 Eriza

label: Erroneous Duplicate: Al-Hijr (Madâin Sâlih)
description: This place was published as an unintended duplicate of https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/814675/.

label: Erymanthos (river)
description: A right tributary of the Alpheios river in the Peloponnese.

label: Erymanthos M.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B2 Erymanthos M.

label: Erythrai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 E4 Erythrai

label: Erythrai
description: An ancient people, tribe, or cultural group.

label: Erythron
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 D1 Erythron

label: Eryx
description: An ancient, indigenous settlement of western Sicily, likely inhabited by the Elymians.

label: Erzurum
description: Erzurum is a modern city in eastern Turkey with antecedents at least as early as the Urartian period. In late Roman times, the settlement was known as Theodosiopolis. A medieval fortress (Erzurum Kale) occupies a prominent hill in the modern city center.

label: Escolives
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 A2 Escolives

label: Esotero (Oasis)
description: The modern Dakhla (Dakhleh) Oasis in Egypt's western desert.

label: Etaples
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B2 Etaples

label: Etruria/Tuscia (region)
description: Etruria/Tuscia was an ancient region of Central Italy inhabited by the Etruscans. Its spatial footprint was roughly equivalent to the modern Italian regions of Toscana and northern Lazio.

label: Euonymus (island)
description: One of the Aeolian Islands with occupation evidence beginning ca. 1200 B.C.

label: Eupalion
description: An ancient Greek settlement in the region of Locris. Modern consensus identifies an ancient "kastro" above modern Efpalio (called Soule prior to 1907) as Eupalion's acropolis.

label: Euphrates (river)
description: The longest river of Western Asia, the Euphrates flows from the Kara Su and the Murat Su to the confluence with the Tigris river.

label: Euripos
description: The strait between Euboea and Boeotia, located where the modern Greek city of Chalkida now stands. A bridge connected the land masses in antiquity.

label: Europos
description: An ancient city in Macedonia. The known components of the site (acropolis, extensive necropolis) are located immediately south of the modern town.

label: Europos/Euromos/Philippoi
description: Europos/Euromos/Philippoi was a settlement of interior Caria.

label: Faesulae
description: Faesulae (modern Fiesole) was an Etruscan foundation called Viesul, Viśl, or Vipsul. The city was conquered by Romans in 283 B.C. Sulla would settle Roman veterans there. Citizens of the town supported the conspiracy of Catiline.

label: Falerii Veteres
description: Falerii Veteres was the principal city of the Faliscans. It is located on a tuff outcropping at the point where several tributaries of the Treia join to flow into the Tiber. After rebelling against Rome in 241 B.C., Falerii suffered serious reversals of fortune.

label: Fanum Cocidi
description: A Roman fort north of Hadrian's Wall.

label: Fanum Fortunae
description: Fanum Fortunae, the site of a shrine to Fortuna, is first mentioned in the ancient sources in 49 B.C. when Iulius Caesar held the town. An Augustan colony was established at the site and the Romans prevailed in the Battle of Fano in A.D. 271. The town was eventually destroyed by the Ostrogoths.

label: Fanum Martis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D2 Fanum Martis

label: Fanum Martis/Civitas Coriosolitum
description: Fanum Martis/Civitas Coriosolitum (modern Corseul) was a major Gallo-Roman settlement, closely associated with the extra-urban sanctuary of Mars at Haut Bécherel. Fanum Martis/Civitas Coriosolitum was the chief town of the Coriosolites and was likely founded ca. 10 BC.

label: Faventia
description: A Roman city on the Via Aemilia.

label: Faviana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 I4 Faviana

label: Fectio
description: Fectio was a castellum along the Roman frontier system (limes) of Germania Inferior.

label: Felsina/Bononia
description: A city of the Po Plain with important cultural phases related to Etruscan, Celtic, and Roman culture. Important evidence for the Iron Age Villanovan culture has been found in Bononia and its vicinity. The Romans established a Latin colony of ca. 3000 settlers at Bononia in 189 BC. After changing hands several times following the fall of the Western Roman Empire, Bologna became an important Medieval center.

label: Ficaria (island)
description: An islet off the southeast coast of Sardinia.

label: Fines
description: A Gallo-Roman site lying along the Roman road from Lyon to Saintes.

label: Fines Africae et Cyrenensium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 37 D2 Fines Africae et Cyrenensium

label: Firmum Picenum
description: Firmum Picenum was founded as a Latin colony in 264 B.C. with 6,000 colonists. It received municipal status after 48 B.C.

label: Flavia Solva
description: Flavia Solva was a Celtic-Roman settlement located on the banks of the Mur river in Noricum.

label: Florentia
description: Florentia (modern Florence / Firenze) was founded as a colony for military veterans ca. 80 B.C. by Lucius Cornelius Sulla.

label: Forentum?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C2 Forentum?

label: Fortuna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 D3 Fortuna

label: Forum Augusti
description: The Forum of Augustus at Rome was dedicated in 2 BCE, to the northeast of Julius Caesar's Forum. It contained the Temple of Mars Ultor.

label: Forum Boarium (at Rome)
description: Rome's so-called "cattle market", the Forum Boarium is a key area of commercial and ritual activity on the east bank of the river Tiber. It is flanked by the Capitoline, Palatine, and Aventine hills.

label: Forum Cornelii
description: An ancient city founded by Lucius Cornelius Sulla as a colony ca. 82 BC.

label: Forum Domitii
description: Forum Domitii was a market created prior to the foundation of Narbonne along the Via Domitia.

label: Forum Iulii
description: A settlement founded as a Roman municipium along the line of the Via Iulia Augusta by Julius Caesar ca. 50 BCE (cited: BAtlas 19 F3 Forum Iulii)

label: Forum Livii
description: The town of Forum Livii in Gallia Cispadana is located on the right bank of the Montone River.

label: Forum Novum (Vescovio)
description: Forum Novum was a Roman town and an early medieval bishopric. It is located in the Sabine hills and was likely founded as a market center during the Republican period. It had achieved the status of municipium by the first century A.D. The market center seems to have remained active until at least the fourth century and by the fifth century, a bishopric is established there.

label: Forum Romanum
description: The ancient Roman forum.

label: Forum Segusiavorum
description: Forum Segusiavorum (Feurs) was a Roman market town at the junction of several major road systems.

label: Fossa Traiana
description: The Fossa Traiana (Channel of Trajan) describes a canal of ca. 45 m width connected with the artificial harbors at Portus. Despite the name, its origins may lie in the Claudian harbor works. The cutting of the channel created an artificial island between Ostia and Portus, the so-called Isola Sacra.

label: Fouman
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Fox-Amphoux
description: At Fox-Amphoux the remains of a Roman villa were discovered, adjacent to those of a sanctuary ad fines that may have been dedicated to the Capitoline triad. The site was in use from the time of Augustus until the third century AD.

label: Fregellae
description: Fregellae was a city of Latium Adjectum that became a Roman colony in 328 B.C., but was subsequently captured by the Samnites; a Roman presence was re-established in 313 B.C. Loyal to Rome during the Second Punic War, Fregellae revolted in 125 B.C. and the site was razed.

label: Fretum Oceani/Gallicum
description: The strait separating Gallia and Britannia.

label: Fufluna/Populonium
description: Populonia likely derives its name from the Etruscan god 'Fufluns' and was an important maritime and commercial center of Etruria located in the Colline Metallifere.

label: Fundanus L.
description: A brackish lake ca. 90 km southeast of Rome.

label: Gabii
description: An ancient Latin city located on the line of the Republican Via Praenestina connecting Rome to Praeneste. Gabii is allied to Rome from an early date and flourished during the archaic period, declining by the time of Augustus.

label: Gabrosentum
description: A Roman fort at present-day Moresby that was a part of the Cumbrian coastal defenses.

label: Gadara/Pompeia
description: A Ptolemaic foundation in northern Jordan that eventually became part of the Decapolis.

label: Gadeira/Gades/Col. Augusta Gaditana
description: Gadeira/Gades/Col. Augusta Gaditana (modern Cadiz, Spain) is an ancient city of Spain and one of the oldest continuously occupied cities of Europe. Its origins may be Phoenician (Gadir (Phoenician: גדר)).

label: Galatia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 B1 Galatia

label: Galatia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 N4 Galatia

label: Galepsos (Thrace)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B3 Galepsos

label: Gallaecia
description: The province of Gallaecia, also known as Hispania Gallaecia, was a Roman province in the north-west of Hispania.

label: Gallia
description: An ancient region covering a large part of southwestern Europe, roughly approximating the territory of modern France. It was bounded by the Atlantic Ocean, the Pyrenees mountains, the Mediterranean, the Alps, and the river Rhine. Gallia was famously described by Caesar as the territory of the ancient Celts (Celtae), whom the Romans called Gauls (Galli in Latin), hence the common modern usage "Gaul" for the region.

label: Gallicia
description: A region of northwest Spain that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Galicia.

label: Gallinaria (island)
description: An island in the Ligurian Sea.

label: Gallo-Roman Sanctuary at Bû
description: Remains of a rectangular Romano-Celtic temple were excavated north of the French town of Bû (in the department of Eure-et-Loir), beginning in the 1960s. Other buildings of uncertain nature and a theater were also identified in the vicinity. Coins and pottery discovered at the site indicate there was activity there during the Roman imperial period.

label: Gallo-Roman Sanctuary at Hanches
description: A Gallo-Roman sanctuary identified in the 1960s at La Cavée du Moulin near Hanches in the Eure-et-Loir department of France.

label: Gallo-Roman sites at Érome, France
description: A pair of archaeological sites in Gallia Narbonensis. The site of Les Orpaillots shows traces of a sanctuary and a group of tombs while Notre-Dame-de-la-Mure showed traces of a late third century Gallo-Roman villa.

label: Gallo-Roman vicus at Pierrefonds
description: An extensive (50+ hectares) ancient settlement located in the modern French commune of Pierrefonds, lying between Pierrefonds itself and Mont Berny to the northeast. Variously referred to in the modern literature as "Pierrefonds", "La Ville des Gaules", "Mont Berny", or "Saint-Étienne-Roilaye" (another nearby modern town), the ancient name of the vicus is unknown.

label: Gandzasar
description: 13th century Armenian cathedral located near the village of Vank in the disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh/Artsakh.

label: Gannat
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I2 Gannat

label: Garumna (river)
description: The Garonne is a river of southwestern Gaul and northern Iberia.

label: Gaulos (island)
description: The island called Gozo in modern times, part of the country of Malta.

label: Gaza
description: An important ancient settlement on the coast of Palestine.

label: Gazara
description: Gazara is a fortified ancient city dating to the early second millennium BCE.

label: Gaziantep
description: Gaziantep, also referred to as Antep, is located in southeastern Turkey. The site has a long history of settlement that begins in the Neolithic period. The site has a significant Hittite presence. Some scholars suggest it is the site of the Hellenistic city of Antiochia ad Taurum.

label: Gazoros
description: An ancient Macedonian settlement, located near the modern town that bears its name. A likely acropolis has been identified at the church of Hagios Athanasios, northeast of the modern town.

label: Gebel el-Haridi
description: An archaeological site located within Sohag Governate, near the village of El-Khazindariya, with evidence for human activity stretching from the Sixth Dynasty of the Old Kingdom to the late Roman Empire and the Coptic period.

label: Gela
description: A Greek colony of Sicily founded by Rhodians and Cretans ca. 688 B.C. The oikists were the Rhodian Antiphemos and the Cretan Entimos.

label: Geminiacum?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E2 Geminiacum?

label: Genava
description: Genava (modern Geneva) was originally an oppidum of the Allobroges that passed into Roman control after the campaigns of Iulius Caesar.

label: Genesion/Apobathmoi
description: An ancient settlement located south of modern Kivari in the Peloponnese.

label: Genua
description: Genua was an ancient settlement of Liguria that came to be destroyed by Carthage in 209 BC. Thereafter it received Roman municipal privileges and was rebuilt.

label: Genusus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 B2 Genusus fl.

label: Gephyra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 C3 Gephyra

label: Gerar
description: Gerar, located in south-central Israel, is associated with the Philistines and is mentioned in the Book of Genesis.

label: Gerasa/Antiochia ad Chrysorhoam
description: Gerasa (modern Jerash in Jordan) became a substantial center under Antiochos IV Epiphanes, at which time it became known as Antioch on the Chrysorhoas. It became part of the territory of Iudaea and in 63 B.C. Pompeius Magnus made it part of the Decapolis. It received the status of a Roman colony in the third century.

label: Gergovia?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I3 Gergovia?

label: Germania Inferior
description: Germania Inferior was a province of the Roman empire located on the west bank of the Rhine river. It was established as a province ca. AD 80.

label: Germania Superior
description: Germania Superior was a province of the Roman empire. Its administrative capital was Mogontiacum (Mainz).

label: Germanikeia
description: An ancient city located in the northern Syrian region of Commagene mentioned. Modern Maraş.

label: Gerunda
description: A settlement of Tarraconensis located at the confluence of the Ter and the Onyar rivers, Gerunda was the chief town of the Gerundenses. Modern Girona in Spain.

label: Gesoriacum/Bononia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B2 Gesoriacum/Bononia

label: Gianola
description: The site of a villa associated with Lucius Vitruvius Mamurra.

label: Gigia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 F1 Gigia

label: Gimilena
description: A Spanish village located in the west of Jaén that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today it is known as Jamilena.

label: Givry
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E2 Givry

label: Giza
place_type: sanctuary, cemetery, pyramid, tomb, settlement, architecturalcomplex
description: The site of Giza encompasses the Giza Necropolis, a large archaeological site famous for its pyramid complexes and monumental sculpture.

label: Glanum
description: Glanum was a Celtic oppidum that became a Roman city; it was eventually abandoned in the third century AD.

label: Glaukos (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B1 Glaukos fl.

label: Golgoi
description: An ancient settlement on the island of Cyprus whose temple of Aphrodite is mentioned in ancient sources. The presumed site is located near modern Athienou and Ag. Fotios.

label: Gomphoi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B2 Gomphoi

label: Gonnoi
description: An ancient settlement of Perrhaibia, located at the western entry of the Tempe pass.

label: Gordion/Vindia?
description: The capital city of ancient Phrygia, the ruins of Gordion are located near the modern village of Yassıhüyük about 10km east of the Turkish city of Polatlı.

label: Gorsium/Herculia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F2 Gorsium/Herculia

label: Gortyn(a)
description: The Roman capital of Creta et Cyrenaica province, then Creta, and later seat of the Archbishop of Crete, Gortyna was a thriving community from the Geometric period to the Middle Byzantine period. The first traces of urban settlement date from the Archaic period. The ancient Greek law code known as the "Gortyn Code" was discovered there in 1884.

label: Gournia
description: A Minoan palace complex and settlement on Crete, finally abandoned ca. 1200 BCE. The original toponym is unknown, and the modern name is derived from stone vessels found at the site.

label: Goyman/Kumandan/Eran-vinard-Kavad
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 92 F2 Goyman/Kumandan/Eran-vinard-Kavad

label: Grannum
description: Grannum was a Gallo-Roman town of the civitas Leucorum.

label: Grave Circle A at Mycenae
description: Grave Circle A encloses a royal cemetery within the walls of the citadel of Mycenae; inside it are six shaft graves constructed around 1600 BC.

label: Graviscae
description: The port of the Etruscan city of Tarquinia.

label: Greek Theater at Syracuse
description: Rock-cut theater of Greek form at Syracuse, Sicily, probably in use from the 5th c. BC to the Late Roman period.

label: Grobbendonk
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E1 Grobbendonk

label: Grumentum
description: Grumentum was an ancient settlement of Lucania, likely inhabited since the sixth century B.C. The site played a role in the Second Punic War and later became a bishopric in the fourth century A.D.

label: Guadarmes (river)
description: Today is known as the Guadalmez, the Guadarmes is a river located in the south of the province of Ciudad Real, Spain.

label: Guillena
description: A Spanish village located north of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Gulf of Saint Eufemia
description: A number of ancient names were used to identify the modern Gulf of Saint Euphemia off the west Calabrian coast of Italy: "Vibonensis sinus", "Hipponiates kolpos", and "Terinaeus sinus" (as well as its Greek equivalent "Terinaios kolpos"). A passage in Aristotle's Politics uses the unrelated Greek name "Lametikos Kolpos" for the same gulf, or at least its northern extent near the mouth of the ancient Lametus (modern Amato) river. The BAtlas treated this name as separate from the others in labeling the map, and the distinction has been maintained in the Pleiades gazetteer by using two separate (but connected) place resources.

label: Gumis?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 F3 Gumis?

label: Guntia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 D4 Guntia

label: Gyaros (island)
description: Gyaros is an island in the Aegean Sea, located to the south of Andros. The geographer Strabo visited the island in 29 B.C.

label: Gyth(e)ion
description: An ancient Greek polis located on the Mani peninsula of the Peloponnese. Modern Gytheio.

label: Göbekli Tepe
description: The site of Göbekli Tepe, located in the Germuş mountains of south-eastern Anatolia, was the location of a Neolithic hilltop sanctuary. This sanctuary, thought to be a series of stone enclosures with T-shaped pillars carrying carving of wild animals, was built in the Pre-Pottery Neolithic and ranges in date from 9,600 to 8,200 B.C.

label: Gücük
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Hacımusalar Höyük
description: A large settlement mound in modern Turkey's Elmalı basin where habitation from the Early Bronze Age through the Byzantine period has been documented. The city was known to Greek and Roman authors as Choma.

label: Hadid/Ad(d)ida
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Hadid/Ad(d)ida

label: Hadrian's Wall
description: Hadrian's Wall or Vallum Aelium was the first of two Roman fortifications built across northern Britannia. The project was begun in A.D. 122 and the works eventually stretched from the River Tyne near the North Sea to the Solway Firth on the Irish Sea. The wall represented the northern limit of the Roman Empire.

label: Hadrianoupolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 H1 Hadrianoupolis

label: Hadrianoutherai
description: Located in Mysia, Hadrianoutherai was established by the Roman emperor Hadrian.

label: Hadrumetum/Iustinianopolis
description: Hadrumetum/Iustinianopolis was an important ancient port in North Africa. Founded by Phoenicians, the site pre-dated Carthage. Under Roman administration the site prospered and Trajan assigned it colonial status as Colonia Concordia Ulpia Trajana Augusta Frugifera Hadrumetina.

label: Hagar Qin Megalithic Temple Complex (Malta)
description: Ħaġar Qim is a megalithic temple complex (ca. 3600-3200 BC), included in the UNESCO World Heritage List.

label: Hala Sultan Tekke
description: A major Late Bronze Age settlement occupied the site of Hala Sultan Tekke, which later became an important Sufi Islamic shrine associated with Umm Haram.

label: Halaesa
description: Halaesa is located on the north coast of Sicily between between Kalakta and Kephaloidion. The city was founded in 403 B.C. by Archonides of Herbita. The city sided with Rome during the First Punic War and was made "libera et immunis". By the Augustan period it had become a municipium.

label: Halder
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F1 Halder

label: Halicarnassus/Halikarnassos
description: An ancient city in Caria, now known as Bodrum in Turkey.

label: Halmyris?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 C3 Halmyris?

label: Halone (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B4 Halone Ins.

label: Halos
description: An ancient city of Thessaly. Modern Alos, Greece.

label: Haltern
description: A sequence of occupational phases at Haltern, Germany, results from the presence of the Roman military following from the earliest period of Roman occupation in the principate of Augustus.

label: Haluntium
description: An ancient settlement located between Tyndaris and Calacte. Some authors ascribe the foundation of the site to the Acarnanians.

label: Halys (river)
description: The Kızılırmak river, the ancient Halys River, is a major river of Asia Minor that flows into the Black Sea.

label: Harappa
description: A Bronze Age fortified city located on the Ravi River, inhabited from the fourth through the second millennia BCE, Harappa was one of the most important settlements of the Indus Valley Civilization.

label: Harran/Carrhae
description: A major settlement of Upper Mesopotamia from the Bronze Age onward. The earliest mentions of the site are found in the Ebla tablets (ca. 2300 B.C.). Notably the location of the Battle of Carrhae between the Roman Republic and Parthian Empire in 53 B.C., which proved to be a devastating defeat for the Romans. Modern-day Ḥarrān, Turkey.

label: Hasta
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 C4 Hasta

label: Hatra
description: Hatra (al-Hadr) is an ancient city of western Assyria. Founded perhaps in the third century BC, the city rose to prominence in the Parthian Empire.

label: Hatria (Picenum)
description: An ancient city of Picenum that may have originated as colony established by Etruscans from Adria in the Veneto region. An alternate narrative suggests that the city's origins may be as a late sixth century B.C. colony founded by Aegina.

label: Hattusa
description: The Late Bronze Age capital of the Hittite empire (near modern Boğazkale in Turkey). The site was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

label: Hebromagus/Eburomagus
description: Hebromagus/Eburomagus (modern Bram, Aude) was a crossroads village along the road from Narbo to Tolosa.

label: Hebron
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Hebron

label: Hebros (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 G1 Hebros fl.

label: Helena (island)
description: An Aegean island that parallels the southeast coast of Attica (modern Makronisos).

label: Helikore/Nicaea
description: Helikore/Nicaea (modern İznik, Turkey) was a Greek city of northwestern Anatolia. It was the site of the First and Second Councils of Nicaea and was the interim capital city of the Byzantine Empire between 1204 and 1261.

label: Heliopolis
description: Ancient Heliopolis was the capital of the 13th or Heliopolite Nome of Lower Egypt and served as a major religious center. The site is now located in Ayn Shams, a suburb of Cairo.

label: Heliopolis/Col. Iulia Augusta Felix
description: An ancient settlement in Lebanon's Beqaa Valley, named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site because "with its colossal structures, [it] is one of the finest examples of Imperial Roman architecture at its apogee."

label: Hellas (Late Roman province)
description: Hellas was an administrative region of the Late Roman Empire, included in the prefecture of Illyrikon according to Hierocles.

label: Hellespont (strait)
description: The Hellespont is a narrow strait of northwestern Turkey that connects the Aegean Sea to the Propontis (Sea of Marmara). It is known today as the Dardanelles. Pseudo-Apollodorus records a myth that seems to have been widespread in antiquity: the Hellespont got its name by being the place where Helle, sister of Phrixus, fell off the flying golden ram.

label: Helorus
description: An ancient settlement of Sicily that was likely a colonial foundation of Syracuse.

label: Helorus (river)
description: Helorus fl. (Tellaro), a river of southeast Sicily.

label: Hephaisteion
description: The temple of Hephaistos located on the northwest side of the Agora of Athens dates to the middle of the fifth century B.C.

label: Heraclea
description: An ancient settlement on the Black Sea coast of Asia Minor at modern Karadeniz Ereğli in Turkey. It is often referred to as Heraclea Pontica (or Heraclea in Pontus) to distinguish it from other cities with the same name.

label: Heraclea Minoa
description: An ancient Greek city on the south coast of Sicily, located at the mouth of the Halykos River. Founded by Selinus in the sixth century BC, the site was abandoned in the first century AD.

label: Heraion
description: The sanctuary of Hera on Samos.

label: Herakleia (island)
description: An Aegean island in the Cyclades island group, located south of Naxos.

label: Heraklion
description: Heraklion was the harbor city of ancient Knossos, and was later re-founded by the Arab conquerors.

label: Herculaneum
description: An ancient Roman town of Campania destroyed by the eruption of Mt. Vesuvius in A.D. 79. Named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

label: Herdoniae/Ardaneae/Civitas Serdonis
description: Herdonia was an ancient city of Apulia located along the via Minucia. The city was the site of two major engagements of the Second Punic War (212 and 210 BCE, respectively), both of which were Carthaginian victories. The city's extensive remains have been investigated by the Belgian Institute since the Second World War.

label: Hermaia Akra/Mercurii Pr./Kalon Akroterion?
description: Cap Bon is a peninsula of northeastern Tunisia.

label: Hermonassa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 E3 Hermonassa

label: Hermopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 E3 Hermopolis

label: Hermopolis Magna/Schmun
description: The capital city of the Hermopolite nome (the fifteenth Nome of Upper Egypt). The ancient Egyptians called the site Khmun after the group of eight divinities (Ogdoad) that represented the primordial world.

label: Hermopolis Mikra
description: Hermopolis Mikra was an ancient city of Egypt that served as he capital of Lower Egypt's 7th Nome (A-ment).

label: Heznalcaçar
description: A Spanish village located in the southwest of the province of Sevilla that once belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today known as Aznalcázar.

label: Hibernia
description: Hibernia is the Classical name for the island of Ireland.

label: Hiera (Hephaistou) (island)
description: One of the Aeolian Islands utilized in antiquity mostly for its natural resources. Ancient Romans exploited resources including wood, alum, and sulfur.

label: Hierapolis/Bambyke
description: Hierapolis/Bambyke was an ancient settlement of Commagene. The city was also a center for the worship of the Syrian goddess Atargatis.

label: Hierapolis/Pamukkale
description: Hierapolis (modern Pamukkale in Turkey's Denizli province) was a major ancient city in Phrygia located at the site of hot springs in southwestern Anatolia. The site was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1988.

label: Hildesheim
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 10 F4 Hildesheim

label: Himera
description: A colony on the north shore of Sicily founded in 649/8 BC by the Myletidai.

label: Hippo Diarrhytus
description: Hippo Diarrhytus was an ancient port located on the coast of North Africa. The site is now occupied by the city of Bizerte in Tunisia.

label: Hippo Regius
description: Hippo Regius (modern Annaba in Algeria) was a colony established by Phoenicians from Tyre as early as the twelfth century BC.

label: Hipponion/Vibo Valentia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 D4 Hipponion/Vibo Valentia

label: Hispalis/Col. Romula
description: Hispalis/Col. Romula (modern Seville, Spain).

label: Hispania
description: An ancient region corresponding to the Iberian peninsula and so roughly to the territories of the modern countries of Spain and Portugal.

label: Histria
description: Histria was a Greek colony founded near the mouths of the Danube ca. 630 BC.

label: Hurmizd Ardashir/[Suq al-Ahwaz]
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 E2 Hurmizd Ardashir/[Suq al-Ahwaz]

label: Husifa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 Husifa

label: Huzirina
description: The ancient Huzirina, modern Sultantepe, is a Late Neo-Assyrian archeological site, now in Şanlıurfa Province, Turkey.

label: Hydata Lesitana
description: An ancient thermal site with both nuragic and Roman remains. Now the community of Benettuti on the island of Sardinia.

label: Hydroussa/Hydrea (island)
description: An island of the Aegean Sea between the Saronic and Argolic gulfs.

label: Hydruntum/Hydrous
description: A Greek city at the easternmost point of the Italian peninsula that sided against Rome in both the Pyrrhic and Hannibalic wars. In the time of the Roman Empire the city was located in the province of Calabria and was an embarkation point for ships leaving for Apollonia across the Adriatic Sea.

label: Hypsous (settlement)
description: An ancient settlement, ruined by Pausanias' day, thought to have been located in the vicinity of the modern village of Stemnitsa in Greece's Trikoloni municipality (Arcadia).

label: Iader
description: The ancient Roman town of Iader (Iadera), given status of a Roman colony in 48 B.C.

label: Ialysos
description: Ialysos was an ancient city located on the north coast of the island of Rhodes. Together with Lindus and Kamiros it was one of the three ancient cities of Rhodes.

label: Iamneia
description: Iamneia was a Philistine town on the northwestern border of Iudaea.

label: Iamo/Iamna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 inset Iamo/Iamna

label: Iasos
description: Iasos was an ancient Greek city in Caria.

label: Iathrippa
description: Iathrippa was an oasis settlement along the Incense Road. From the Roman period until the advent of Islam the site was the seat of influential Iudaeo-Arabian tribes. Iathrippa would become an important center of Islam. Muhammad fled here from Mecca in 622 and the site was renamed Al-Madīna. It remained a key center until 656. It is the site of Muhammad's grave and a place of Muslim pilgrimage.

label: Iatinon/Fixtuinum
description: Iatinon/Fixtuinum was a city of the the city of the Meldi, a people of Gallia Lugdunensis.

label: Iciodoro
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F2 Iciodoro

label: Iconium/Claudiconium
description: Iconium/Claudiconium (modern Konya) was an important city in Lycaonia that later became part of the Roman province of Galatia.

label: Icosium
description: Icosium (modern Algiers) was a Punic and, later, Roman settlement in coastal north Africa. Legend holds that 20 of Herakles' companions founded the original town.

label: Idalion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C2 Idalion

label: Idu/Diacira/Hit
description: An Old Babylonian site in Iraq's Al Anbar province, Hit was renowned in antiquity for its bitumen springs.

label: Ierusalem/Hierosolyma/Col. Aelia Capitolina
description: The city of Jerusalem.

label: Ietas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Ietas

label: Igabrum/Egabrum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A4 Igabrum/Egabrum

label: Igel
description: The village of Igel is known for its funerary monument of the Secundinii dating ca. A.D. 250.

label: Igilgili
description: Originally a Carthaginian trading post, Igilgili eventually came to be part of Mauretania Caesariensis as a Roman colony.

label: Igilium (island)
description: An island in the Tyrrhenian Sea with Etruscan and Roman occupation.

label: Igilium (settlement and villa)
description: An ancient settlement and villa at modern Giglio Porto on the Italian island of Giglio.

label: Iguvium
description: An Umbrian hilltown, Iguvium is best known as the find-spot of the Iguvine Tables.

label: Ikaros (island)
description: An island in the Aegean Sea (modern Ikaria), now part of the modern country of Greece. According to Ovid, the island took its name from the burial place of Ikaros, son of Daidalos, whose fantastic flight on wings made by his father ended tragically in the sea nearby.

label: Ilerda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F4 Ilerda

label: Iliberri
description: An ancient settlement located to the west of modern Granada. Its precise location is unknown.

label: Ilici/Helike
description: The site of Ilici began as a pre-Roman settlement that eventually developed into a Roman municipium. The site continued into the Visigothic and Byzantine periods as a minor urban settlement, controlling a vast territory which reached old Lucentum. The settlement was relocated to the modern site of Elche in the Islamic period.

label: Ilipa Magna
description: Ilipa Magna was located on the right bank of the Baetis river. It is now the modern Alcalá del Río. In antiquity it was notable for silver mines located nearby.

label: Ilium/Troia
description: An ancient city of northwest Anatolia with occupation ranging from the Bronze Age to the Roman period. Troy features as the central setting of Homer's Iliad.

label: Ill(ib)erris/Helena
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H3 Ill(ib)erris/Helena

label: Iluro
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F5 Iluro

label: Iluro
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 H4 Iluro

label: Ilva/Aethalia (island)
description: The largest island of the Tuscan Archipelago, Ilva (modern Elba) is located in the Tyrrhenian Sea 50 km east of Corsica. It is the third largest Italian island.

label: Imbros (island)
description: The island of Imbros (modern Gökçeada in Turkey) was colonized by Athens in antiquity.

label: Imbros (settlement)
description: An ancient settlement (modern Kaleköy on the Turkish island of Gökçeada).

label: Imeus (mountain)
description: Imeus Mons is the name given in the Peutinger Table to a pass that leads from the Fucine lake to the territory of the Peligni; the Via Valeria crossed the pass which is now known as the Forca Caruso.

label: Imus Pyreneus
description: A Roman military installation and route station mentioned in the Antonine Itineraries, Imus Pyreneus is located in the modern French commune of Saint-Jean le Vieux.

label: Inachos (river)
description: A river located near Argos in modern Greece.

label: India
description: The region of ancient India as understood by the Greeks and Romans.

label: Intaranum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 A2 Intaranum

label: Interamna Nahars
description: An Umbrian center founded in the seventh century B.C. that became an important Roman municipality along the Via Flaminia.

label: Interamnia Praetuttiorum
description: Originally a settlement of the Praetuttii located at the confluence of the rivers Tordino and Vezzola (modern Teramo).

label: Intercisa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F3 Intercisa

label: Internum Mare
description: The Mediterranean Sea or Mare Nostrum is a sea connected to the Atlantic Ocean that is surrounded almost completely by land.

label: Interocrium
description: A Sabine town that was later known as a mansio on the course of the Via Salaria.

label: Iolkos
description: Iolkos was an ancient city located in Magnesia, Thessaly, Greece.

label: Ionium Mare
