description: The Ionian Sea, located south of the Adriatic Sea, is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea.

label: Ioppe
description: Ioppe (Jaffa) is an ancient port city in Iudaea.

label: Iordanes (river)
description: Iordanes fl. (the Jordan river).

label: Ios (island)
description: One of the Cycladic Islands.

label: Ios (settlement)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A4 Ios

label: Iotapata
description: A Hellenistic village that later became a key site during the Great Jewish Revolt.

label: Iotape
description: An ancient settlement, located at modern Aytap on the southern coast of Turkey.

label: Iouernikos Okeanos
description: The Irish Sea separates the islands of Ireland and Great Britain.

label: Ipagrum/Epagrum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F4 Ipagrum/Epagrum

label: Irgenhausen
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 A2 Irgenhausen

label: Iria/Forum Iulii Iriensium
description: Iria/Forum Iulii Iriensium (modern Voghera) was located along the road from Placentia to Dertona. An Augustan colony was established there (colonia Forum Iulium Iriensium) that was then destroyed in the first century AD.

label: Isca Dumnoniorum
description: Isca Dumnoniorum (modern Exeter) was a Roman military complex and later town that was the likely base of Legio II Augusta in the first century, prior to its move to Isca Silurum.

label: Isca Silurum
description: Roman legionary fortress at present-day Caerleon. Base of Legio II Augusta from ca. A.D. 75-300. Also known as Isca Augusta and Isca Silurum.

label: Issa (island)
description: An island in the Adriatic, known today as Vis (Croatian) and Lissa (Italian).

label: Isthmos
description: The Isthmus of Corinth is a narrow land bridge connecting the Peloponnese peninsula to the Greek mainland.

label: Istros (island)
description: The modern Aegean island of Giali.

label: Isurium
description: Isurium (modern Aldborough) was a Roman settlement - and likely fort - along Dere Street.

label: Italica
description: A city in Spain founded in 206 B.C. by Publius Cornelius Scipio Africanus as a site at which to settle Roman soldiers wounded in the Battle of Ilipa.

label: Itanos
description: An ancient coastal settlement of east Crete. The site is located north of the palm forest at Vai and has provided evidence for occupation from the archaic period through late antiquity.

label: Ithaca (island)
description: A rocky, Ionian island located off the west coast of Greece that boasted important natural harbors. By historical Greek times, the island was assumed to be identical with the Ithaca of Homer (i.e., the home of Odysseus) and a hero cult dedicated to him was active there.

label: Ithaca (settlement)
description: The ancient city of Ithaca on the homonymous Aegean island. Following RE, BAtlas locates it at the small, protected harbor of Polis on the island's northwest coast.

label: Ithome/Thamiai (Thessaly)
description: A town in the Hestiaiotis region between Metropolis and Gomphoi. Now modern Phanari, where the visible architecture on the acropolis largely belongs to Byzantine and Ottoman fortresses.

label: Iudaea (province)
description: The Roman province of Iudaea, incorporating the historical regions of Judea, Samaria, and Idumaea, was established in 6 CE, when the former tetrarchy of Herod Archelaus came under direct Roman administration. Following the Bar Kokhba War (132-135), Hadrian changed the province's name to Palaestina, and in the mid- to late 4th century CE the area was divided into three provinces (Palaestina Prima, Secunda, and Tertia or Salutaris).

label: Iuliobona
description: A settlement of the Caletes in Gallia Belgica

label: Iuliomagus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E1 Iuliomagus

label: Iulium Carnicum
description: Iulium Carnicum (modern Zuglio) was a Roman settlement built atop an indigenous settlement after 52 BC. It was a dependency of Aquileia.

label: Iuvavum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 F2 Iuvavum

label: Izernore
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 C3 Izernore

label: Jabal al-Bayḍā
description: Hill southwest of Mount 'Abd al-'Aziz in Syria. The peak at the southwestern end of the hill is known as Rās et-Tell. Excavations were carried out there by Max von Oppenheim in the early 20th century, uncovering sculptures and graves from the Bronze Age.

label: Jaunay-Clan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F2 Jaunay-Clan

label: Jericho
description: An ancient site in the Jordan valley with occupation beginning ca. 11,000 years BP. The tell of Hierichous (Jericho) has more than 20 settlement horizons, ranging from Natufian Hunter-Gatherers to modern.

label: Jrvezh
description: Village east of Yerevan in Armenia. The town, which has been settled since at least the 5th century CE, contains a 7th-century chapel.

label: Kabeira/Neocaesarea/Diospolis/Sebaste/Hadriane
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 B4 Kabeira/Neocaesarea/Diospolis/Sebaste/Hadriane

label: Kabnak
description: An important town of the Middle Elamite period discovered at the archaeological site of Haft Tepe in southwestern Iran. The site was an important center of the Elamite kingdom in the 15th century BCE, and also shows signs of inhabitation from the Parthian to the Early Islamic periods.

label: Kabul
description: Pre-modern settlement at and around the area of modern Kabul, Afghanistan has been known by various names in a variety of languages and periods. Excavations begun in the early twenty-first century have significantly extended scholarly understanding established in the early-to-mid 20th century.

label: Kadasa
description: A multi-period settlement, with Bronze Age to Roman occupation, most notably the site of a large, Persian and Hellenistic administrative building.

label: Kaine/Maximianopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 80 B1 Kaine/Maximianopolis

label: Kainepolis
description: Major city of Armenia. Inhabited since the Neolithic Period, the city was capital of the Arsacid Kingdom of Armenia from 120-330 CE, and became a major religious center with the construction of Etchmiadzin Cathedral in the early 4th century.

label: Kaisareia
description: An ancient settlement of west Macedonia, mentioned by Procopius as one of many whose fortifications were reconstructed under Justinian.

label: Kaisareia/Hadrianopolis/Proseilemmene
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 C3 Kaisareia/Hadrianopolis/Proseilemmene

label: Kalamai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C3 Kalamai

label: Kalaureia (island)
description: An island near the coast of Troezen in the Peloponnesus, now known as Poros.

label: Kallipo(u)lis
description: Kallipo(u)lis was founded by the Macedonians in the fifth century BC.

label: Kallipolis/Anxa
description: Kallipolis/Anxa in legend was said to have been founded by Idomeneus of Crete, while Pliny the Elder credits Senonian Gauls as founders. It is most likely that the site was a Messapic settlement.

label: Kaloi Limenes
description: An embayment of the Mediterranean Sea on the southern coastline of Crete, some 7 km east of Cape Lithinon, 2 km west of Lasaia, and 10 km west of Lebena. The location is noted for the visit of the Christian apostle St. Paul in ca. 47 CE.

label: Kalos Limen?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 23 F3 Kalos Limen?

label: Kana
description: Kana is a site of Christian pilgrimage located in southern Lebanon.

label: Kantanos
description: An ancient settlement and associated mine at modern Kandanos in west Crete.

label: Kapan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 B1 Kapan

label: Kapros
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B3 Kapros

label: Kapros (island)
description: Modern Kafkanas island, which lies just off the northeast coast of the Chalkidike in the Strymonic Gulf.

label: Karambis
description: A coastal promontory located northwest of Doğanyurt, Turkey. Modern Kerembe burnu.

label: Karanis
description: Karanis was a settlement (κώμη) located on the northern edge of the Fayum, now Kom Ausīm. Ptolemy II Philadelphus established Karanias in order to settle Greek mercenaries among indigenous Egyptians. This foundation, and others, also aimed to exploit the agricultural fertility of the Fayum depression.

label: Karbalāʾ
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Kardamyle (Messenia)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C4 Kardamyle

label: Karnasion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B3 Karnasion

label: Karpasia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 E1 Karpasia

label: Karpasiai (islands)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 E1 Karpasiai Inss.

label: Karpathos (island)
description: Karpathos, part of the Dodecanese, lies between Crete and Rhodes in the southern Aegean Sea.

label: Kars
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Karyai?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 D3 Karyai?

label: Karystos
description: Karystos was a Greek polis located on the south coast of Euboea. It is included in Homer's "catalogue of ships" in the Iliad, and its name is also thought to be attested in Linear B documents. The ancient acropolis hill, which lies to the north of the modern coastal village, is now occupied by the remains of the Venetian "Castel Rosso".

label: Kasos (island)
description: Southwest of Karpathos, Kasos is the southernmost island of the Dodecanese.

label: Kasos (settlement)
description: The homonymous ancient settlement on the Dodecanese island of Kasos, which was located at modern Kastro/Poli.

label: Kassiope
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 A2 Kassiope

label: Kassope
description: A city with an extensive circuit wall, temple, theater, and agora.

label: Kasta tomb
description: A tumulus of Macedonian or Roman date located in the hinterland of Amphipolis. The tomb was discovered in 2012 and first entered in 2014.

label: Kastamonu
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 D2 Kastamonu

label: Katane/Catina
description: The colonial city of Katane (modern Catania) was founded by Chalcidian Greeks sometime after the foundation of Leontini in 730 B.C.

label: Kebili (formerly Babil)
description: The small village of Babil (now Kebili) is located about 25 km southwest of Cizre, near the Tigris river, directly on the Turkish-Syrian border. The name of the ancient site whose ruins lay beneath the modern village is not known.

label: Kefar Nahum/Kapharnaoum
description: Kefar Nahum/Kapharnaoum was a Hasmonean village located on the northern shore of the Sea of Galilee.

label: Kekryphaleia (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 E2 Kekryphaleia Ins.

label: Kenchreai
description: The ancient Saronic Gulf port of Corinth (near modern Kechries in Greece).

label: Keos (island)
description: One of the islands of the Cyclades.

label: Kephisia
description: Kephisia was an inland deme of the tribe Erechtheis in Attica

label: Kerameikos
description: A district of ancient Athens located northwest of the Acropolis, the Kerameikos takes its name from the potters' workshops in the area; the portion of the district lying outside the Dipylon Gate served as a necropolis.

label: Kerasous/Pharnakeia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 D4 Kerasous/Pharnakeia

label: Keria (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 B4 Keria Ins.

label: Kerinthos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 E3 Kerinthos

label: Keryn(e)ia/Keraunia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C2 Keryn(e)ia/Keraunia

label: Keryneia
description: An ancient city located on a hill immediately north of the modern Greek village of Mamousia (Achaea).

label: Kestrine/Kammania
description: A district of Epirus.

label: Khabiṣ
description: Neolithic site located about 5 km east of the town of Shadad on the edge of the Dasht-i Lut (Lut desert) in southeastern Iran.

label: Kharg
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 G4 Kharg

label: Khirbet Qeiyafa
description: Khirbet Qeiyafa, also known as Elah Fortress, is an Iron Age fortress site located about 40 kilometers southwest of Jerusalem, overlooking the Elah Valley. The site was likely constructed in the late eleventh century BCE and destroyed or abandoned in the mid- to late tenth century BCE.

label: Kimolos (island)
description: Kimolos Ins. (Kimolos) is an island in the Aegean Sea that is part of the Cyclades.

label: Kios/Askanios (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 E4 Kios/Askanios fl.

label: Kirra
description: An ancient port settlement located at modern Magoula Xeropigadas in the Greek municipality of Itea near where the Pleistos river debouches into the Corinthian Gulf. Classical Kirra has earlier, Helladic antecedents in this area.

label: Kisamos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A2 Kisamos

label: Kition
description: Kition was an ancient city founded on the southern coast of Cyprus in the thirteenth century B.C.

label: Kizkapanli
description: A modern village near the Pazarcik dam in Turkey. The Pazarcik Stele, which bears inscriptions of the Assyrian kings Adad-nerari III and Shalmaneser IV, was discovered here.

label: Kladeos (river)
description: A river of the Peloponnese and tributary of the Alpheios, which it joins from the north at the ancient site of Olympia in Greece.

label: Klaros
description: The site of a temple of Apollo administered by Colophonians and active from the seventh century B.C. to the fourth century A.D.

label: Klazomenai (earlier)
description: The initial, mainland site of the city, located to the southwest of modern Urla Iskelesi in Turkey. Pausanias reports that the city relocated to an island in the Bay of Smyrna, for which see "Klazomenai (later)."

label: Klazomenai (later)
description: A town in Lydia that, according to Pausanias, moved from an initial, mainland site thought by scholars to have been southwest of modern Urla Iskelesi to an island in the Bay of Smyrna (modern Klazümen). This place resource represents the later city; see also "Klazomenai (earlier)."

label: Kleitor (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C2 Kleitor fl.

label: Kleitor (settlement)
description: An ancient city of Arcadia in the Peloponnese. The site of ancient Kleitor lies at the western end of a valley; modern Kleitoria lies at the eastern end.

label: Kleonai
description: An ancient city located in the mountainous area southwest of Corinth. The acropolis of ancient Kleonai lies about two kilometers east of the modern town named after it in the 1960s (Archaies Kleones, formerly Kontostavlos).

label: Knidos
description: Knidos was an ancient city of Cyprus located on the Elaea promontory in northeastern Cyprus.

label: Knosos/Col. Iulia Nobilis Cnosos
description: A major ancient settlement of Crete, located some 5 km southeast of Heraklion, Knossos was occupied from the Neolithic period to the time of the Roman Empire.

label: Koinyra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 D3 Koinyra

label: Koloneia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 D4 Koloneia

label: Kolonos
description: Kolonos was a deme assigned to the phyle Aegeis in Attica. It was located to the north of the Academy and provided the setting for one of the tragedies of Sophocles. The district is associated with the god Poseidon.

label: Komar(ei) (promontory)
description: The modern Kanyakumari (Cape Comorin), southernmost tip of the Indian subcontinent.

label: Kornos?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C3 Kornos?

label: Korope
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 E2 Korope

label: Korydallos
description: An Attic asty deme of the Hippothontis phyle.

label: Kos (settlement)
description: An ancient city, located on the Aegean island of the same name.

label: Kos/Cos (island)
description: A large island in the Aegean Sea, lying off the modern Turkish coast near Bodrum (ancient Halicarnassus).

label: Kotiaeion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 C3 Kotiaeion

label: Koukonesi
description: Koukonesi (or Koukonisi) is a small, coastal island in the Moudros harbour of Lemnos where important archaeological evidence for Bronze Age commerce has been discovered.

label: Kourion
description: An ancient settlement in the southern part of the island of Cyprus, located southwest of Episkopi in the Lemesos district.

label: Krannon/Ephyra
description: An ancient Thessalian settlement, with evidence of occupation in the area stretching back to the Neolithic.

label: Krenides/Philippi/Col. Augusta Iulia Philippensis
description: An ancient city founded as Philippi by the king of Macedon, Philip II of Macedon on the site of the Thasian colony of Krinides.

label: Krete
description: Krete was a Late Roman province in the Diocese of Macedonia of the Praetorian prefecture of Illyricum.

label: Krios (river)
description: A small river of the northern Peloponnese, draining into the Corinthian Gulf between Aigeira (modern Vitrinitsa) and Aristonautai (modern Xylokastro). The modern Fonissa in the Greek municipality of Xylokastro.

label: Krokeai
description: Krokeai was a settlement in southern Laconia.

label: Krokodilopolis/Ptolemais Euergetis
description: An ancient city in the Heptanomis and the capital of Arsinoites nome. The ancient Egyptian name of the site was Shedyet and in Pharaonic times it was a major cult center for the god Sobek.

label: Kruishoutem
description: An ancient settlement (name unknown) located at modern Kruishoutem in Belgium.

label: Kuntillat 'Ajrud
description: A late ninth to early eighth century BC site located in the northeastern part of the Sinai peninsula, the fortress-like Kuntillat ‘Ajrud may have been a sanctuary. Hebrew and Phoenician inscriptions have been identified at the site.

label: Kydonia
description: An ancient settlement on Crete inhabited since the Neolithic period, Kydonia has been a major center of Minoan, Greek, and Byzantine civilization.

label: Kyllene
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 A2 Kyllene

label: Kyllene (mountain)
description: A mountain in Arcadia (Greece), still known as Kyllene today.

label: Kyparissia
description: Kyparissia was an ancient settlement of Messenia.

label: Kypros
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 F4 no. 44 (Kypros)

label: Kyrros
description: An ancient settlement of Macedonia, probably to be located south of the modern village of Aravisos at the site of a now-abandoned small town known in the 19th century as Palaiokastro. Some scholars have also proposed its equation with an attested mutatio Scurio on the Via Egnatia, but the latter, despite a probable relationship with Kyrros, is more likely to be found further south.

label: Kyrthanion
description: An ancient place, cited: None

label: Kythera (settlement)
description: An ancient settlement on the Aegean island of the same name. Its acropolis was probably at the site now known as Palaikastro.

label: Kythnos
description: The chief, homonymous city on the Cycladic island of Kythnos (modern Vriokastro/Episkopi).

label: Kythnos (island)
description: Kythnos is an island in the Aegean Sea and one of the Cyclades.

label: Kāśī
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 E4 Kāśī

label: Kāšān
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Kȧbul
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: La Graufesenque
description: La Graufesenque is the name of an archaeological site located in southern France at the point of the confluence of the Tarn and Dourbie rivers. The archaeological site is across the river valley from Millau, known in antiquity at Condatomagus. The site was famous for its large-scale production of high quality red terra sigillata pottery. This was produced in enormous quantities and exported across the western Roman world. Production of this type began in the reign of Augustus.

label: La Villeneuve-au-Châtelot
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D4 La Villeneuve-au-Châtelot

label: Lac(c)obriga
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B4 Lac(c)obriga

label: Lacedaemon/Laconia
description: Lacedaemon/Laconia is a region comprising the south-eastern part of the Peloponnese.

label: Lachish
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Lachish

label: Lacobriga
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 G2 Lacobriga

label: Lactora
description: Lactora was the capital of the civitas of the Lactorates.

label: Ladesta (island)
description: Ladesta (modern Lastovo) is a part of ancient Liburnia in the Adriatic Sea.

label: Lagash
description: Lagash was an important Sumerian city of the late third millennium B.C.

label: Lago dell'Accesa (lake)
description: Lago dell'Accesa is a lake located in the Colline Metallifere.

label: Lake Stymphalia
description: A lake located in the northeastern part of the Peloponnese in Greece.

label: Lalonquette
description: A Gallo-Roman villa that is expanded upon the second and third centuries A.D.

label: Lambaesis
description: A Roman settlement established in the second century A.D. as the legionary base of Legio III Augusta.

label: Lambdia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 30 E4 Lambdia

label: Lamia
description: An ancient settlement of Phthiotis, modern Lamia.

label: Lancaster
description: Roman fort at present day Lancaster.

label: Langon
description: Modern Langon is a commune located in the Ille-et-Vilaine department of Brittany in northwestern France. Various archaeological remains from the Roman period survive there, including paved roads, the remains of a villa, and the so-called Chapelle Sainte-Agathe.

label: Lansargues
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 C2 Lansargues

label: Lanuéjols
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 B5 Lanuéjols

label: Laodicea
description: Laodicea or Laodicea ad Mare (modern Lattakia, Syria) is an ancient city with significant Punic, Greek, and Roman phases.

label: Laodicea ad Libanum
description: Laodicea ad Libanum was a Hellenistic city located on the Orontes River in Coele-Syria.

label: Lapethos/Lepethis Phoinikon
description: Located on the north coast of Cyprus 10 km west of Keryneia, Lapethos/Lepethis Phoinikon is known through archaeological remains for the most part. Archaeological evidence shows settlement already in the Late Bronze Age, continuing to the first millennium BCE and beyond. The tradition of Lapethos holds that the kingdom was founded by Praxandros from Lakonia in the Peloponnese.

label: Lapidaria?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 B3 Lapidaria?

label: Lapurdum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 D2 Lapurdum

label: Laranda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 66 C2 Laranda

label: Largo di Torre Argentina
description: A square in the Campus Martius of Rome, at the center of which lies an archaeological site that includes the remains of four temples of the Republican period, as well as elements of the first century B.C. theater complex of Cnaeus Pompeius.

label: Larinum
description: A settlement of Apulia that originated with the Samnites and Frentani and later came under Roman influence. During the Second Punic War, the Romans defeated Hannibal at Larinum. The settlement eventually gained Roman municipal status.

label: Larinum Roman amphitheater
description: An amphitheater of the first century A.D.

label: Larisa Kremaste/Pelasgia
description: An ancient settlement of Achaea Phthiotis, located in the area of the modern town of Pelasgia in Greece.

label: Larissa
description: The ancient capital of the Thessalian Pelasgiotis, modern Larisa in Greece.

label: Larissa/Sizara
description: An ancient settlement located on the Orontes river to the southeast of Apamea. Scholars identify it with modern Shaizar in Syria.

label: Larius/Comacinus L.
description: Larius/Comacinus L. (Lake Como)

label: Larsa
description: Larsa (modern Tell as-Senkereh), a city located ca. 21 km east of Uruk, was an important southern Mesopotamian cult center of the sun-god (Utu/Šamaš). Its principal religious structure was called Ebabbar, just like the Šamaš temple in the northern Babylonian city of Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial names of some of Larsa’s other religious buildings are mentioned in two first-millennium-BC lists of ziggurats and some royal inscriptions, especially from the Isin-Larsa Period (ca. 2025–1763 BC) — when the city of Larsa temporarily became a dominant political power (ca. 1924–1763 BC) — and the Neo-Babylonian Period. The most important of these, at least in the sixth century BC, was the temple tower Edurana, which sometimes went by the name Eduranki. At the beginning of the second millennium BC (ca. 1924 BC), under a man called Gungunum (r. 1932–1906 BC), Larsa broke free of Isin’s dominance over it and established its political dynasty. Although it grew more powerful than its former overlord, Larsa never accumulated a significant amount of territory. At its peak, under the authority of Rīm-Sîn I (r. 1822–1763 BC), it controlled only ten to fifteen other city-states. This city’s political dominance, as well as its dynastic line, was brought to an end by Hammu-rāpi of Babylon (r. 1792–1750 BC). After 1763 BC, Larsa was never again a major political player in Babylonia.

label: Larymna (Boeotia)
description: Located on the Gulf of Euboea, Larymna was a town of eastern Locris.

label: Lateran Basilica, Palace, and Castra Nova equitum singularium
description: Site of a basilica and palace from early Roman imperial times, as well as an military installation built by Septimius Severus for the Roman imperial cavalry bodyguard. Now the site of the Archbasilica of St. John Lateran (rebuilt in the 16th century): Complesso dei San Giovanni in Laterano (Basilica, Palazzo Apostolico Lateranense, edifici annessi) Holy See; listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1990.

label: Lato
description: Lato was an ancient city of Crete, a Dorian city-state located on Mirabello Bay. The principal ruins date to the fifth and fourth centuries B.C. and the city was destroyed ca. 200 B.C.

label: Latopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 80 B3 Latopolis

label: Latresne
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E4 no. 122 (Pannetier, Cm. Latresne)

label: Lattara
description: A walled port city inhabited by Gauls, Etruscans, and Massalian Greeks.

label: Lauriacum
description: An ancient Roman fortification at the confluence of the modern Enns and Danube rivers, with associated settlement.

label: Laus Pompeia
description: Laus Pompeia is an ancient city located in Transpadane Gaul. It was situated along the road between Mediolanum and Placentia. Modern Lodi Vecchio.

label: Lavi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 Lavi

label: Le Rozier
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I4 Le Rozier

label: Lebadeia
description: Lebadeia was an ancient settlement located close to the western frontier of Boeotia.

label: Lechaion
description: The port of ancient Corinth.

label: Ledroi/Leuke Ousia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C2 Ledroi/Leuke Ousia

label: Legio VII Gemina
description: The Roman Legio VII Gemina was based in Tarraconensis and gave its name to the settlement. This ancient place is now León, Spain, which is built atop the ancient settlement.

label: Legio/Caporcotani/Maximianopolis
description: The ancient site of Legio was a Roman military camp located south of Tel Megiddo in the Roman province of Galilee. Legio VI Ferrata was stationed there following the Bar Kokhba revolt.

label: Lemnos (island)
description: A large volcanic island in the northern Aegean Sea. Lemnos appears frequently in Greek myth, not least as the crash-landing place of the god Hephaestos (Vulcan) when he was thrown from Mount Olympus by Zeus for attempting to protect his mother Hera.

label: Lentia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 H4 Lentia

label: Lenzburg
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 F2 Lenzburg

label: Leonforte
description: A modern Sicilian town in the province of Enna, thought to be located in the area of the ancient settlement of Assorus.

label: Leontini
description: A Greek colonial city founded by Naxians in 729 B.C., Leontini was reduced by Hippocrates of Gela in 498 B.C. Following the Sicilian Expedition, the city became subject to Syracuse. In Roman times it may have been of little importance and was destroyed by the Saracens in A.D. 848.

label: Lepreon
description: An ancient city of Elis.

label: Lerna
description: Lerna was an ancient settlement on the east coast of the Peloponnesus. Extensive Bronze Age layers were excavated in the twentieth century by J. L. Caskey.

label: Leros
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D3 Leros

label: Leros (island)
description: One of the Sporades, ca. 40 km from the coast of Caria.

label: Les Martys
description: A center of mining and ore processing.

label: Lesbos (island)
description: Lesbos is an island of the northeastern Aegean Sea and was named for the son of Lapithos, the descendant of Deucalion and Helen.

label: Lete
description: Lete was a strategically located city of ancient Macedonia.

label: Letopolis
description: Letopolis was an ancient Egyptian city. It served as the capital of the second nome of Lower Egypt.

label: Leuca/Portus Sallentinus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 inset Leuca/Portus Sallentinus

label: Leucas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C4 Leucas

label: Leucas (island)
description: The ancient Ionian island of Leucas is known today as Lefkada.

label: Leuke
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 F3 Leuke

label: Leuke (island)
description: Leuke, now Koufonísi, is a small, rocky island southeast of Crete that in antiquity was a center for the production of the purple dye derived from from the gastropod Murex trunculus.

label: Leukolla?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 E2 Leukolla?

label: Leukos Limen
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 A2 Leukos Limen

label: Leuktra
description: Leuktra was a settlement located in ancient Boeotia. It was located along the road leading from Thespiae to Plataea, somewhere in the vicinity of the modern town. In 371 B.C. the Thebans defeated the Spartans in a celebrated battle near the site.

label: Leuktron
description: Leuktron was an ancient settlement in the southern Peloponnese. Pausanias places it twenty stades from Pephnus.

label: Lezoux
description: Lezoux was an important industrial center for the production of central Gaulish Terra sigillata pottery.

label: Libanus M.
description: A mountain range of northern Syria that is between the Mediterranean coastline and the Antilibanos mountains of the interior.

label: Libarna
description: Libarna was a Roman city located in Liguria.

label: Library of Hadrian at Athens
description: The Library of Hadrian is located on the north side of the Athenian Acropolis, immediately to the north of the Roman Agora. The Roman emperor Hadrian built the complex in A.D. 131/2. It was subsequently destroyed during the Herulian sack of Athens in A.D. 267.

label: Liffol-le-Grand
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F4 Liffol-le-Grand

label: Liguria (region)
description: Liguria is a coastal region of northwest Italy.

label: Lilaia
description: Ancient Lilaia (modern Kato Agoriani/Pyrgos in Greece) was an ancient Phocean city.

label: Lilybaeum
description: Lilybaeum (modern Marsala) is located at the extreme westernmost point of Sicily. Lilybaeum was a Punic settlement that was conquered by the Romans in 241 B.C.

label: Limen to Kaisareiou
description: A harbor constructed in Constantinople during the reign of Theodosius I; thirty-seven Byzantine-era shipwrecks have been excavated from the harbor site.

label: Limnaia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 D4 Limnaia

label: Limnias?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 38 D1 Limnias?

label: Limonum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F2 Limonum

label: Limyra
description: An ancient settlement located at modern Yuvalılar in the district of Finike, Antalya province, Turkey.

label: Lindinis
description: A Roman fort is thought to have been established at Lindinis (modern Ilchester) ca. 60 CE. The site protected the crossing of the Fosse Way over the River Yeo. The settlement developed in phases from the first to the fourth centuries CE. It was eventually one of only two known settlements with a stone wall in the territory of the Durotriges. The inhabitants of the town seem to have been reasonably wealthy, as a number of domestic complexes have fine mosaic pavements.

label: Lindos
description: Lindos is an ancient city located on the island of Rhodes.

label: Lipara (island)
description: An island in the Tyrrhenian Sea, north of Sicily. Modern Isola Lipari.

label: Lipara (settlement)
description: A Greek colony and long-time settlement on the island of the same name, located to the north of Sicily in the Tyrrhenian Sea. Modern Lipari.

label: Lissa (island)
description: An island in the Adriatic, known today as Ugljan/Ugliano.

label: Lissos
description: An ancient settlement and harbor on the southwest coast of the island of Crete at Ag. Kyrkos.

label: Litanobriga?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C3 Litanobriga?

label: Lixus
description: Lixus was an ancient settlement of Mauretania Tingitana. It was founded as a Punic port settlement as early as the eighth century B.C. Under the Roman emperor Claudius Lixus was elevated to the rank of colonia.

label: Lo(a)cus Felicis?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 H4 Lo(a)cus Felicis?

label: Lobera
description: A Spanish village located in the northwest of the province of Jaén, between Jaén and Córdoba, that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Lopera.

label: Lobeton
description: A now unlocated site that was the center of the Lobetani in ancient Iberia.

label: Locoteiacus
description: A Benedictine abbey that is located 7 km south of Poitiers and was founded by Martin from 361 to 371.

label: Lokroi Epizephyrioi
description: Locri is a town and comune in the province of Reggio Calabria, Calabria, in southern Italy. Epizephyrian Locris was founded ca. 680 BC near modern Capo Zefirio, by the Locrians, apparently under the Opuntii (East Locrians) from the city of Opus, but also including Ozolae (West Locrians) and Lacedaemonians.

label: Londinium/Augusta
description: Roman London was established ca. A.D. 43.

label: Longaticum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Longaticum

label: Longovicium
description: A Roman fort at present-day Lanchester.

label: Longuich
description: Roman villa urbana in Longuich

label: Lopadusa (island)
description: The largest of the Pelagie Islands in the Mediterranean Sea, Lopadusa has long served as a maritime base beginning with Punic occupation in the first millennium BC.

label: Lopodunum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 12 B3 Lopodunum

label: Los Pedroches
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F3 Los Pedroches

label: Loupiac
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E4 no. 141 (Loupiac)

label: Luca
description: Luca (the modern Lucca) was originally an Etruscan settlement that became a Roman colony ca. 180 B.C.

label: Lucena
description: A Spanish village located in the south of the province of Córdoba that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Lucentum
description: Lucentum was a Phoenician and then Roman settlement in Tarraconensis that was largely abandoned after the third century.

label: Luceria/Noukeria (Apoulon)
description: Luceria/Noukeria (Apoulon) was originally a Daunian city. It was named as a Colonia Togata in 320 B.C. and came to play a significant role in the Second Punic War. Constans II sacked the town in A.D. 663.

label: Lucurgentum
description: An ancient city in Hispania Baetica.

label: Lucus Augusti
description: Lucus Augusti (Lugo, Spain). The Roman walls of the city were listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

label: Ludn(...)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H1 Ludn(...)

label: Lugdunum Convenarum
description: Lugdunum Convenarum (modern Saint-Bertrand-de-Comminges) was founded by Cnaeus Pompeius as a Roman colony in 72 BC. The site defended the Aran valley and the approaches to Iberia.

label: Luna
description: Luna (the modern Luni) is an ancient settlement of Liguria. It was re-founded by the Romans as a colonial settlement in 177 BC.

label: Lupia(e)
description: A settlement of the indigenous Messapii that was refounded under Roman influence in the third century B.C.

label: Lusitania
description: The Late Roman province of Lusitania remained relatively stable in terms of administration under Diocletian. In 298 CE, Lustiania was reorgznied as part of the Diocesis Hispaniarum.

label: Lusitania
description: The province of the Roman Empire known as Lusitania. This ancient place was included on map 100 of the Barrington Atlas, representing the provinces of the Roman Empire as organized at the time of the death of the emperor Trajan in 117 CE.

label: Lusitania (region)
description: An ancient region that took its name from an Iberian people (the "Lusitani"), who originally occupied an area between the Tagus and Durius rivers. The Romans applied the name to the later, much larger, province.

label: Lutetia
description: Lutetia (modern Paris) was the capital of the Parisii, a tribe of ancient Gaul.

label: Luteva/*Forum Neronis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 A2 Luteva/*Forum Neronis

label: Lycia et Pamphylia
description: The Roman province of Lycia and Pamphylia after the Verona List (303-324 AD) (BAtlas 101 M4 Lycia et Pamphylia).

label: Lycia et Pamphylia
description: "Lycia et Pamphylia" was a province of the Roman Empire. Vespasian created the province by merging Lycia and Pamphylia into a single administrative division. Prior to Vespasian's reign, Claudius had annexed Lycia (43 CE) while Pamphylia was once a part of the province of Galatia.

label: Lydda/Diospolis/Georgioupolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Lydda/Diospolis/Georgioupolis

label: Lykopolis/Siout
description: A city of the west bank of the Nile, Lykopolis/Siout was the capital of the Thirteenth Nome of Upper Egypt (Lycopolites Nome) around 3100 B.C.

label: Lykos (river)
description: An ancient river in Pontus, known today as Kelkit Çayı.

label: Lykosoura
description: A city of Arcadia and home of the cult of Despoina

label: Lykouria?
description: According to Pausanias, Lykouria? is located in Arcadia and marks the boundary between Pheneus and Cleitor.

label: Lyktos
description: An ancient settlement on Crete, located just east of modern Xydas/Xidas, with which it is sometimes conflated. The city is mentioned in Homer and seems to have flourished in Hellenistic and Roman times, at least.

label: Lyons-la-Forêt
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B3 Lyons-la-Forêt

label: Lysimacheia
description: An ancient city in Aetolia, located 3km south of the modern city that now bears its name.

label: L’Ecluse
description: Remains of fortifications dating to the Late Roman period.

label: L’Escale
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 B1 L’Escale

label: Maadi
description: A Predynastic settlement located on the eastern bank of the Nile on the outskirts of modern Cairo.

label: Macedonia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 L3 Macedonia

label: Macedonia (Roman province)
description: A province of the Roman empire, formed in the mid-second century BCE, becoming a senatorial province in the mid-first century CE.

label: Macoraba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 C5 Macoraba

label: Mactaris
description: A Numidian site that eventually became a Roman colony in the second century A.D.

label: Madaba
description: Madaba has a long settlement history. During the Roman period the city was part of the Trajanic province of Arabia.

label: Magarsa/Antiochia ad Pyramum
description: Magarsa was a settlement in eastern Cilicia, located on the Karataş Peninsula near the mouth of the river Pyramus. In the Hellenistic period, it was re-founded as Antiochia ad Pyramum.

label: Magdala/Taricheai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 C4 Magdala/Taricheai

label: Magdalensberg
description: An ancient settlement and emporium of the Celtic Kingdom of Noricum.

label: Magidû
description: Magidû or Megiddo (modern Tell al-Mutesellim, "The Tell of the Governor") is an ancient settlement mound located in northern Israel near Kibbutz Megiddo, about 30 km southeast of Haifa. Bronze Age Megiddo was an important Canaanite city-state and during the Iron Age, it was a royal city in the Kingdom of Israel. The site is mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources.

label: Magnesia ad Maeandrum/Leukophrys
description: Magnesia ad Maeandrum was an ancient city on the Maeander River in Ionia, site of an important sanctuary of Artemis Leukophryene ("of the white eyebrow"). Its extensive remains are located near the modern village of Tekin in Turkey's Aydın Province.

label: Maia
description: The Roman fort of Maia located at Bowness-on-Solway, was part of the Roman defenses supporting Hadrian's Wall along the Cumbrian coast.

label: Maiden Castle, Dorset
description: One of the largest and most complex Iron Age hillforts in Europe, Maiden Castle, in Dorset, was occupied from the Neolithic period through to the fourth century A.D.

label: Maipa/Martyropolis/Ioustinianopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D2 Maipa/Martyropolis/Ioustinianopolis

label: Makaria
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 D2 Makaria

label: Makna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 76 F5 Makna

label: Makra Kome
description: An ancient settlement and fortification in the upper Spercheios river valley, located near modern Varibopi in Greece.

label: Makyneia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B4 Makyneia

label: Malaca
description: A Roman city of Baetica that was perhaps founded by the Carthaginians in the fifth century BC. Modern Malaga, on the Mediterranean coast of Spain.

label: Malaca (river)
description: The modern Guadalmedina river, which debouches into the Mediterranean at modern Malaga, Spain (ancient Malaca)

label: Maliacus Sinus
description: Maliacus Sinus (Malian Gulf) is a gulf of the Aegean Sea in eastern central Greece. The gulf is located in the region of Phthiotis.

label: Manching
description: At modern Manching are the remains of a massive proto-urban Celtic settlement (oppidum) that reached its maximum size of ca. 380 ha during the late La Tène period (late second century BC). It is possibly to be identified with Vallatum, a civic entity mentioned in ancient sources.

label: Manduria
description: Manduria was a key Messapic center. Archidamus III, king of Sparta, fell there in 338 B.C. while leading the army of Taras.

label: Mantineia/Antigoneia
description: Mantineia/Antigoneia was an ancient settlement in Greece most noted for being the site of two major battles. The First Battle of Mantineia was the largest land battle of the Peloponnesian War (418 B.C.) and the Second Battle of Mantineia brought an end to Theban hegemony (362 B.C.).

label: Mantoche
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 C2 Mantoche

label: Mantua
description: Mantua (modern Mantova) is a city of Etruscan origin that received Roman citizenship in 49 B.C.

label: Manṣuāte
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the name of the place in Egyptian sources is Mnḏt. Manṣuāte is probably to be identified with modern Maṣyāf (Maṣyāt).

label: Maon/Menoeis/Castrum Moenoenum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 E3 Maon/Menoeis/Castrum Moenoenum

label: Marathon
description: Marathon was a coastal deme of the tribe Aiantis, in northeastern Attica, the site of the Battle of Marathon in 490 BC, and capital of the Marathon tetrapolis.

label: Marchena
description: A Spanish village located in the east of the province of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Marde/Margdis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 C3 Marde/Margdis

label: Mareotis (lake)
description: A brackish lake of Lower Egypt (now Lake Mariout).

label: Margerides
description: Remains of a large religious complex, consisting of a fanum, two small subsidiary structures, and three altars.

label: Mariana
description: Mariana was a Roman city on the east coast of Corsica founded by Caius Marius ca. 93 BC.

label: Marion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 A2 Marion

label: Marmarion
description: An ancient settlement and associated marble quarries on the island of Euboea.

label: Maroneia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 F3 Maroneia

label: Marsonia
description: An ancient settlement at modern Slavonski Brod in Croatia.

label: Marta (river)
description: The Marta river flows from Lake Bolsena to the Tyrrhenian Sea. Its course flows past both Tuscania and Tarquinia and enters the Tyrrhenian Sea near Lido di Tarquinia.

label: Martelange
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F3 Martelange

label: Marukh Pass
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 G1 Marukh Pass

label: Masada
description: Masada is a natural fortress in the Iudaean desert that overlooks the Dead Sea. It was the site of the standoff between Jewish rebels and the Roman army in A.D. 73. Herod the Great built a palace atop the citadel during his reign. Roman camps and siege works are still visible at the site, which is listed on the UNESCO World Heritage List.

label: Massalia/Massilia
description: Massalia/Massilia (modern Marseille, France) was founded by Phocaean Greeks ca. 600 B.C. as a trading outpost. Massalia, in turn, established its own secondary colonies. During the Punic Wars Massalia, was allied to Rome and, following the sacking of Carthage in 146 B.C., the settlement enjoyed increased economic vitality.

label: Matalon
description: An ancient settlement and port on the south coast of Crete, now identified at modern Matala. Excavations have revealed an acropolis, tombs, a maritime slipway for a shipshed, a quarry, and fish tanks.

label: Mathis (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 B2 Mathis fl.

label: Matisco
description: A settlement in the territory of the Aedui mentioned by Caesar.

label: Matiātu
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that is identified with modern Midyat. Midyat originated as a Hurrian settlement in the third millennium B.C.

label: Matrona (river)
description: The Marne river.

label: Maubeuge
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D2 Maubeuge

label: Mauretania
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 B4 Mauretania

label: Mauretania Caesariensis (Roman province)
description: A Roman imperial province.

label: Mausoleum Augusti
description: A monumental tomb built in the Campus Martius at Rome by Augustus and dedicated in 28 B.C. The mausoleum served as a family tomb for the Iulio-Claudians.

label: Mausoleum of Caecilia Metella
description: A tomb on the Via Appia south of Rome belonging to Caecilia Metella, a daughter of Metellus Creticus. She was born ca. 100 BC. In 1303, the tomb was incorporated into the Castrum Caetani, serving as the main tower of the fortification.

label: Mausoleum of Lucius Munatius Plancus
description: A Roman mausoleum that is associated with Lucius Munatius Plancus.

label: Maxula
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 F3 Maxula

label: Mazaka/Eusebeia/Caesarea
description: Mazaka/Eusebeia/Caesarea was the chief town of Cappadocia, modern Kayseri.

label: Mazara
description: An ancient settlement located on the western coast of Sicily.

label: Mašhad
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Māri
description: Mari (Tell Hariri) was an ancient Semitic city that flourished as a trade center and hegemonic state between 2900 BC until 1759 BC. The site was submitted as a tentative candidate for the UNESCO World Heritage list in 1999.

label: Medinet Habu
description: The New Kingdom mortuary temple of Ramesses III at Medinet Habu, on the West bank of the Nile near Luxor.

label: Mediolan(i)um
description: A Celtic settlement and crossroads, later a Western Roman capital. Now modern Milan, Italy.

label: Mediolanum
description: A town of southwest Gaul founded ca. 20 BC, Mediolanum Santonum was connected with the Roman road network that served Burdigala.

label: Mediolanum
description: An ancient settlement, located in the modern French commune of Châteaumeillant.

label: Mediolanum Aulercorum
description: Mediolanum Aulercorum was the chief town of the Aulerci Eburovices.

label: Megale/Pityodes/Prinkipos Ins.
description: Megale/Pityodes/Prinkipos Ins. (Büyükada)

label: Megalopolis
description: An ancient settlement in Arcadia in the Peloponnese, likely founded in the 4th century BCE. The site lies just to the northeast of the modern town of Megalopolis.

label: Megara
description: Megara was an important ancient city of Greece, located in the northern part of the the Isthmus of Corinth opposite the island of Salamis.

label: Megiste (island)
description: Megiste Ins. (modern Kastellorizo) is the easternmost Greek island. In antiquity, it was colonized by Dorian Greeks.

label: Megiste (settlement)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 C5 Megiste

label: Mehring
description: Roman villa rustica in Mehring

label: Melas (river)
description: The ancient name for the Manavgat River (Manavgat Nehri) in Turkey.

label: Melas (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 C4 Melas fl. (1)

label: Melita
description: A capital town founded by Carthaginians.

label: Melita/Malta (island)
description: The island of Malta, located in the Mediterranean Sea between Sicily and Libya.

label: Melitene
description: Melitene was an ancient city on the Tohma River. It was the station of Legio XII Fulminata from AD 70 onwards.

label: Melos (island)
description: Melos is a volcanic island in the Cyclades and in prehistoric times served as an important source of obsidian in the Aegean Sea. Substantial remains of Bronze Age and Greco-Roman civilizations have been excavated on the island.

label: Melos (settlement)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 G4 Melos

label: Melta
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 B5 Melta

label: Memphis
description: A city and capital of Ancient Egypt that remained an important center for most of Egyptian history.

label: Menai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 Menai

label: Mendes
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 F3 Mendes

label: Meninx/Lotophagitis/Girba (island)
description: Meninx/Lotophagitis/Girba Ins. (modern Djerba) is the largest island of North Africa.

label: Meroe
description: Meroë is an ancient city located on the east bank of the Nile river near Shendi, Sudan. The city was a center of the kingdom of Kush.

label: Meron
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 Meron

label: Meschistha
description: Meschistha (modern Mtskheta (Georgian: მცხეთა)) is an ancient city in Georgia and was the capital of the Hellenistic kingdom of Iberia. Meschistha became a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1994.

label: Mese (island)
description: Modern Gramvousa island off the northwest coast of Crete.

label: Mesembria
description: Originally a Thracian site known as Menebria, Mesembria was subsequently settled by Dorian Greeks in the early sixth century BC, eventually becoming an important trading colony on the Black Sea coast (modern Nesebar, Bulgaria). Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983.

label: Messene
description: Capital of Messenia

label: Mesua
description: A Pre-Roman settlement located north of the Étang de Thau.

label: Metapa
description: According to Polybius, this ancient settlement of Aetolia was razed by Philip of Macedon. Stephanus of Byzantium places Metapa in Acarnania. Pritchett (SAGT) meticulously describes the vicinity and identifies the site of Metapa based on ancient stone blocks in conditions of reuse and abandonment, as well as plentiful ceramic sherds in the vicinity of an older and modern church of the Analipsis on the lake shore just east of the modern village of Daphnias.

label: Metapontum
description: An important city of Magna Graecia, Metapontum was located on the Gulf of Tarentum. The Achaeans were responsible for its foundation, perhaps as early as the eighth century B.C.

label: Methana/Arsinoe
description: Methana/Arsinoe refers to a peninsula and settlement located on the north coast of the Argolid. In geological terms, the peninsula is formed by relatively recent volcanic activity, with the last-known eruptive activity in the third century BCE. Human activity on the peninsula spans many periods. The chief polity was located in the southwest of the peninsula where the modern village of Megalochori is found today.

label: Methone (Pieria)
description: An ancient settlement in Macedonian Pieria on a hilltop named Koryphi, near modern Nea Agathoupolis in the Pydna-Kalindros municipality in Pieria, Greece. The site was occupied from the Late Neolithic period (ca. 4000 BCE) through 354 BCE, when it was destroyed by the armies of Philip II. It was succeeded by a new settlement approximately 1km to the northwest; known as Macedonian Methone, this later settlement was occupied in the Hellenistic and Roman periods.

label: Methone/Mothone (Messenian)
description: An ancient settlement sited on the west coast of the Messenian peninsula of the Peloponnese. The collocated modern settlement is called Methoni and is located in the administratively part of the Pylos-Nestoras municipality, Messenia regional unit, of the modern Greek state.

label: Methora
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 D4 Methora

label: Methymna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Methymna

label: Metropolis (Thessaly)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B2 Metropolis

label: Midea
description: An ancient site in the Argolid in Greece, it shares a name with the neighboring modern town.

label: Milatos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 E2 Milatos

label: Miletus
description: A major ancient city in Ionia.

label: Misenum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Misenum

label: Modicia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 E2 Modicia

label: Modiin
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Modiin

label: Moesia Inferior
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 M3 Moesia Inferior

label: Moger
description: A Spanish village located in the east of Huelva that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. While there is on-site evidence for long-term human activity since antiquity, the present settlement, known in modern terms as Moguer, is traditionally said to have been founded in 1333 by the Señorío de Moguer ("Seigneury of Moguer").

label: Mogontiacum
description: The original Roman settlement at Mogontiacum (modern Mainz) was established by Drusus ca. 13/12 BC. The settlement became an important military center throughout Roman times and was the base of operations for numerous Roman legions.

label: Molibodes (island)
description: Molibodes Ins. (Isola di Sant'Antioco)

label: Mona (island)
description: Mona Ins. (Isle of Anglesey or Ynys Môn) is an island off the northwest coast of Wales.

label: Montana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 F6 Montana

label: Montans
description: Montans was one of the largest and oldest centers for the production of Gallo-Roman terra sigillata pottery.

label: Montbouy
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 H1 Montbouy

label: Montcaret
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F4 no. 117 (Montcaret)

label: Monte Amiata
description: Monte Amiata is a lava dome located about 20 km northwest of Lake Bolsena in Italy.

label: Monte Artesino di Nicosia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Monte Artesino di Nicosia

label: Monte Falterona
description: A peak of the Tuscan-Romagnolo Apennines, rising to 1,654 m. above sea level, Monte Falterona is the source of the Arno River and shows evidence of Etruscan occupation.

label: Monte Saraceno di Ravanusa (Kakyron?)
description: The ancient city of Kakyron, said to have been founded by the Sicani in the eighth century B.C., is probably to be identified with the remains of a fortified city, north of Licata, located on the western side of Sicily.

label: Montmaurin
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 Montmaurin

label: Mopsou(h)estia/Seleukeia pros to Pyramo
description: Mopsou(h)estia/Seleukeia pros to Pyramo was an ancient settlement in Cilicia Pedias (now modern Yakapınar, Turkey).

label: Mor(o)unda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 H2 Mor(o)unda

label: Mora
description: A Spanish village that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Moura, and is located in the country of Portugal, across the border from the Spanish cities of Huelva and Badajoz.

label: Morgantina
description: An indigenous Sicilian site founded by the Morgeti, according to Strabo, Morgantina was eventually defeated by Syracuse and thus, in turn, passed into Roman hegemony in the third century B.C.

label: Morlanwelz
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E2 Morlanwelz

label: Mortuum Mare/Asphaltitis Limne
description: The modern "Dead Sea", which is bordered by Israel, Jordan, and the West Bank.

label: Mosomagus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F3 Mosomagus

label: Mosul/‘Mespila’?
description: An ancient city located across the Tigris River from the site of Nineveh. Modern Mosul in Iraq.

label: Mothis
description: Mūṭ, known in antiquity as Mothis and today as Mūṭ al-Kharāb, a city of the Western Desert that served as a capital of the Dakhleh Oasis region since the Old Kingdom period. In the Late Antique period, it was the capital of the Mothite Nome.

label: Motya
description: A small island in the Stagnone Lagoon of western Sicily, Motya has evidence for quite ancient settlement, including a significant Punic phase. The settlement on the island was destroyed by Syracuse in 379 BC. At one point the island was connected to the mainland via a causeway.

label: Mount Judi
description: Mount Judi (also al-Ǧūdiyy, Cûdî‎, Cudi), also spelled Guti and Kutu, is a mountain where Sennacherib had several monuments carved. The Neo-Assyrian name is Mount Nipur.

label: Moysiacum
description: A place mentioned in passing in the Vita of Saint Desiderius. Modern scholars have identified it with modern Moissac in southern France where there are significant Merovingian and later medieval remains, some of which overlie structures of late Roman date.

label: Moza/Ammaous/Kolonia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 G2 Moza/Ammaous/Kolonia

label: Muccurum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E6 Muccurum

label: Mun. Vindobona
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 13 B4 Mun. Vindobona

label: Munda (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F4 Munda fl.

label: Munychia
description: A hill in the Piraeus and the site of extensive fortifications in the Classical and Hellenistic periods.

label: Murcia
description: A city located in southeastern Spain that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. The city on the present location was an Islamic foundation under the name Madinat Mursiyah and was established in A.D. 825 by Abd ar-Rahman II, the emir of Córdoba.

label: Mursa
description: Mursa was an ancient city on the Drava River and the site of a colonia Aelia Mursa, likely founded by Hadrian in AD 133. Traces of Neolithic and Iron Age cultures have also been discovered at the site.

label: Mursia
description: A modern village on the northwest coast of the Mediterranean island of Pantelleria. Mursia lies atop a settlement of late Bronze Age date that is associated with the cemetery (Sesi) that lies immediately to its south.

label: Murviel-lès-Montpellier
description: Murviel-lès-Montpellier was an oppidum with three circuit walls located 6 km north of the Via Domitia.

label: Mutina
description: Ancient Mutina (originally the Etruscan town Mutna), was first inhabited by Villanovans and later by Ligurians and the Gaulish Boii. The Boii sieged the city in 218 BC and later Mutina was re-established as a Roman colony (183 BC). It was an important city and played a role in the civil wars during the last decades of the Roman Republic.

label: Mutyce
description: Ancient settlement on the southern side of the Hyblean Mountains, between Syracuse and Camarina.

label: Muṣaṣir
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources. Although the city's exact location is not known, it has tentatively been identified with modern Mergasur, which is 10 km west of Topzawa.

label: Mycenae
description: Mycenae was an ancient settlement of the Argolid, with the earliest occupation evident ca. 2900 B.C. As the eponymous site of the Mycenaean culture of the Aegean Bronze Age, the site flourished as a fortified citadel during the mid to late second millennium B.C. In the first millennium B.C., the site experienced a revival of fortunes, although by Strabo's time the settlement had vanished.

label: Mycenaean cemetery at Aidonia
description: Mycenaean burial ground located approximately 8 kilometers west of Nemea containing 20 tombs dated to the 15th century BCE. All but two of the burials were looted in the 1970s, but the illicit finds were retrieved and repatriated to Greece in 1996.

label: Mykonos (island)
description: Mykonos is part of the Cyclades island group in the Aegean Sea.

label: Mykonos (settlement)
description: Homonymous settlement on the Aegean island of Mykonos.

label: Mylae
description: An ancient Greek settlement on the north-east coast of Sicily, located at the base of a peninsula that juts into the Tyrrhenian Sea. A colony of Zancle, it was probably founded in the eighth or seventh century BC. In 260 BC, during the First Punic War, the Romans won their first major naval battle against the Carthaginians in the waters off Mylae.

label: Mylasa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 F3 Mylasa

label: Mylasa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 F3 Mylasa (1)

label: Myle (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A1 Myle Ins.

label: Myos Hormos?
description: Myos Hormos was a port on the Red Sea built by the Ptolemies in the third century BC.

label: Myra
description: An ancient Lycian town

label: Myrina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 A2 Myrina

label: Myrkinos
description: A settlement of the Edones, conquered by the Persians and given to Histiaios of Miletos in 513 BC, then briefly colonised by Milesians after the Ionian Revolt. It was conquered by Macedon in 356 BC.

label: Mytilene
description: An ancient settlement. The early fortified core of the city was located on an islet off the east coast of Lesbos, now joined to the mainland. That site is dominated by the remains of a Byzantine fortress with Ottoman and Genoese repairs and additions. This original city later expanded onto the main island.

label: Nabataea (region)
description: Nabataea was an ancient region of Arabia inhabited by the Nabataeans. This region covers parts of northern Arabia and the Southern Levant, lying between Arabia and Syria, and stretching from the Euphrates river to the Red Sea.

label: Nabrissa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D5 Nabrissa

label: Nad-i Ali/Zarang?
description: A large site in modern Afghanistan's Nimruz province. Archaeological evidence is abundant for habitation during the third - first millennia BCE, as well as 8th - 13th centuries CE, when Nād ʿAlī was clearly a major fortified urban center.

label: Naeva
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E4 Naeva

label: Naissus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 D6 Naissus

label: Namur
description: Namur was a Gallo-Roman settlement (vicus) of the civitas Tungrorum.

label: Nape?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C3 Nape?

label: Napoca
description: Napoca (modern Cluj-Napoca) was an ancient Roman settlement established after the conquest of Dacia in A.D. 106. It became a provincial capital of Dacia Porolissensis and was abandoned in the late third century. Its name appears on the Roman milestone found in nearby Aiton.

label: Naqsh-i Rustam
description: An ancient necropolis located northwest of Persepolis.

label: Narona
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E6 Narona

label: Nasika
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 5 C3 Nasika

label: Nasium
description: A large ancient settlement located in the vicinity of modern Naix-aux-Forges and Saint-Armand-sur-Ornain in France. Excavations began in the 19th century and continued in the 20th.

label: Naucratis
description: Naucratis was a city of the Nile river delta, located on the Canopic branch. Capital of Ptolemaic Egypt, Naucratis was the site of permanent Greek habitation from the sixth century BC onward.

label: Naulochon/Smyrna/Palaia Smyrna
description: An ancient settlement located on the gulf of Smyrna, east of the town of Bayraklı (some 4 km north of Izmir, Turkey). Archaeological evidence indicates that the earliest Hellenic evidence dates to the eleventh or tenth centuries B.C.

label: Naupactus
description: Originally a city of the Ozolian Locrians, Naupactus eventually fell to Athens; under Macedonian rule Philip II ceded it to the Aetolians.

label: Nauplia
description: Although the Classical/Hellenistic city was deserted in Pausanias' day, archaeology reveals that the area of modern Nafplio and its natural harbor on the Argolic Gulf was repeatedly a site of habitation and human activity from the Neolithic period to the modern day. Remains of a Hellenistic acropolis wall have been identified under the later Byzantine (with subsequent accretions and modifications) fort.

label: Navia (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 E1 Navia fl.

label: Naxos (island)
description: Naxos is the largest of the Cycladic islands and was the center of the Cycladic civilization.

label: Naxos (settlement)
description: Settlement on the Aegean island of Naxos.

label: Naxos (settlement)
description: Naxos was the earliest Greek settlement in Sicily, according to Thucydides who places its foundation in 734 B.C.

label: Nazala
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 D5 Nazala

label: Nazareth
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 Nazareth

label: Neaition/Netum
description: Neaition/Netum was an ancient town in Sicily that likely became subject to Syracuse after 263 B.C.

label: Neapolis
description: After the sacking of Jerusalem, Vespasian settled Roman veterans on a new town site located between Mt. Gerizim and Mt. Ebal. The new Roman colony was built on the site of Mabartha.

label: Neapolis (Kavalla)
description: An ancient port city on the coast of Thrace, Neapolis (modern Kavalla in the Decentralized Administration of Macedonia and Thrace in Greece) was probably founded from Thasos in the seventh century CE. It served as the port for Philippi in Hellenistic and Roman times, and was refortified by Justinian in the sixth century CE.

label: Neapolis/Lepcis Magna
description: Originally a Phoenician colony founded ca. 1100 B.C., Lepcis Magna became a prominent Roman city and birthplace of the emperor Septimius Severus.

label: Neapolis/Theodosias
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C3 Neapolis/Theodosias

label: Necropolis of Pantalica
description: A large, rock-cut necropolis of over 5,000 tombs dating from the thirteenth to the seventh centuries BC.

label: Necropolis of Porta Ercolano
description: The Porta Ercolano necropolis, excavated between 1763 and 1838, is the best known of Pompeii's necropoleis, in use from the middle of the first century BC until the first century AD.

label: Nedon (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C3 Nedon fl.

label: Nemausus
description: Nemausus (modern Nîmes, France) was the ancient capital of the Volcae Arecomici and later a Roman colony.

label: Nemavand/Laodicea/Niphaunda
description: Nemavand/Laodicea/Niphaunda was an ancient city in Media founded by Darius the Great.

label: Nemea
description: Nemea, located north of Argos, was the site of the Panhellenic Games and the Sanctuary of Nemean Zeus.

label: Nemea (river)
description: Today an intermittent drainage known as the Nemeas or Zapantis that rises in the vicinity of ancient Nemea and flows north, emptying into the Corinthian Gulf near the modern village of Vrachati.

label: Nemetacum
description: Nemetacum was the principal center of the Atrebates.

label: Nemorensis (lake)
description: Nemorensis Lacus (modern Lake Nemi) is a small, volcanic lake in Latium located south of Rome. The lake is known for its adjacent sanctuary of the goddess Diana and for the recovery of several sunken Roman ships of the first century AD.

label: Nennig
description: The site of a Roman villa some 40 km upstream on the Moselle from Trier. The site was discovered in 1852 and was excavated between 1866 and 1876.

label: Nequinum/Narnia
description: Nequinum/Narnia (modern Narni) was an ancient settlement in Umbria. It became a Latin colony in 299 BC.

label: Nestane
description: An ancient fortified settlement in Arcadia.

label: New Basilica of Saint Apollinaris
description: A basilica in Ravenna, Italy, erected by Theodoric the Great in the first quarter of the sixth century AD.

label: Nicaea
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 D2 Nicaea

label: Nicephorium/Callinicum/Leontopolis
description: Nicephorium (modern ar-Raqqa in Syria) was an ancient settlement on the river Euphrates in Syria. It may be identical with Callinicum, which was renamed Leontopolis in the mid-fifth century CE.

label: Nicomedia
description: Nicomedia was founded in 712/11 BC as a Megarian colony named Astacus and was rebuilt by Nicomedes I of Bithynia in 264 BC. The city was an important administrative center of the Roman Empire.

label: Nicopolis ad Nestum/Ulpia Nicopolis
description: A settlement founded in Thrace to mark Trajan's victory in the Dacian Wars. It is located on the left bank of the Mesta river. Occupied through late antiquity, the site was destroyed by the seventh century and subsequently re-occupied by the late tenth century.

label: Nida
description: A Roman vicus, corresponding to the modern Frankfurt am Main-Heddernheim in Germany.

label: Nigrum Pullum
description: Nigrum Pullum was a castellum along the Roman frontier in Germania Inferior. The archaeological site is located in modern Zwammerdam in the Netherlands.

label: Nilus (river)
description: The Nile is a major river of northeastern Africa and is generally acknowledged as the longest river in the world, measuring some 6,650 km (4,130 miles) from source to mouth.

label: Nimrud
description: In the ninth century BC, Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883-859 BC) built himself a new administrative center. Kalhu (biblical Calah) — modern Nimrud, a site identified as Larissa, a city mentioned in Xenophon’s Anabasis — became the capital of the Assyrian Empire, replacing Ashur, which had served as Assyria’s capital since the third millennium BC. The city — which is located twenty miles south of the modern Mosul and which occupied a strategic position six miles north of the point where the Tigris River meets the Greater/Upper Zab — served as Assyria’s capital until the reign of Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC). Although Kalhu never again became the primary residence of Assyria’s kings, that city remained a vital administrative, military, and religious center until the fall of the Assyrian Empire.

label: Nineveh/Ninos
description: This important Mesopotamian city flanks the eastern edge of the Tigris flood plain, opposite modern Mosul, of which it is now a suburb. From the third millennium B.C. onwards, Nineveh was the most important religious center of the goddess Ištar in the area that would become the Assyrian heartland. Starting in the Middle Assyrian period, the city came under the authority of the kings of Assyria, who often sponsored large-scale building activities there. However, it was not until 704 B.C. that Nineveh became the administrative capital of Assyria when the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib moved the royal family and court there and transformed the city into a thriving imperial metropolis. Nineveh remained Assyria’s capital until 612 B.C., when it was captured and destroyed by a Babylonian-Median coalition led by Nabopolassar and Cyaxares. The visible remains of the (7th-century) Assyrian city include the citadel mound Kuyunjik, the smaller mound of Nebi Yunus, and the twelve-kilometer-long city wall.

label: Nippur/Nufar/‘Hippareni’
description: An ancient Sumerian settlement whose ruins lie at Nuffar in modern Iraq. Under various names it persisted as a settlement throughout the periods of Greek and Roman engagement in Babylonia.

label: Nirabu
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources. Nīrabu is equated with Aramaic nrb, classical Nērabos, and modern Nayrab.

label: Niriz/Narezzash?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 F4 Niriz/Narezzash?

label: Nisibis/Antiochia
description: Nisibis/Antiochia was an ancient city of Mesopotamia that began as part of an Aramaean kingdom that the Assyrian king Adad-Nirari II captured in 896 BC. Following its capture by Alexander the Great, the city became Antiochia Mygdonia under the Seleucids.

label: Nisyros (island)
description: A volcanic island in the Aegean Sea that is part of the Dodecanese group of islands.

label: Nisyros (settlement)
description: The eponymous settlement of the volcanic island of Nisyros in the Aegean Sea.

label: Noiodounon Diablintum
description: Noiodounon Diablintum is a settlement with significant extant remains, located at modern Jublains in France.

label: Noiodounon/Nu Dionnum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 G3 Noiodounon/Nu Dionnum

label: Nola
description: The city of Nola (Nuvlana) is considered one of the oldest in Campania. Under Augustus the settlement became a Roman colony; it was the spot where Augustus died in A.D. 14.

label: Nora
description: A pre-Roman and Roman site in southern Sardinia.

label: Norba
description: Norba, located in the Monti Lepini, was a member of the Latin League (ca. 499 B.C.) and became a Latin colony ca. 492 B.C. The city was destroyed in the early first century B.C.

label: Noricum (province)
description: A province of the Roman Empire at the death of Trajan (117 CE).

label: Novae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 C5 Novae

label: Novaesium
description: Novaesium (modern Neuss) was a Roman castrum along the German frontier (limes) founded ca. 16 B.C.

label: Novaria
description: A Roman municipium with an orthogonal plan.

label: Noviomagus
description: In Britannia, Noviomagus was the capital of the Regni. According to the Antonine Itinerary, Noviomagus was the first road station along the road from London to Durovernum.

label: Noviomagus Lexoviorum
description: Noviomagus Lexoviorum, located at the confluence of the Orbiquet and Touques rivers, was the chief settlement of the Lexovii.

label: Noviomagus/Nemetae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 I3 Noviomagus/Nemetae

label: Novioregum
description: An ancient road station, identified with the archaeological site at Barzan, in France.

label: Numana
description: Numana was a settlement of ancient Picenum located south of Ancona.

label: Numantia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 C4 Numantia

label: Nure (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 F4 Nure fl.

label: Obulco
description: Obulco was a Roman municipium of Hispania Baetica.

label: Ocriculum
description: An ancient Umbrian city that became allied with Rome in 308 B.C.

label: Octodurus/Forum Claudii Vallensium
description: Octodurus/Forum Claudii Vallensium (modern Martigny).

label: Ocules
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 C2 Ocules

label: Odessus
description: The ancient Black Sea settlement of Odessus is now Varna, Bulgaria.

label: Oea
description: Phoenicians established Oea in the seventh century B.C., and it later became a Roman–Berber colony. Modern-day Tripoli, Libya.

label: Oglasa (island)
description: Oglasa (Montecristo) is an island in the Tyrrhenian Sea and part of the Tuscan Archipelago.

label: Ohalo II
description: The archaeological site of Ohalo II is located near the Sea of Galilee. It is one of the best preserved hunter-gatherer archaeological sites dating to the Last Glacial Maximum. It has been dated, via radiocarbon, to 19,400 BP.

label: Oiasso
description: Oiasso was a settlement of the Vascones.

label: Oiniadai
description: A city at the former mouth of the Achelous river.

label: Oinoe (Attica)
description: An ancient fortified settlement and deme of Attica. The archaeological site is located to the east of modern Oinoe/Inoi (formerly Mazi).

label: Oinoe (Corinthia)
description: A fortress of the ancient Corinthia captured by Agesilaus II of Sparta in 390 B.C.

label: Oinophyta?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 F4 Oinophyta?

label: Oinousa (island)
description: The largest of the ancient Oinoussai islands, a small group of islands lying between the island of Chios and the Ionian peninsula.

label: Olbia
description: A Phoenician, Carthaginian, and Roman center in northeast Sardinia.

label: Oliaros (island)
description: Oliaros Ins. (modern Antiparos) is an inhabited island in the southern Aegean Sea and part of the Cyclades.

label: Olisipo
description: Olisipo (modern Lisbon, Portugal). Decimus Junius Brutus Callaicus pacified western Iberia and integrated the settlement into the Roman Republic in 138 BC.

label: Olympia
description: Ancient sanctuary of Zeus and home of the ancient Olympic games.

label: Olympos (mountain in Greece)
description: Olympus is the highest mountain in Greece, located in the Olympus Range. In Greek mythology, it is the home of the Olympian gods.

label: Olynthos
description: Olynthos was an ancient city of the Chalcidice, founded in the seventh century B.C. and destroyed in 348 B.C. by the forces of Philip II of Macedon.

label: Omboi
description: The Ptolemaic temple to Sobek and Horus the Elder at Kom Ombo.

label: Ophoven
description: Ophoven is the site of a Gallo-Roman vicus located along the left bank of the Meuse river between Tongres and Nijmegen.

label: Opitergium
description: Opitergium (modern Oderzo) is a settlement of the Veneti along the Piave River located at a junction of the Via Postumia.

label: Oplontis
description: An ancient place (modern Torre Annunziata in Italy), lying between Pompeii and Herculaneum and buried by the eruption of Vesuvius in 79 CE. Its ancient name is known only from Peutinger's Roman Map.

label: Orchomenos (Arcadia)
description: The so-called "Arcadian Orchomenos", located near a modern village in the Peloponnese that, until the 1960s, was known as Kalpaki.

label: Orchomenos/Orchomenus
description: The so-called "Boeotian Orchomenos", located in the vicinity of the Byzantine church of Panaghia Skripou. The longer, modern title is used to distinguish this settlement from another Greek site with the same ancient name located in Arcadia in the Peloponnese.

label: Ormi/[Urmia]
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 H3 Ormi/[Urmia]

label: Orolaunum
description: A large settlement (vicus) of the Treveri, located at modern Arlon in Belgium.

label: Oropos
