description: Oropos was an ancient settlement and port located on the border between Boeotia and Attica; the bulk of its Hellenistic - Roman remains are thought to underlie the modern village of Skala Oropou. Oropos was source of ongoing disputes in antiquity. Colonists from Eretria founded Oropos.

label: Orotan (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 B1 Orotan fl.

label: Ortona
description: An ancient site in Italy that most likely originates with the Frentani.

label: Ortygia (island)
description: A coastal island of Sicily that became the center of ancient Syracuse.

label: Osca/Urbs Victrix
description: Osca/Urbs Victrix (modern Huesca) was an Iberian oppidum and capital of the Ilergetes that later became a Roman colony.

label: Ossa (mountain)
description: A mountain in central Greece (between Olympus and Pelion), important in Greek mythology. Several ancient cities and a shrine to the Muses were located on its western slopes.

label: Ossonoba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 C4 Ossonoba

label: Osteria dell’Osa
description: The site of a major Iron Age necropolis (Latial chronology) composed of over 600 burials.

label: Ostia
description: The port city of ancient Rome located at the mouth of the river Tiber.

label: Ostra
description: Ostra was an ancient town of Umbria.

label: Oudenburg
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D1 Oudenburg

label: Ouergionios Okeanos
description: The Celtic Sea is a region of the Atlantic Ocean off the south coast of Ireland.

label: Ouindinon/Subdinnum
description: An ancient settlement at modern Le Mans in the French department of Sarthe.

label: Ourania
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 E1 Ourania

label: Oviedo
description: Founded in the eighth century, Oviedo was modeled after Toledo and flourished in the ninth century under Asturian King Alfonso II (791-842). It was at that time that Oviedo became the Asturian capital and an episcopal see. Oviedo remained prominent until the early tenth century.

label: Ovilava
description: A Celtic and subsequent Roman settlement at an important road junction and river crossing (modern Wels in Austria). The core of the ancient town, which evidently grew to significant size in the Roman period, is covered by the modern settlement and has only been selectively excavated.

label: Pachynum (promontory)
description: A promontory of extreme southeastern Sicily.

label: Pagasaeus/Demetriacus Sinus
description: The Pagasetic Gulf.

label: Paithana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 5 D3 Paithana

label: Palaestina (province)
description: Following the Bar Kokhba War, Hadrian abolished the name "Iudaea," renaming the province Palaestina. Under Diocletian, the area was divided into three provinces (Palaestina Prima, Secunda, and Tertia).

label: Palairos
description: A fortified ancient Greek city located in southern Epirus.

label: Palantia
description: The chief town of the Vaccaei in the northern part of Hispania Tarraconensis.

label: Palatinus Mons
description: The central hill of Rome, Italy. Legend held that Romulus founded the city of Rome on the Palatine Hill following an augural contest with Remus, his brother.

label: Pallantion
description: An ancient settlement located just west of the modern Greek city that has borne the ancient name since the 20th century (previously Berbati). Archaeological evidence confirms continuous habitation from the archaic through the Byzantine periods, and there is plentiful evidence in the surrounding area for activity beginning in the Mycenaean period.

label: Pallene
description: Pallene was an ancient mesogeia deme of the phyle Antiochis in Attica, located at Stavros in what is now the Gerakas suburb of Athens.

label: Palma
description: The site of Palma, on the island of Majorca, experienced multiple phases of settlement from Talaiotic to Roman.

label: Palmyra
description: Palmyra is an ancient oasis and trading city with monumental remains located in modern Syria. Under Zenobia, It was the capital of the breakaway Palmyrene Empire, which led to Aurelian razing the city. In 1980, Palmyra was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

label: Pan(h)ormus
description: First founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as Ziz, Pan(h)ormus (modern Palermo) was an important ancient city of the Greek, Roman, and Arabic civilizations.

label: Panakton
description: A fort located at the frontier between Attica and Boeotia, on the slopes of Mt. Cithaeron.

label: Pandataria (island)
description: An island in the Pontine archipelago of the Tyrrhenian Sea, Pandataria is volcanic in origin and is best known, in historical terms, as the place to which Augustus banished Julia the Elder, his daughter, in 2 BC and to which Tiberius banished Agrippina the Elder in AD 29.

label: Paneas/Caesarea Philippi
description: An ancient settlement at the southwest foot of Mount Hermon, located in the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights, just across the Lebanese border.

label: Pannonia
description: A province of the Roman Empire bounded on the north and east by the Danube, on the west by Noricum and upper Italy, and on the southward by Dalmatia and upper Moesia

label: Panopolis/Schmin
description: Capital city of the ninth (Chemmite) nome of Upper Egypt.

label: Panormos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 D4 Panormos

label: Panormos (Crete) / Aulopotamos?
description: Panormos was an ancient settlement and port of northern Crete, mentioned by Pliny. The Roman-era site was probably near and/or now covered by the destroyed remains of the 13th century Castel Milopotamo (Kastelli Mylopotamou) in modern Panormos. Aulopotamos, attested in late antiquity and thereafter as a bishop's seat, may refer to the same settlement and its region (the modern Mylopotamos river runs just south, emptying into the sea west of Panormos and finds of 7th and 8th century date have been excavated in the vicinity).

label: Panormos (Kalymna)
description: A bay, sheltered on the north and west by the island of Kalymna.

label: Pantelleria (island)
description: An island in the Strait of Sicily with human occupation dating back at least 35,000 years, Pantelleria has evidence for Bronze Age, Punic, Roman, Medieval, and modern phases. The Romans first acquired the island in 255 B.C. They called it Cossyra.

label: Pantheon
description: A temple in the Campus Martius of Rome that was first built by Marcus Agrippa (ca. 27-25 B.C.) and then re-built by the emperor Hadrian (after A.D. 126). In A.D. 609 the structure was consecrated as a Christian church, S. Maria ad Martyres.

label: Pantikapaion/Bosp(h)orus
description: The main city and port of the Kimmerian Bosporus, founded by Miletus in the late seventh or early sixth centuries B.C. Modern Kerch.

label: Paos
description: An ancient settlement of Arcadia. The remains of its acropolis (Paleokastro) lie on the Skoupitsi hill near modern Neon Paos.

label: Papa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 D3 Papa

label: Paphlagonia
description: The 5th/6th century AD Roman province as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 102 F3 no. 33 [Paphlagonia])

label: Paphlagonia
description: The Late Roman province as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 101 N3 Paphlagonia)

label: Paphlagonia
description: The Roman province as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 100 N3 Paphlagonia)

label: Paphlagonia (region)
description: The ancient region as defined in the Barrington Atlas (BAtlas 86 C2 Paphlagonia)

label: Paraetonium/Ammonia
description: The westernmost town of ancient Egypt.

label: Parapotamos
description: A tumulus/tell and associated necropolis in Epirus (Greece), with burials dating from the Hellenistic through post-Byzantine times.

label: Parentium
description: Ancient Parentium, now Poreč, Croatia, was a city on the western coast of the Istrian peninsula. There is archaeological evidence of Illyrian settlement from the Bronze Age onward. The site factors in Roman campaigns of the second century BC. The settlement became an oppidum civium Romanorum and then was advanced to municipium by Augustus. Tiberius dubbed it Colonia Iulia Parentium in the first century AD.

label: Parma
description: The site of a Bronze Age terramare settlement, Parma was re-founded first by Etruscans and later by the Romans when a colony was established there in 183 B.C. The city was rebuilt by Augustus and was eventually sacked by Attila.

label: Parma (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 G4 Parma fl.

label: Parndorf
description: Parndorf was the site of a Roman estate covering some 12 ha. The villa was situated near the Roman road leading from Savaria-Scarbantia to Carnuntum. The site was fortified by means of an enclosure wall ca. 1.5 km long.

label: Parnes (mountain)
description: A densely forested mountain range located to the north of Athens.

label: Paros (island)
description: A Cycladic island.

label: Paros (settlement)
description: The homonymous polis and settlement on the Aegean island of Paros.

label: Parthenicum
description: Ancient settlement on the north-west side of Sicily, thought to be in the area of modern Partinico, near Palermo.

label: Parthenion
description: On a hill southwest of the modern Greek town of Partheni, a fortified Classical-Hellenistic settlement has been identified with the attested ancient Eritrean deme of Parthenion.

label: Parthenope/Neapolis
description: Founded as Parthenope by Greeks in the eighth century B.C., the site eventually gave rise to Neapolis in the sixth century B.C. and was one of the most prominent cities of Magna Graecia. Modern-day Naples, Italy.

label: Pasargadae/Batrakatash
description: Pasargadae/Batrakatash was an ancient Persian city and the capital of Cyrus the Great (559–530 BC). It remained the capital until Cambyses II moved it to Susa. The site is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

label: Patara/Arsinoe
description: Patara/Arsinoe was an ancient maritime center of southwest Lycia.

label: Patavium
description: An ancient settlement of the Veneti, Patavium became a Roman municipium in 45 BC. It was the birthplace of several famous Romans including Titus Livius, Valerius Flaccus, Asconius Pedianus and Thrasea Paetus.

label: Patmos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D3 Patmos

label: Patmos (island)
description: Patmos is the smallest and northernmost island of the ancient Sporades.

label: Patra(e)
description: Patra(e) (modern Patras) is an important ancient center with settlement beginning in the Late Helladic period. Patras played a leading role in the foundation of the second "Achaean League" and was the site of a Roman colony after 146 BC.

label: Patroklou Charax (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 C4 Patroklou Charax Ins.

label: Paxoi (islands)
description: Paxoi Inss., the smallest group of Ionian islands. Paxos and Antipaxos lie 13 km south of Corcyra.

label: Paxos (island)
description: An island in the Ionian Sea, south of Kerkyra.

label: Pegai/Antipatris/Arethousa?
description: A series of settlements and fortifications localized in and around the mound known today as Tel Afek/Râs el-'Ain in Israel. The mound itself is dominated today by the remains of an Ottoman fort, built on Crusader foundations, but an excavated Roman-era odeon can also be seen.

label: Peiraieus/Piraeus
description: The ancient, fortified port settlement of ancient Athens. It was also the coastal deme of the tribe Hippothoontis.

label: Pelagonia
description: An ancient region of north Macedonia.

label: Pelinna(ion)?
description: A major city of western Thessaly.

label: Pella/Apamea
description: Pella/Apamea in Syria was an ancient city established by the Seleucids ca. 300 B.C.

label: Pella/Berenice/Philippeia
description: Pella/Berenice/Philippeia (Tabaqat Fahl (طبقة فحل)) is a ruined ancient city located in northwestern Jordan. Pella was continuously occupied from the Neolithic period until its destruction by means of an earthquake in AD 749.

label: Pella/Diokletianoupolis
description: Capital of the Kingdom of Macedonia.

label: Pellana
description: An ancient settlement whose remnants are located at the modern village now bearing the ancient name (formerly Kalyvia Georgitsi) in Greece's Sparti municipality.

label: Pellene
description: Pellene was an ancient settlement in Achaea allied with Sparta during the Peloponnesian War.

label: Peloponnesus/Peloponnesos/Peloponnese
description: The large peninsula protuding into the Mediterranean Sea that constitutes the southern part of Greece. It is largely separated from mainland Greece on the north by the Corinthian Gulf, joining it only in the northeast via the narrow Isthmus of Corinth.

label: Pelorus/Regium (promontory)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 H2 Pelorus/Regium Pr.

label: Pelousiakos Kolpos
description: Pelousiakos Kolpos (Jūnah aţ Ţīnah)

label: Peltuinum
description: Peltuinum was a settlement of the Vestini located along the Via Claudia Nova. The town is notable as the birthplace of the Roman general Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo.

label: Pelusium
description: Pelusium was a fortified ancient city located at the mouth of the eastern-most branch of the Nile river. Its ruins, now land-locked and located approximately 30km southeast of Port Said, are known as Tell Farama.

label: Pentele
description: An ancient settlement of Attica and possibly a deme. BAtlas tentatively (hollow symbol with question mark) locates it on mount Pentelikon. A modern town at the mountain's western foot now bears this name, but is not directly identified by scholars with the ancient settlement.

label: Pentelikon/Brilessos (mountain)
description: Pentelikon/Brilessos is a mountain to the northeast of Athens that was famous for its fine-grained marble.

label: Peparethus (island)
description: An island of the western Aegean Sea (modern Skopelos).

label: Pergamum
description: An important ancient settlement, located at modern Bergama in Turkey. It was first described in Xenophon's Anabasis and was later used as a treasury under Lysimachus. Pergamum became the administrative capital and principal city of the Attalid kingdom and dynasty (282-133 BCE) and was briefly the first capital of the Roman province of Asia. It later was a seat of a Christian bishopric and is listed in Revelation as one of the seven churches of Asia. It was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2014 under "Pergamon and its Multi-Layered Cultural Landscape".

label: Perge
description: An ancient Greek city of Asia Minor and capital of Pamphylia.

label: Perinthus/Heraclea
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 B3 Perinthus/Heraclea

label: Perre
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 G1 Perre

label: Persepolis/Parsa/Persai/Sat Setun
description: Persepolis/Parsa/Persai/Sat Setun was the ceremonial capital of the Achaemenid Empire. The origins of the settlement belong to the sixth century BC (ca. 515). The archaeological site was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

label: Persicus Sinus/Erythr(ae)um Mare
description: The Persian Gulf is located in Western Asia between Persia and the Arabian Peninsula.

label: Pertusa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E3 Pertusa

label: Perusia
description: A city of ancient Umbrian and Etruscan origin, Perusia aided Rome during the Second Punic War but was sieged and reduced by Octavian in the first century B.C. during campaigns against Lucius Antonius. It was rebuilt by Augustus and became Colonia Vibia Augusta Perusia quite late, in A.D. 251-3, under Trebonianus Gallus.

label: Peshawar
description: Ancient Peshawar was a capital of the Gandharan kingdom from the second century AD, when it was known as Purushapura.

label: Pessinous/Iustinianoupolis
description: An ancient city of Asia Minor, today Ballıhisar in Turkey.

label: Peteon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 E4 Peteon

label: Petra
description: Capital city of the Nabataeans located on the slope of Mount Hor.

label: Petrocori
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F3 Petrocori

label: Petronell
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 13 B4 Petronell

label: Peuma(ta)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D2 Peuma(ta)

label: Phaistos
description: An ancient settlement on Crete where occupation began ca. 3000 B.C., Phaistos was a major center of the Minoan civilization and continued to be a Greek city of the first millennium B.C.

label: Phalasarna
description: An ancient harbor town located on the northwest coast of Crete.

label: Phara(i)
description: Phara(i) was an ancient settlement of western Achaea, located west of the Peirus river.

label: Pharan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 76 D4 Pharan

label: Pharsalus
description: Pharsalus was one of the most important cities of ancient Thessaly.

label: Phaselis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 E4 Phaselis

label: Pheneos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C2 Pheneos

label: Pherai
description: Pherai was an ancient city of Thessaly in the district of Pelasgiotis.

label: Phigaleia
description: Phigaleia was an ancient city in the southwestern part of Arcadia in Greece.

label: Philadelpheia
description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor, modern Alaşehir, Turkey.

label: Philae
description: An ancient island located just above the First cataract of the Nile River that was flooded by the construction of the Aswan High Dam. The island was home to a multi-period temple complex, which was moved to the nearby island of Agilkia and declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in the 1970s.

label: Philippopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 E4 Philippopolis

label: Philippopolis/Trimontium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 B6 Philippopolis/Trimontium

label: Philomelion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 62 F5 Philomelion

label: Phintias
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Phintias

label: Phlaouiopolis/Flavias
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 C2 Phlaouiopolis/Flavias

label: Phlya
description: Phlya was an inland deme of the tribe Kekropis until 224 BC and then of the tribe Ptolemais.

label: Phocaea
description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor, modern Foça in Turkey.

label: Phocis
description: A region of central ancient Greece. In ~ 356 BCE, Phocian generals seized Delphi, starting the Third Sacred War.

label: Phoenicusa (island)
description: One of the Aeolian Islands, Phoenicusa shows evidence for Bronze Age occupation, as well as activity during the Greek and Roman periods.

label: Pholegandros (island)
description: Pholegandros is an island in the Aegean Sea located in the southern part of the Cyclades.

label: Pholegandros (settlement)
description: An ancient settlement on the island of Pholegandros in the Creticum Mare. Located at the modern village of Chora (Palaiokastro).

label: Phorbantia (island)
description: Phorbantia Ins. (modern Levanzo) is the smallest of the Aegates Inss.

label: Phreatto?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Phreatto?

label: Phrixa(i)
description: An ancient settlement, thought by modern scholars to have been located east of the site of ancient Olympia and south of the Alpheios river in the vicinity of modern Frixa. CFL/AGO reports the discovery of Classical/Hellenistic tombs just south of Frixa and west of Anemochoraki. The ToposText editors note the presence of pottery scatter just north of Phrixa village, coincident with the hilltop (Paliophanaro) identified in New Pauly as the site.

label: Phyle
description: Phyle was an Attic fortress and deme located on the Boeotian frontier, some 120 stades from Athens.

label: Phyliadon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 C2 Phyliadon

label: Pilias/Torre del Rey
description: A Spanish village located in the west of the province of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Pilas.

label: Pindus (mountain range)
description: A large mountain range in north and central Greece.

label: Pinna
description: Pinna (modern Penne) was a center of the Vestini. The site came under Roman control after the Social War (89 BC).

label: Piquentum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 A4 Piquentum

label: Pisae
description: A city situated on the Tyrrhenian seaboard and likely of Etruscan origin. Its early nature was that of a mercantile center. The city became a Roman colony in 89 B.C.

label: Pisida
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 35 D1 Pisida

label: Pityonesos (island)
description: Modern Agkistrion in the Saronic Gulf, located to the west of Aegina.

label: Pityoussa (island)
description: A large island at the entrance to the Argolic Gulf, lying to the southwest off the tip of the peninsula of the Argolid. Modern Spetses.

label: Pityoussa/Lampsacus
description: A Greek city located on the eastern side of the Hellespont.

label: Placentia
description: Placentia (modern Piacenza) was an ancient site with Gallic and Etruscan occupation before the Roman conquest of 218 B.C. The city persisted into Late Antiquity.

label: Plana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F7 Plana

label: Planasia (island)
description: Planasia (modern Pianosa) is an island of the Tuscan archipelago to which Agrippa Postumus was exiled by Augustus in A.D. 6 or 7.

label: Plataea
description: Plataea is an ancient city of Boeotia, located south of Thebes. In 479 BC Plataea was the site of the Battle of Plataea, in which an allied Greek army defeated the Persians. Plataea was destroyed in the Peloponnesian War by Thebes and Sparta in 427 BC and rebuilt in 386 BC.

label: Platea (island)
description: An island in the Aegean Sea that is mentioned by Pliny the Elder. It is probably to be identified with the modern Kamilonísi.

label: Plestia
description: Plestia was a municipium of the tribus Ufentina.

label: Poggio Capalbiaccio
description: The hill known as Poggio Capalbiaccio is located in the Maremma plain.

label: Pol-e Dokhtar
description: Pol-e Dokhtar (also Romanized as Pol Dokhtar and Pul-i-Dukhtar) is a city in the Lorestan Province of Iran. The ruins of a Sasanian bridge over the Kashkan River are still visible today a few kilometers north of the city; that structure was part of a Sasanian Royal road that connected the Persian capitals Istakhr and Bishapur with towns in central and northern Mesopotamia. In 1992, a horde of ancient objects were found in the nearby Cave Kalmakareh (also referred to as Cave Kalmakarra).

label: Pola
description: A port city on the Adriatic Sea (modern Pula in Croatia).

label: Polemonion/Side
description: A harbor city on the Black Sea, Polemonion/Side was founded in the region of Sidene (Pontus) by either Polemon I or Polemon II of Pontus. Following the Roman annexation of the Pontic kingdom in the 60s CE, the city's importance declined substantially.

label: Pollina
description: Modern town in Sicily, near Cefalù, that has been associated with the ancient settlement of Apollonia.

label: Polyaigos (island)
description: An island in the Aegean, mentioned by a number of ancient authors, Polyaigos is part of an archipelago that includes Melos and Kimolos and is still known by variants of its ancient name.

label: Polyrrenia
description: Polyrrenia was an important ancient city of western Crete.

label: Pomaria
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 29 D2 Pomaria

label: Pommiers oppidum
description: The archaeologically attested oppidum at modern Moulin à Vent in the French commune of Pommiers is probably to be identified with the Noviodunum mentioned by Caesar. The oppidum was occupied from the late La Tène period through the early Roman.

label: Pompeii
description: An ancient city of Campania destroyed by the volcanic eruption of Mt. Vesuvius in A.D. 79, Pompeii was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

label: Pompelo
description: Cn. Pompeius Magnus is considered to have been the founder of Pompelo (modern Pamplona) while on campaign against Sertorius in 75 BC.

label: Pompey's pillar
description: A Roman triumphal column in Alexandria, Egypt.

label: Pons Aeli
description: The site of a Roman fort at Newcastle dating between the second and fourth centuries. The fort was perhaps designed to protect a bridge over the river Tyne.

label: Pons Aemilius
description: The Pons Aemilius was the first stone bridge across the Tiber river at Rome (241 B.C.). Its remains are known today as the 'Ponte Rotto'.

label: Pons Saravi
description: A road station between Tarquimpol and Saverne.

label: Pont du Gard
description: The Pont du Gard is an ancient Roman aqueduct bridge that crosses the Gardon River near the town of Vers-Pont-du-Gard in the south of France. It was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1985.

label: Pontia
description: A settlement on Pontia Ins. The largest of the Pontine Islands, Pontia lies 33 km south of Cape Circeo on the Italian mainland.

label: Pontiae (islands)
description: An archipelago in the Tyrrhenian Sea off the west coast of Italy.

label: Pordonnium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 67 G1 Pordonnium

label: Porta Leoni
description: A Republican gate of Verona dedicated by P. Valerius, Q. Caecilius, Q. Servilius and P. Cornelius.

label: Porta Maggiore
description: The Porta Maggiore is the ancient Porta Praenestina, an early Imperial gate preserved in the later third century walls built by Aurelian.

label: Porta Ostiensis
description: The Porta Ostiensis, now known as the Porta San Paolo, is a gate in Rome's Aurelian Wall from which the Via Ostiensis issues.

label: Portus Lemanis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 8 I3 Portus Lemanis

label: Portus Veneris
description: An ancient seaport located near Cape Béar, modern Port-Vendres in France.

label: Portus Victoriae Iuliobrigensium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 H1 Portus Victoriae Iuliobrigensium

label: Poseidonia/Paestum
description: Greeks from Sybaris originally founded Poseidonia/Paestum, a major Greco-Roman center of south Italy, in the seventh-century BCE. It was originally named Poseidonia. After the Pyrrhic war, the city became a Latin colony named Paestum ca. 273 BCE.

label: Potaissa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 F3 Potaissa

label: Potentia
description: Potentia was the site of a Roman colonial foundation ca. 184 BCE.

label: Pouillé
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G1 Pouillé

label: Praeneste
description: An ancient city of central Italy, the eighth and seventh century B.C. origins of which demonstrate high-level trade contact with the Eastern Mediterranean world. The city withdrew from the Latin League (499 B.C.) and opposed Rome in the Latin war; Cincinnatus eventually subdued Praeneste. Sulla founded a new colony there in the first century B.C.

label: Praetorium
description: An ancient settlement, at Thamad Hassan in Libya, cited: BAtlas 37 A1 Praetorium

label: Praetorium Agrippinae
description: A Roman fortification on the Oude Rijn, Praetorium Agrippinae was likely established under Caius ca. AD 39 or 40.

label: Praetorium Latobicorum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B4 Praetorium Latobicorum

label: Prepesinthos (island)
description: The island of Prepesinthos, now known as Despotikó, is a small, arid island of the Cyclades island grouping. It is situated just some 700 meters to the west of the island of Antiparos. It lies to the east of the small island of Strongyli. Its location is nearly at the center of the Cyclades. While in the present day the island is uninhabited, it was an important communication node in antiquity, offering safe harborage.

label: Priapus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 A4 Priapus

label: Priene/‘Lince’?
description: Priene/‘Lince’? was an ancient Greek city of Ionia on an escarpment of Mycale Mons.

label: Prinias (Patela)
description: An Iron Age settlement on the Patela plateau north of the modern village of Prinias; its ancient name is uncertain. The site is notable for its occupation from the end of the Bronze Age through to the Archaic period, as well as for the monumental architecture and Orientalizing sculpture of its Buildings ('Temples') A and B.

label: Proerna
description: An ancient city in Tetras or Achaia Phthiotis in Greece.

label: Propaxos (island)
description: The modern Ionian island of Antipaxos.

label: Propontis
description: The Sea of Marmara.

label: Prostanna
description: A city of Pisidia, the site of Prostanna is located near modern Eğridir in Turkey in a saddle between the peak of Sivri Tepe and the main body of Davras Daği. Prostanna is mentioned in two literary sources (Ptolemy 5.5.7 and a listing of of bishops attending the Council of Constantinople in 381). The name is also attested in an inscription from Delos that dates ca. 113 B.C.

label: Prusa
description: Human settlement at Prusa began as a site called Cius that came under the control of the king of Bithynia in 202 BC. The city was renamed Prusias and was eventually willed to the Roman Empire in 74 BC by Nicomedes IV, the last King of Bithynia.

label: Prusias ad Mare/Kios
description: Prusias ad Mare/Kios was an ancient Greek city on the Propontis. The city joined the Aetolian League and was destroyed by Philip V of Macedon. Prusias I of Bithynia rebuilt the site, naming it for himself.

label: Psophis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B2 Psophis

label: Pteleon
description: An Archaic to Late Antique settlement and Mycenaean tombs on the hill Gritsa south of modern Pteleos in Magnesia Thessaly.

label: Ptolemais Hormou
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 D2 Ptolemais Hormou

label: Ptolemais/Barkes Limen
description: An ancient capital of Cyrenaica, Ptolemais was probably named after Ptolemy III Euergetes. The city was founded in either the seventh or sixth century BC.

label: Ptychia (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 A2 Ptychia Ins.

label: Puzriš-Dagan
description: An ancient city of Lower Mesopotamia, Puzriš-Dagan was founded in the twenty-first century B.C. by King Shulgi of Ur.

label: Pydna
description: An ancient settlement and seaport in Macedonia, located south of modern Makrigialos. According to Apollodorus, the population was relocated to a new, inland site by Archelaos (see Pydna/Kitron), but it is clear that this original, coastal site was reoccupied.

label: Pydna/Kitron
description: According to Apollodorus, Archelaos relocated the population of coastal ancient Pydna (q.v.), remains of which lie on the southern edge of modern Marygialos, to a new, inland site. Scholars believe that, by the Roman era, this site had become or moved to the area of modern Kitros, although no definitive urban center has yet been identified. Several locations between Marygialos, Kitros, and Alonia (further inland and north of Kitros) have produced related funerary material and epigraphy.

label: Pylos/Koryphasion
description: A Classical settlement, probably the Pylos of Thucydides, on the Koryphasion promontory, (modern Akr. Koryphasiou in Messenia) in the Peloponnese.

label: Pyra
description: Pyra is a place with preserved ruins of a Doric temple dating to the third century B.C. The sources connect Pyra with the pyre of the hero Herakles.

label: Pyramid of Djoser
description: The pyramid of the Third Dynasty pharaoh Djoser was built at Saqqara by architect Imhotep ca. 2267-2648 B.C.

label: Pyramid of Khentkawes
description: Khentkawes I was a queen of the 4th dynasty of ancient Egypt. She may have been a daughter of the pharaoh Menkaure, and the wife of both kings Shepseskaf and Userkaf. Her tomb at Giza – LG100 – is located close to Menkaure's pyramid complex.

label: Pyramid of Menkaure
description: The Pyramid of Menkaure is the smallest of the three main pyramids located on the Giza plateau. It marks the tomb of the fourth dynasty Egyptian Pharaoh Menkaure.

label: Pyramid of Unas
description: A pyramid at Saqqara built for Unas, the final ruler of Egypt's Fifth Dynasty.

label: Pyramids of Meroe
description: The pyramid tombs of the kings of the Kushite kingdom.

label: Pyrenaei (mountains)
description: The Pyrenees Mountains separate the Iberian Peninsula from the rest of continental Europe. The mountain ranges extends from the Bay of Biscay to Cap de Creus, for an extent of 491 km (305 miles).

label: Pyrgi
description: Pyrgi is an ancient Etruscan port city on the Tyrrhenian coast of Italy. A Roman colony was established at the site by 191 B.C. In 1964, the bilingual 'Pyrgi Plaques' were discovered during the course of excavations.

label: Pyrgoi/Pyrgos
description: An ancient settlement of Triphylia in the western Peloponnese, thought to have been located in the vicinity of the modern Greek village of Agios Elias in the municipality of Zacharo, some 36km south-southeast of the modern city of Pyrgos.

label: Pyrrichos
description: An ancient city of the Peloponnesian Mani, located near the modern village of Kavalos/Pyrrhikhos.

label: Pythion
description: An ancient city, located on the western slope of Mount Olympos to the southwest of modern Pythion.

label: Pîtres
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B3 Pîtres

label: Qalat al-Bahrain
description: An ancient settlement with evidence of occupation stretching from 2300 BC to the sixteenth century AD, Qal'at al-Bahrain was once the capital of the Dilmun civilization. In 2005, it was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

label: Qaleh Dukhtar
description: The so-called "Maiden Castle" is a large fortification built by Ardashir I in the early third century A.D. It is located about 8 kilometers to the north of Firuzabad in modern Iran. Despite the distance involved, it is listed as part of the "cultural landscape of Bam" in the 2004 UNESCO World Heritage List.

label: Qasr Al-Kharanah
description: Early Islamic structure in Eastern Jordan, likely constructed before the eighth century CE. Though its outward appearance suggests a castle, it does not seem to have had any military function, and the structure's original purpose is unknown.

label: Qasr-i Abu Nasr/Seraz/Tirazzish?/Shiraz(zish)?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 94 C4 Qasr-i Abu Nasr/Seraz/Tirazzish?/Shiraz(zish)?

label: Qatif
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 95 B3 Qatif

label: Qatna
description: A city in western Syria that was first settled in the Early Bronze Age III (ca. 2700-2600 BCE). In the Middle Bronze Age (2000-1600 BCE), it became a major trading center and the capital of a regional kingdom. In the Late Bronze Age, the city of Qatna became a vassal of first the Mitanni Kingdom, then the Neo-Hittite Empire, and Egypt. The city's acropolis was abandoned in the Late Bronze Age I, though the surrounding area remained inhabited. It was resettled in the 10th century BCE as part of the Aramaean kingdom of Hamath, but was sacked by the army of Sargon II in 720 and ultimately abandoned in the 6th century BCE.

label: Quintilii
description: A suburban villa built by Sextus Quintilius Maximus and Sextus Quintilius Condianus (consuls in A.D. 151).

label: Quirinal Hill
description: One of the hills of Rome, comprised of several smaller peaks. According to tradition its first inhabitants were Titus Tatius and the Sabines; during the Republic the hill was a mostly residential area.

label: Qutb Minar
description: The second tallest minar (73 m) in India after Minar-E-Fateh was built by Qutb-ud-din Aibak beginning in AD 1192. The monument is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

label: R(h)oda
description: A Greek trading settlement in northeastern Spain founded by the Rhodians.

label: Rablê
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is Riblah, located ca. 35 km south of Ḥomṣ.

label: Raetia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 J2 Raetia

label: Ramesseum
description: The funerary temple of Ramesses II, built within the area known as the Ipet-isut, "The Most Selected of Places", along the Nile River.

label: Ramista
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D3 Ramista

label: Raphia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 E3 Raphia

label: Ras Ibn Hani
description: Archaeological evidence on this cape on the northwest coast of the modern country of Syria demonstrates continuous human occupation from the Bronze Age through Byzantine times, down to the modern day.

label: Ratae
description: Ratae Corieltauvorum (modern Leicester) was a settlement in Britannia.

label: Rauranum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 F2 Rauranum

label: Ravenna
description: A city of northern Adriatic Italy that served as the capital of the Western Roman Empire from A.D. 402 until 476.

label: Rašt
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Reate
description: Reate (modern Rieti) was a major Sabine center that came to be captured by Manius Curius Dentatus in late third century B.C.

label: Reginum/Castra Regina
description: Reginum/Castra Regina was a Roman military installation on the Danube established ca. A.D. 179 for Legio III Italica.

label: Regium Lepidum
description: Regium Lepidum (modern Reggio Emilia) was founded by M. Aemilius Lepidus in either 187 or 175 B.C.

label: Regulbium
description: Regulbium was a Roman 'Saxon Shore' fort.

label: Retracted: Akropolis
description: Doublet for https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/582866/

label: Rhaga(i)/Europos/Arsakia/Ray
description: Rhaga(i), now the city of Rey in Iran, was an important settlement of the Medes that declined after the Mongol invasions.

label: Rhamnous
description: Rhamnous was an ancient settlement of Attica adjacent to the Euboean Strait and a coastal deme of the tribe Aiantis.

label: Rhegion/Regium
description: A site with settlement origins in the Bronze and Iron Ages, Rhegion was eventually colonized by Chalcis in either 743 or 730 BCE.

label: Rhinocolura
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 D3 Rhinocolura

label: Rhithymna/Arsinoe
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 B2 Rhithymna/Arsinoe

label: Rhizaion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 F3 Rhizaion

label: Rhodia(polis)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 D5 Rhodia(polis)

label: Rhodos (island)
description: The island of Rhodes has an area of some 1,400 square km and sits 18 km from the coast of Asia Minor. The island has been inhabited by humans since the Neolithic period.

label: Rhodos (settlement)
description: A settlement on the island of Rhodes.

label: Ribemont-sur-Ancre
description: Ribemont-sur-Ancre is the site of a Celtic and Gallo-Roman sanctuary located on the right bank of the Ancre river, a tributary of the Somme. Roger Agache discovered the site in 1962. The site is vast in its area, covering some 80 ha.

label: Ricciacum (or Ricciacus)
description: An ancient settlement and road station of the Treveri, located at modern Dalheim in Luxembourg.

label: Ricina
description: A Roman road station along the Via Aemilia Scauri on the Mediterranean coast of Italy, thought to have been located in the vicinty of modern Recco.

label: Riduna (island)
description: The northernmost of the Channel Islands.

label: Rigomagus
description: Rigomagus (Remagen) was the site of a Roman fort built west of the Rhine.

label: Rijswijk
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 10 A4 Rijswijk

label: Ripacandida
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 C3 Ripacandida

label: Rittium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 C4 Rittium

label: Rodumna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 C1 Rodumna

label: Roiate
description: A fortified pre-Roman center connected with the Aequi. The ancient name of the site is unknown.

label: Roma
description: The capital of the Roman Republic and Empire.

label: Roman Agora of Athens
description: The Roman agora at Athens is located to the north of the Acropolis and to the east of the ancient Agora.

label: Roman Heidelberg
description: A complex of Roman military structures was established and upgraded between the first and third centuries CE on the banks of the Neckar River in Germany where modern Heidelberg now stands. Forts, bridges, roads, and manufacturing facilities with attendant burials and inscriptions have been excavated.

label: Roman Theater of Minturnae
description: A theater constructed in Minturnae under Augustus or Tiberius, and further embellished under Hadrian.

label: Roman Villa and Medieval Settlement at Piazza Armerina
description: The so-called "Villa Romana del Casale" (of Roman date) and the nearby settlement of Piazza Armerina, which seems to have been occupied by survivors from the villa site after it was destroyed in an earthquake in the early middle ages. The villa is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, in part because of its famous mosaics.

label: Roman Villa at Welschbillig
description: This extensive villa (ancient name unknown) was located at modern Welschbillig in Germany (in the ancient territory of the Treveri).

label: Roman amphitheater of Catania
description: The Roman amphitheater of Catania is the largest known ancient amphitheater in Sicily. Its external dimensions measure ca. 125 x 105 meters. It likely dates to the second century.

label: Roman amphitheater of Col. Tarraco
description: A Roman amphitheater in Tarragona built in the first century A.D. The structure was renovated under Elagabalus.

label: Roman amphitheater of Italica
description: The amphitheater of Italica, built in the second century A.D., was one of the largest in the Roman world and could accommodate an estimated 25,000 spectators.

label: Roman theater at Benevento
description: A Roman theater of the second century A.D. constructed during the reign of Hadrian.

label: Roman theater at Iguvium
description: The Roman theater at Iguvium is located within the Guastuglia archaeological area and dates to the late republican period. Sear (2004) notes several important architectural innovations evident in the theater's construction.

label: Roman villa at Positano
description: An opulent Roman villa maritima destroyed by the A.D. 79 eruption of Vesuvius. The remains of an opulent and well-decorated Roman villa have been known at Positano since at least 1758 when ruins were discovered during work on the bell tower of the church of S. Maria Assunta. Karl Weber conducted excavations there in the same year. Modern work, begun in 1999, has stabilized and consolidated the site.

label: Romula/Malva
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 22 B4 Romula/Malva

label: Roque-de-Viou
description: Roque-de-Viou was an oppidum located in the Vaunage valley. Occupational evidence shows the site was in use between 700 BC and 600 BC, 350 BC and 300 BC and around 50 BC.

label: Roscianum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 E2 Roscianum

label: Rotomagus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 B3 Rotomagus

label: Royat
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 I3 Royat

label: Rufrae
description: A Samnite settlement at the margins of Campania.

label: Rumst
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E1 Rumst

label: Rusaddir
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 29 C1 Rusaddir

label: Rusellae
description: An Etruscan city captured by Rome in 294 B.C., Rusellae's >2 mile circuit of megalithic walls represent an important early instance of stone fortification walling in the Italian peninsula.

label: Rusguniae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 30 F3 Rusguniae

label: Ruspina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 G1 Ruspina

label: Rutupiae
description: The Roman fort at Rutupiae was erected at the location where the Claudian landings took place in A.D. 43.

label: S. Paulus
description: One of Rome's four major papal basilicae, S. Paulus was founded by Constantine I in the early fourth century A.D. and expanded by Valentinian I in the 370s. The basilica, with many renovations, repairs, and improvements, stood until the 19th century, when it was destroyed in a fire. The reconstructed basilica only generally resembles the original structure.

label: S. Vincenzo al Volturno
description: S. Vincenzo al Volturno is a multi-period settlement. In pre-Roman times a phase of Samnite occupation has been identified. By the fifth century A.D. the site was occupied by a large agricultural estate (villa) that was abandoned in the later fifth century, only to be replaced by a Christian church.

label: Saarbrücken
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 H3 Saarbrücken

label: Sabatinus lacus
description: A volcanic lake in Latium north of Rome (modern Lago di Bracciano).

label: Sabiona
description: A seventeenth century Benedictine nunnery located on a site that shows occupational evidence stretching back to the Neolithic period and that includes substantial Roman and Late Antique phases.

label: Sabora
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E5 Sabora

label: Sabzevār
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Sacred Area of S. Omobono
description: An archaeological area in the Forum Boarium comprising an ancient ritual precinct with twin temples ranging in date from the Archaic period through the time of the Roman Empire. The Medieval church dedicated to S. Omobono stands atop the remains of one of the two ancient temples.

label: Saepinum
description: An ancient town of Samnium captured by the Romans in 293 B.C., located on the road between Beneventum and Corfinium.

label: Sagalassos
description: Sagalassos is an ancient city in Pisidia that was later part of the Roman province of Galatia. The city flourished until natural disasters and disease led to its decline in the sixth century AD.

label: Sagii
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 A4 Sagii

label: Saguntum/Arse
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Saguntum/Arse

label: Sahab
description: A farming village southeast of Amman, Jordan, inhabited from the late Neolithic Period through the sixth century BCE, and briefly inhabited again from the eleventh-thirteenth centuries; now the site of the modern town of Sahab.

label: Sainte-Colombe
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 E4 no. 129 (Ste-Colombe)

label: Sais
description: Sais was an ancient Egyptian town located in the Western Nile Delta on the Canopic branch of the Nile River. It served as the provincial capital of Sap-Meh, the fifth nome of Lower Egypt, and became a capital during the Twenty-fourth Dynasty (ca. 732–720 BC) as well as during the Late Period. Herodotus claimed that Osiris was buried at Sais. Other Greek authors, including Plato, maintained a connection between Sais and the goddess Athena.

label: Sakarya-Ebene
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Sal(a)mas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 G2 Sal(a)mas

label: Sala
description: In and around the area where the Islamic-era cemetery of Chellah now lies in modern Rabat, Morocco, a Phoenician and Carthaginian settlement developed. The Roman colony of Sala was eventually established there.

label: Sala (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D3 Sala fl.

label: Salamias
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 68 D3 Salamias

label: Salamis (island)
description: Salamis is the largest island of the Saronic Gulf.

label: Salamis (settlement)
description: The ancient city of Salamis was located on the Saronic island of the same name, overlooking the modern Ampelaki Bay to the east. The site was likely largely in the area now covered by the modern city of Ambelaki/Ampelaki.

label: Salamis/Konstantia
description: An ancient settlement on the east coast of Cyprus, located northwest of Ammokhostos.

label: Salanda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 63 F3 Salanda

label: Salaria?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Salaria?

label: Salduie/‘Salduba’
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E4 Salduie/‘Salduba’

label: Salernum
description: A city of Campania with Osco-Etruscan origins that became a Roman colony in 197 B.C.

label: Sallentinum/Iapygia
description: Cape Leuca, known as Sallentinum and Iapygia in ancient sources, is a headland that forms the extreme southeastern point of Italy and separates the Gulf of Tarentum from the Adriatic Sea.

label: Salmantica
description: Salmantica (modern Salamanca) was an indigenous Celtic center before falling to the Carthaginians and, later, the Romans.

label: Salmone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B2 Salmone

label: Salodurum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 E2 Salodurum

label: Salona
description: A coastal city of Dalmatia.

label: Salsum (river)
description: The Guadajoz river.

label: Sam'al
description: A Hittite and Aramaean city located at Zincirli Höyük in the Anti-Taurus mountains. The site appears in Neo-Assyrian sources as Samʾalla and Aramaic texts as šmʿl (also yʾdy). It is identified with the modern site of Zincirli.

label: Samaria/Sebaste
description: Samaria/Sebaste was an ancient city of Iudaea. In 30 B.C. it passed under the control of Herod the Great and was renamed Sebaste in honor of the emperor Augustus.

label: Samarobriva Ambianorum
description: A city of Gallia Belgica located on the Somme that is mentioned in Caesar's commentaries.

label: Same/Samos (settlement)
description: The primary ancient settlement and port on the island of Samos (modern Sami).

label: Samikon/Samia
description: A town of Triphylia in ancient Elis.

label: Samos (island)
description: The island of Samos.

label: Samos (settlement)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 D2 Samos

label: Samosata
description: An ancient city on the Euphrates River's West bank, established perhaps as early as the Hittite period. Its ruins, known in modern times as Samsat (Turkey), were submerged following the construction of the Atatürk Dam in the early 1990s. The modern village of Samsat was relocated and is not coincident with the ancient site.

label: Samothrace (island)
description: Samothrace is an island of the northern Aegean Sea.

label: Samothrace (settlement)
description: The homonymous settlement on the Aegean island, located on its north shore (modern Paleopolis).

label: San Nicola in Carcere
description: San Nicola in Carcere is a titular church in Rome's historical district (rione) Sant'Angelo, close to the Forum Boarium. The twelfth-century church is built atop the remains of Roman temples of the ancient Forum Holitorium and incorporates their remains into its structure.

label: Sanctuary of Eleusinian Demeter in Laconia
description: An extensive sanctuary mentioned by Pausanias and located at the modern village of Kalyvia Sochas by virtue of the discovery of a number of inscriptions on the site. Very little of the sanctuary is visible today, as the site was damaged by a number of floods and only ever partly excavated. Modern signage in the village marks the location of some finds.

label: Sanctuary of Mercury Canetonnessis
description: Findspot of the so-called "Berthouville Treasure," discovered in 1830 in the hamlet of Villeret in the French commune of Berthouville. A temple and a theater of presumed Roman imperial date were subsequently excavated in the late 19th century. The site is not visible today, but a resistivity survey conducted in 2005 (Thierry) verified the locations of these major structures and the general accuracy of Babelon's map, deriving from the original excavations.

label: Sane
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D4 Sane

label: Sane/Ouranopolis
description: An ancient settlement, located on the Athos/Akte peninsula.

label: Sanitium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 B2 Sanitium

label: Sanremo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 E2 Sanremo

label: Sant Esteuan
description: A Spanish village located in the northeast of the province of Jaén that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X (thirteenth century). The site's modern name is Santisteban del Puerto.

label: Sant'Agata di Militello
description: A modern town in Sicily that has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Agathyrnum.

label: Santicum
description: A settlement located at a favorable crossing over the Drau river that was an important road junction.

label: Saqqarah
description: A pharaonic necropolis serving the ancient Egyptian city of Memphis. It was most active during Early Dynastic and Old Kingdom Egypt. The step pyramid complex of the Third Dynasty Pharaoh Djoser is the site's best preserved and most well-known structure.

label: Saranta Ekklēsiai
description: A town in Eastern Thrace with signs of habitation dating from the Paleolithic period; it became a major city in European Turkey in the Ottoman period, and is now the capital of Kırklareli Province.

label: Sardinia (island)
description: Sardinia is the second-largest island in the Mediterranean Sea.

label: Sardinia (late Roman province)
description: The Late Roman province of Sardinia was organized under a praeses during the reign of Diocletian. In the fifth century (455) the island was occupied by the Vandals. Justinian I reclaimed the island in 534 and it remained under Byzantine control until the eleventh century.

label: Sardinia et Corsica (Roman province)
description: The province of Sardinia et Corsica was the second Roman province and came under Roman control after the First Punic War.

label: Sardis/Hyde?
description: Sardis was the capital of the Lydian Empire, located in western Turkey. In 188 B.C. Sardis became a part of the Attalid kingdom, and thus it passed with the territory of Attalus III to Rome in 133 B.C.

label: Sardurihinili
description: An Urartian fortress constructed in the eighth century BCE and destroyed in the seventh century BCE.

label: Saronicus Sinus
description: The Saronic Gulf (also called the Gulf of Aegina) is a part of the Aegean Sea that delimits the eastern side of the isthmus of Corinth.

label: Sarsina
description: Sarsina was a town of the Umbri that was captured by Cornelius Scipio in 271 B.C. and was the birthplace of the Latin author Plautus. The necropolis at Sarsina has been extensively studied.

label: Sarte
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B4 Sarte

label: Sason (island)
description: Pliny notes that this island was notorious as a pirate refuge.

label: Savaria
description: Colonia Claudia Savaria (Szombathely) Hungary.

label: Savo/Vicus Virginis?
description: Savo/Vicus Virginis? (modern Savona) was a Ligurian settlement that came under Roman influence after the Second Punic War.

label: Saxa Rubra
description: Saxa Rubra (modern Grottarossa) is the name of a road station on the Via Flaminia nine Roman miles from the center of ancient Rome. It was at Saxa Rubra that Constantine I defeated Maxentius in A.D. 312.

label: Scallabis/Praesidium Iulium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B2 Scallabis/Praesidium Iulium

label: Scarbantia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D2 Scarbantia

label: Scarborough Castle
description: The ruins of a medieval castle built ca. A.D. 1135 by William le Gros, Earl of Albemarle. Now an English Heritage site.

label: Scardona
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C6 Scardona

label: Scodra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 B1 Scodra

label: Scupi
description: Scupi (modern Skopje, Macedonia (Macedonian: Скопје)) has been the site of human settlement since ca. 4000 BC.

label: Scythopolis/Nysa
description: A settlement located at the juncture of the Jordan and Jezreel valleys, Scythopolis/Nysa had important Egyptian through Roman phases.

label: Sebasteia/Megalopolis?/Talaura?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 64 E1 Sebasteia/Megalopolis?/Talaura?

label: Sebastopolis/Herakleopolis/Karana?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 64 C1 Sebastopolis/Herakleopolis/Karana?

label: Sebennytos
description: Sebennytos was an ancient city of Lower Egypt located on the Sebennytic branch of the Nile River. It was the capital of Lower Egypt's twelfth nome (the Sebennyte nome).

label: Segedunum
description: Segedunum was a Roman fort located at modern-day Wallsend, North Tyneside in the northeast of England. The fort was located at the eastern end of Hadrian's Wall.

label: Segessera
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E4 Segessera

label: Segesta/Egesta
description: A center of the Elymian people in northwestern Sicily.

label: Segestica/Siscia
description: Segestica/Siscia is an Iron Age settlement recorded by Strabo. It was located at the confluence of three rivers and was used as a staging area for a campaign against the Dacians.

label: Segobriga
description: Segobriga was an Ibero-Roman city.

label: Segodunum
description: Segodunum was a Gallic oppidum and later a Gallo-Roman town. It has been identified by scholars with modern Rodez.

label: Segontia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 C4 Segontia

label: Segovia
description: Segovia, originally of Celtiberian origin, became a Roman settlement. It is perhaps the site where Metellus defeated Hirtuleius, the general of Sertorius, in 75 B.C.

label: Segusio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 I3 Segusio

label: Segustero
description: A Roman settlement along the Via Domitia.

label: Selenia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 59 B3 Selenia

label: Seleucia ad Calycadnum/Tracheia
description: A city founded by Seleucus Nicator between 296 and 280 BC.

label: Seleucia/Sliq Kharawta
description: Seleucia/Sliq Kharawta was a city founded on the Tigris River by Seleukos I Nikator.

label: Selino(u)s (river near Krestena)
description: One of two rivers in the Peloponnese that bore this name, this Selino(us) was a late, left tributary of the Alpheious that flows past modern Krestena (the ancient city of Selino(u)s) and Makrisia (ancient Skillous) in the modern Elis Regional District. It is known today as the Selinountas or Selinous potamos.

label: Selino(u)s (settlement)
description: Modern Krestena, in the Elis regional unit of the Peloponnese.

label: Selinous (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 C1 Selinous fl.

label: Selinus
description: A Greek colonial city located on the southern coast of Sicily, Selinus was said to have been founded as a colony of the city of Megara Hyblaia.

label: Sellasia
description: An ancient fortified settlement located a few kilometers north of ancient Sparta on a hill known in modern times as Palaiogoulas, which is east of the modern town of Sellasia. Sacked several times in antiquity, Pausanias reports the settlement was abandoned by his time.

label: Sellium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 B2 Sellium

label: Sely(m)bria/Eudoxiopolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 C2 Sely(m)bria/Eudoxiopolis

label: Sena (island)
description: Sena Ins. (modern Île de Sein).

label: Sena Gallica
description: Senonian Gauls founded Sena Gallica at the mouth of the Misa River in the fourth century B.C. This place became the site of Rome's earliest colony on the Adriatic seaboard before 280 B.C. Pompeius Magnus destroyed the city in 82 B.C.

label: Senia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 B5 Senia

label: Sep. Scipionum
description: A family tomb of the Cornelii Scipiones near the Porta San Sebastiano in use from the third century B.C. to the first century A.D.

label: Septem
description: Now the Spanish exclave of Ceuta, Septem is an ancient port whose phases are not entirely clear owing to modern overburden. The city was the seat of a bishopric in the Byzantine period and was the last of Morocco's cities to recognize the authority of the emperor at the time of the Arab conquest.

label: Serapeum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 75 E1 Serapeum

label: Serdica
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 F7 Serdica

label: Seriphos (island)
description: Seriphos is an island of the western Cyclades. The island was settled by the third millennium B.C. The island was a member of the Delian League.

label: Serpa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 C4 Serpa

label: Serreion Teichos/Ganos
description: An ancient settlement in the Propontis near modern Ganos, Turkey.

label: Sestinum
description: Sestinum was an ancient place in Umbria near the headwaters of the river Pisaurus. Pliny mentions the site, and its ancient name is preserved in modern toponymy.

label: Sestos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 G4 Sestos

label: Settlement at Titelberg, Luxembourg
description: A Celtic and Roman settlement of the Treveri (ancient name unknown) with prehistoric antecedents.

label: Sexi/Saxetanum
description: Sexi/Saxetanum (modern Almuñécar) was a Phoenician colony established ca. 800 BC that eventually became a Roman one (Sexi Firmum Iulium).

label: Shad Shapur
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 F4 Shad Shapur

label: Shaduppum
description: Shaduppum was a small but heavily fortified city dating from the middle of the third millennium to the second millennium B.C.

label: Shahr-e Sukhteh
description: A Bronze Age urban settlement, associated with the Jiroft culture, located in Sistan and Baluchistan provinces in the southeastern part of Iran. The site was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2014.

label: Shahraban
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 F4 Shahraban

label: Shahristan/Zarang?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 H3 Shahristan/Zarang?

label: Shephela
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 70 F2 Shephela

label: Shimron/Simonias
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 Shimron/Simonias

label: Shiragan/Sirjan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 G4 Shiragan/Sirjan

label: Sicca Veneria
description: Sicca Veneria was an important Punic and Roman city located in what is now Tunisia.

label: Sicilia (island)
description: Sicily is the largest island in the Mediterranean Sea and has been the site of human habitation since ca. 8,000 BC. In historical terms, Sicily has seen important settlement activity connected to numerous culture groups - Punic, Carthaginian, Greek, Roman, Vandalic, Ostrogothic, Byzantine, Arabic, and Norman.

label: Siculum Fretum
description: A strait separating the eastern tip of Sicily and the southern tip of Calabria in the south of Italy.

label: Sicyon/Demetrias
description: Sicyon/Demetrias was an important ancient city of the Corinthiad, located some 26 km to the west of Corinth. The city had a long history, beginning in the Archaic period when Orthagorid tyrants ruled it. It flourished in later Archaic and Classical times, was a member of the Peloponnesian League, and became a center of Theban power after 371 B.C. The city was long noted for its association with fine arts and during the fourth century B.C. produced the famous sculptor Lysippos. Under Aratos, Sicyon joined the Achaean League in 251 B.C. By the time Pausanias visited the site, declining political fortunes and disastrous earthquakes had reduced it to a ruinous state.

label: Side
description: An ancient settlement on the southern coast of Asia Minor (modern Selimiye in Turkey).

label: Sidon/Col. Aurelia Pia
description: Sidon/Col. Aurelia Pia is an ancient maritime city and Phoenician metropolis

label: Signia
description: A city of Latium Adjectum established as a Latin colony ca. 494 B.C.

label: Sigus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 31 F4 Sigus

label: Sikinos (island)
description: A Cycladic island, with evidence for human habitation from the Early Cycladic period onward.

label: Sillyon
description: Sillyon was an ancient Graeco-Pamphylian fortress and city near Attaleia in Pamphylia, on the southern coast Asia Minor.

label: Simitthu
description: A city of Africa Proconsularis, Simitthu is especially noted for its marble quarries.

label: Sinai
description: The Sinai Peninsula is bounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north and the Red Sea to the south.

label: Sindos
description: A tell settlement, located 20km west of Thessaloniki.

label: Singidunum
description: An ancient settlement and Roman fort on the site of modern Belgrade in Serbia.

label: Singitikos Kolpos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B4 Singitikos Kolpos

label: Sinope
description: Sinope (modern Sinop, Turkey) on the Black Sea has been a major port since the time of the Hittites.

label: Sinzig
description: Modern Sinzig in Germany's Rheinland-Pfalz was the site of a Roman-era pottery manufacturing site. Scattered other Roman archaeological remains have been identified over the years, but a settlement center -- presumed to have been located on the Kirchhügel -- has not yet been positively located. BAtlas followed earlier scholarship in tentatively identifying this presumed settlement as "Sentiacum" or a variation on same by inferring backward in time on the basis of its earliest appearance in an 8th-century CE document of Pippin the Younger.

label: Siphnos (island)
description: The island of Siphnos has been inhabited since the Neolithic period and was a major center of Cycladic civilization.

label: Sirenes/Seirenoussai (islands)
description: Sirenes/Seirenoussai Inss. (modern Le Sirenuse or Li Galli) is an archipelago off the Amalfi Coast of Italy. In Greek mythology, the islands were home to the Sirens who tempted sailors, including Odysseus.

label: Sirmio
description: Modern Sirmione on Lake Garda.

label: Sirmium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 B5 Sirmium

label: Sirra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B2 Sirra

label: Sissû
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources. It is identified with modern Kozan (formerly Sis) and classical Sision.

label: Sithonia (peninsula)
description: The middle of the three peninsulas making up the Chalkidike.

label: Sitifis
description: An ancient site at modern Sétif in Algeria, originally founded as a colonial settlement for Roman veterans during the reign of the emperor Nerva.

label: Skarpheia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 D3 Skarpheia

label: Skiathos (settlement)
description: An ancient settlement on the Sporadic island of the same name, founded in the 6th or 5th century BCE.

label: Skotoussa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 D2 Skotoussa

label: Skotoussa (Thessaly)
description: An ancient settlement, abandoned by Pausanias' day.

label: Skydra
description: An ancient settlement, probably to be localized in the southern part of the modern Greek municipality of Skydra on the basis of epigraphic finds in the modern communities of the area, especially Arseni, Loutrokhoroi, and Marina (Papazoglou). A Hellenistic temple (q.v.) subsequently has been discovered much closer to the residential agglomeration of modern Skyra, but the precise location of the settlement remains elusive.

label: Skyllaion (promontory)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 F3 Skyllaion Pr.

label: Skyros (settlement)
description: Homonymous ancient settlement on Skyros island, co-located with the modern settlement. Habitation dates from the early Helladic onward.

label: Smintheion
description: Homer mentions the temple of Apollo Smintheus as the shrine where Chryses was priest. The second-century B.C. remains of an Ionic sanctuary with an adjacent town are located in the southwestern Troad near modern Gülpinar.

label: Smyrna/Eurydikeia
description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor, modern Izmir in Turkey.

label: So-called Arch of Hadrian (Capua)
description: The remains of a triple arch in opus latericium marking the pomerium of Capua. It is perhaps originally constructed under the Flavians.

label: Solimariaca
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F4 Solimariaca

label: Soloi/Aipeia?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 B2 Soloi/Aipeia?

label: Solous
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D2 Solous

label: Soluntum
description: An ancient settlement on the north-west coast of Sicily, some 16 km east of modern Palermo.

label: Solva
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F2 Solva

label: Sopianae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F3 Sopianae

label: Sora
description: An ancient city of Latium located in the valley of the Liris River that likely had Volscian origins. The Romans captured the city in 345 BCE and later established a colony there in 303 BCE after the Second Samnite War.

label: Soria
description: Soria is located on the Duero river in north-central Spain. Inhabited in pre-Roman times by the Arevaci, the site became prominent in the eleventh century as it was positioned near the border between Muslim-controlled lands and those controlled by Christians. It was absorbed into the Kingdom of León in 1134 and later (thirteenth century) belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

label: Sorviodunum
description: Sorviodunum (Old Sarum) is the site of pre-Roman habitation in Salisbury, England, where occupation began as early as 3,000 B.C. The oval Pre-Roman fort, covering some 11 ha, was re-used during the Roman and Norman periods.

label: Sos Höyük
description: An ancient settlement mound located within the boundaries of modern Yiğittaşı, Turkey, in eastern Anatolia.

label: Sostomagus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G2 Sostomagus

label: Sostrate/Shushtar
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 93 E1 Sostrate/Shushtar

label: Sounion (Attica: settlement and deme)
description: The fortified port settlement at Sounion, a coastal deme of Leontis, served the Athenian grain ships originating in Euboea and was the site of the sanctuary of Poseidon, among others.

label: Souppara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 5 C3 Souppara

label: Southwark
description: An extensive Roman settlement located on the south bank of the river Thames opposite Londinium.

label: Spalatum
description: Spalatum (modern Split, Croatia) is an ancient settlement on the Adriatic coast most noted for the palatial residence of the emperor Diocletian.

label: Sparta
description: Sparta was a prominent city-state (polis) of ancient Greece.

label: Speos Artemidos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 77 D1 Speos Artemidos

label: Spera
description: A Spanish village located in the north of Cádiz, between Sevilla and Cádiz, and that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Espera.

label: Sphakteria (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 B4 Sphakteria Ins.

label: Spoletium
description: An ancient city along the route of the Via Flaminia; an initial colony was established there in 241 BCE.

label: Sporades (archipelago)
description: An archipelago off the east coast of Greece in the Aegean Sea consisting of 24 islands.

label: Sri Lanka
description: The island of Sri Lanka lies at the center of the Indian Ocean world, connecting and connected by trade and communication with and between Africa, Arabia, southwest Asia, peninsular south Asia, Southeast Asia, Oceania, and beyond.

label: St-Aubin-sur-Gaillon
description: St-Aubin-sur-Gaillon was the site of a Gallo-Roman sanctuary.

label: St-Aubin-sur-Mer
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 7 F2 St-Aubin-sur-Mer

label: St-Béat
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F3 St-Béat (1)

label: St-Dié
description: St-Dié was the site of a Gallo-Roman settlement located on the Meurthe river.

label: St-Romain-de-Jalionas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 E2 St-Romain-de-Jalionas

label: Stabiae
description: An Oscan and Roman settlement located on the bay of Naples.

label: Stageira
description: An ancient city on the east coast of the Chalcidian peninsula. Birthplace of Aristotle.

label: Stagnum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 E7 Stagnum

label: Ste-Cécile Paleochristian Church
description: Remains of this paleochristian church, located at modern Loupian in Hérault, France, were discovered and excavated in the 1980s. The structure lies immediately north of the current church of Ste-Cécile, which dates to the 14th century.

label: Stobi
description: An ancient town of Paeonia that eventually became the capital of the Roman province of Macedonia Salutaris.

label: Stonehenge
description: An ancient formation of stones set in a field near Salisbury (Wiltshire County, England).

label: Stratonos Pyrgos/Caesarea
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 A4 Stratonos Pyrgos/Caesarea

label: Stratos
description: Stratos was the chief town of Acarnania. Modern Sourovigli in Greece.

label: Strongyle (island)
description: One of the eight Aeolian Islands, Strongyle Ins. is one of the three active volcanoes in Italy.

label: Strophades/Plotai (island group)
description: The modern Strophades/Strofades islands (Stamfani and Arpi): an Ionian island group mentioned in Vergil and other ancient sources.

label: Strymon (river)
description: The modern Sturma river originates in what is now Bulgaria, flows through the ancient region of Thrace, and empties into the Aegean Sea.

label: Strymonikos Kolpos
description: Strymonikos Kolpos (the Strymonian Gulf)

label: Styra
description: Styra was an ancient port city located in the southwestern part of Euboea that possessed also an inland acropolis (on the modern peak of Hagios Nikolaos), extensive quarries, and a series of large stone structures known today as drakospita (dragon's houses).

label: Suana
description: Suana (Sovana) has Etruscan origins but later became a Roman municipium. In the fifth century A.D. it became an episcopal see.

label: Sufetula
description: Sufetula, the modern Sbeitla, was founded in the later first century A.D. and was located at a major road junction.

label: Sulmo
description: A chief settlement of the Peligni that was ravaged by the Carthaginians during the Second Punic War.

label: Sultanahmet Camii
description: The Sultanahmet Camii (The Blue/Sultan Ahmed Mosque) was built on the primary site of the Great Palace of Constantinople between 1609 and 1616 during the rule of Ahmed I.

label: Sumelocenna
description: Sumelocenna was a Roman settlement on the Neckar river that was the seat of the procurator of the saltus Sumelocennensis during the late first century AD.

label: Surae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 B4 Surae

label: Susa/Seleucia ad Eulaeum
description: An ancient city of the Elamite, Persian, and Parthian empires of Iran. Located at modern Shush, Susa was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2015.

label: Sybaris (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 46 D2 Sybaris fl.

label: Sybaris/Thurii/Copia
description: Sybaris was an ancient city of Magna Graecia founded as an Achaean colony as early as 720 BCE on a plain that was drained by both the Crati and Sybaris rivers. Greeks from Kroton destroyed Sybaris ca. 510 BCE. Following this destruction, two successive cities, Thurii and Copia, respectively, were established on the same site. This topic is of particular interest to ancient authors, at least 70 of whom mention it.

label: Sybota (islands)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 B3 Sybota Inss.

label: Sychem
description: An ancient settlement in the Levant, attested Biblically and in ancient Egyptian documents and the Amarna letters. Scholars associate this settlement with the archaeological site of Tel Balata, which is located in the modern West Bank and has seen attention from archaeologists since the early 20th century.

label: Syene
description: The ancient city of Swenett in Egypt, called Syene by the Greeks.

label: Syme
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 F4 Syme

label: Syme (island)
description: An island located off the coast of Caria, some 24 km north of Rhodes.

label: Syna M.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 76 D4 Syna M.

label: Syracusae/Syrakousai
description: An important ancient city on the island of Sicily.

label: Syria
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 1 K3 Syria

label: Syria (Roman imperial province)
description: The Roman imperial province of Syria.

label: Syria Coele
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 101 P4 Syria Coele

label: Syros
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A5 Syros

label: Syros (island)
description: Syros is an island in the Cyclades in the Aegean Sea. Human settlement on Syros began at least 5,000 years ago with the so-called Kastri culture.

label: Syrtis Minor
description: The Gulf of Gabès.

label: Syspiritis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 F4 Syspiritis

label: T(o)maros (mountain)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 C2 T(o)maros M.

label: Ta' Ħaġrat Temple Complex
description: Ta' Ħaġrat is a megalithic temple complex on the island of Malta (ca. 3600-3000 B.C.), included in the UNESCO World Heritage List.

label: Tabrīz
description: A large, modern city in northwest Iran with archaeological and textual evidence for dating potentially as early as the 9th or 8th century BCE.

label: Tacape
description: Tacape (modern Gabès) was a commercial city located on the Lesser Syrtis.

label: Tainaron (settlement)
description: An ancient settlement, located near the tip of a southern peninsula of the Peloponnese (modern Cape Matapon in Greece). The site featured a sanctuary of Poseidon and served as both a port and a mercenary staging and recruitment area at least as early as the Classical period.

label: Takrit/Birta
description: Ancient Birta (or Birtha) was a fortress on the Tigris river that may have been established by Alexander the Great.

label: Tall Ḥamūkār
description: Tall Ḥamūkār is a large archaeological site located in the Jazira region of northeastern Syria close to the Iraqi border. The site may be one of the world's earliest urban centers. A place from the TAVO Index.

label: Tamassos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 C2 Tamassos

label: Tamiathis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 F2 Tamiathis

label: Tamion?
description: Tamion? (modern Cardiff, Wales). A series of Roman forts occupied the same site in Cardiff, located on a river terrace adjacent to the River Taff, and represent continuous occupation from the late 50s AD until the late fourth century.

label: Tamuda
description: Tamuda was a city of Mauretania Tingitana. Pliny hints at a pre-Roman settlement that has been confirmed archaeologically.

label: Tamuda (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 28 D2 Tamuda fl.

label: Tanagra
description: Tanagra was an ancient settlement of Boeotia.

label: Tanais
description: Tanais (located near modern Nedvigovska) was a city of the third century B.C. founded on the banks of the Tanais river by Bosporanian Greeks.

label: Tanais (river)
description: The modern Don River.

label: Tanis
description: An important settlement in the eastern Nile delta (modern San el-Hagar), Tanis boasted a massive temple precinct and was the burial site for Egyptian kings of the 21st and 22nd dynasties.

label: Taparura
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 G3 Taparura

label: Taq-i Bustan
description: Site in western Iran with a series of Sassanid rock reliefs carved in the fourth century A.D.

label: Taramptos (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 E3 Taramptos Ins.

label: Taras/Tarentum/Neptunia
description: A Greek colonial city founded in 706 B.C.

label: Tarba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 Tarba

label: Tarnis (river)
description: The Tarn river.

label: Tarsos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 52 G3 Tarsos

label: Tarsus/Antiochia ad Cydnum
description: An important city and river port on the Cydnus river located in Cilicia Pedias.

label: Tarvenna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C2 Tarvenna

label: Tarvisium
