description: Tarvisium (Treviso) is a settlement located in the plain of the Silis river, not far from the Via Claudia Augusta.

label: Tarxien (Malta)
description: A megalithic temple complex that was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980. This temple dates to the later Neolithic period on Malta and remained in use for several millennia. The first usage of the site occurs ca. 4100 BC and the temple complex develops across the fourth millennium.

label: Tas-Silġ
description: A hilltop on Malta that is the locus of multi-period settlement and religious activity from the Neolithic period to late antiquity.

label: Tasciaca?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G1 Tasciaca?

label: Tasg(a)etium
description: A fort and vicus located on the Rhine near the southwest end of Lake Constance. A military outpost was created here in the early first century. The site was likely abandoned at the beginning of the fifth century.

label: Taurike Chersonesos
description: The Crimean Peninsula, located in the northern Black Sea.

label: Tauromenium
description: Tauromenium was an ancient city in Sicily founded in 358 B.C.

label: Taurunum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 21 C5 Taurunum

label: Taurus (mountain range)
description: The Taurus Mountains in southern Turkey, the modern Toros Dağları.

label: Tavia (river)
description: A river flowing from Alpes Maritimae and emptying into the Ligusticum Mare near Costa Bellene.

label: Taxila
description: An ancient city with the ruins of the Gandhāran city of Takṣaśilā, an important Hindu and Buddhist center. (cited: BAtlas 6 C3 Taxila)

label: Tbilisi
description: Tbilisi, the modern capital of Georgia, was the ancient Tiflīs and was founded in A.D. 455 or 458 when the capital of Georgia was transferred from Mtsk̲h̲eta.

label: Teate
description: Originally named Teate Marrucinorum, Teate (modern Chieti) was the principal settlement of the Marrucini. Strabo attributes its origins to Arcadian Greeks.

label: Tebtynis/Theodosioupolis?
description: An ancient Egyptian settlement located near the modern village of Tell Umm el-Baragat in the Al Fayyum Governorate. Tebtunis was founded by Amenemhat III around 1800 BC and flourished during the Ptolemaic period.

label: Tegea
description: Tegea was an ancient city of Arcadia. It is especially noted for its sanctuary dedicated to Athena Alea.

label: Tehrān
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Teichion?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B4 Teichion?

label: Tel Bet Yerah/Khirbet el-Kerak
description: An ancient settlement, represented by a massive mound located on the southern coast of the Sea of Galilee, now partly covered by modern structures. Recurrent periods of habitation on the site date from at least the third milennium BCE to Islamic times.

label: Tel Hazor
description: Tel Hazor (Hebrew: תל חצור‎‎) is an archaeological site located in the southern Hula Valley overlooking Lake Merom. From the Middle Bronze Age to the Israelite period in the ninth century B.C., Hazor was the largest fortified city in the region. It served as a commercial center with links to Babylon and Syria. In the Book of Joshua, Hazor is described as “the head of all those kingdoms” (Josh. 11:10).

label: Tel Michal
description: A site on the Mediterranean coast of Israel with signs of habitation from the Middle Bronze Age and the Persian through the Roman periods. In the Hellenistic and Roman periods, its purpose was primarily military, and a series of forts occupied the site until around 50 CE. A small watchtower or lighthouse was built on the site in the eighth-ninth centuries CE, after which it was abandoned.

label: Tel Shiqmona
description: An ancient settlement located near the coast of the modern city of Haifa, Israel. Archaeological evidence indicates habitation there from the late Bronze Age through the late Byzantine period. Strabo describes the city as a ruin in his time.

label: Tel Yokneam
description: Settlement in northern Palestine inhabited from the Early Bronze Age through the Mamluk period.

label: Tell Beydar
description: Tell Beydar (ancient Nabada) is an archaeological site in NE Syria that was first settled ca. 2600 BC.

label: Tell Bismaya
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 91 G5 Tell Bismaya

label: Tell Brak
description: Tell Brak, located in the Upper Khabur of northeastern Syria, was occupied between the sixth and second millennia BCE. The tell stands ca. 40 m tall and covers ca. 130 hectares.

label: Tell Chuēra/Harbe
description: Tell Chuēra (also known as Tall Dahr ash Shuwayrah), a settlement in northern Syria inhabited from the fourth to third millennia BCE. A small settlement, called Harbe, was built on the site during the Middle Assyrian period.

label: Tell Jerablus Tahtani
description: Jerablus Tahtani is a multi-period settlement located south of Carchemish. Excavation has revealed evidence related to the Uruk expansion in the fourth millennium B.C. as well as evidence of the "second urban revolution" in Early Bronze Age Syria. The Bronze Age fortified site is built atop remains of a third millennium B.C. phase. Numerous tombs and stratified mortuary deposits have been excavated, including a prominent tomb near the entrance to the Bronze Age settlement.

label: Tell Qasile
description: Archaeological site on the Yarkon River in modern Tel Aviv, identified as a Philistine city inhabited during the 12th and 11th centuries BCE.

label: Tell al-Fūl
description: An archaeological site in East Jerusalem, identified as a possible location for the ancient sites of Gibeah or Perath/Parah.

label: Tell al-Ubaid
description: Tell al-'Ubaid is a small tell located west of Ur.

label: Tell el-Heir
description: An ancient site in the Sinai that was the location of a series of successive fortresses from the Persian through the Roman periods. It may be identifiable with the Greek name Magdolos and/or the Hebrew name Migdol. There is also some speculation that much earlier textual evidence for a fortification of Ramses III should be tied to this site as well.

label: Tell el-Hesi
description: Archaeological site located in southern Palestine with signs of habitation (with gaps) from the late Neolithic through the Hellenistic period, as well as burials from Late Antiquity.

label: Tell-i Zohak/Pasa?/Bashiyan?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 F4 Tell-i Zohak/Pasa?/Bashiyan?

label: Telo Martius
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 A3 Telo Martius

label: Telos (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 E5 Telos Ins.

label: Telos (settlement)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 E5 Telos

label: Temenion
description: Temenion was located in the Argolid. It was built by Temenus, the son of Aristomachus. Temenion lay 50 stades from Nauplia and 26 from Argos.

label: Temple of Aphaia on Aegina
description: An ancient sanctuary on the island of Aegina, dedicated to the autochthonous deity Aphaia.

label: Temple of Concordia, Agrigento
description: The Temple of Concord, located in the so-called "Valle dei Templi" of Agrigento, dates ca. 440-430 B.C.

label: Temple of Hera I (the "Basilica")
description: An Archaic Doric temple probably dedicated to Hera in the central urban sanctuary of Paestum/Poseidonia.

label: Temple of Mercurius
description: A Gallo-Roman temple of Mercurius, located atop the modern Puy-de-Dôme, commune Orcines in France.

label: Templebrough
description: At Templebrough, an archaeological sequence of three superimposed Roman forts and a vicus was discovered. The first fort dates ca. A.D. 43.

label: Tenedo
description: Tenedo lies at the confluence of the Aare and the Rhine. In pre-Roman times, a key trade route crossed the River Rhine here.

label: Tenedos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 C2 Tenedos

label: Tenedos (island)
description: An island located in the Aegean Sea 5 km off the coast of Troas. Modern Bozcaada.

label: Tenos (island)
description: Tenos Ins. (Tinos) is an island in the Aegean Sea and part of the Cyclades archipelago.

label: Tenos (settlement)
description: Ancient homonymous settlement on the Aegean island of Tenos (modern Tinos/Chora).

label: Tentyra
description: The Ptolemaic temple to Hathor at Dendera.

label: Teos
description: An ancient Ionian settlement of Asia Minor, located at modern Siğacik in Turkey.

label: Tergeste
description: Tergeste (the modern Trieste) was first a vicus dependent on Aquileia (ca. 100 BC) and later became a colony under Caesar, sometime before 52 B.C. In the Augustan reorganization of Italy, the city was part of the Decima Regio and then of Venetia et Histria. By Late Antiquity, it had become a bishopric.

label: Tericiae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 D2 Tericiae

label: Teriolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 D2 Teriolis

label: Termessos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 D4 Termessos

label: Terrace and altar of M. Nonius Balbus
description: Marcus Nonius Balbus of Nuceria was an important civic patron of Herculaneum. Balbus was a praetor and proconsul of Crete and Cyrene and served as tribune of the plebs in 32 B.C. This architectural complex near the Suburban Baths included the terrace as well as an honorific statue and altar.

label: Teurnia
description: Teurnia, on the Drau river, was an ancient settlement of Noricum.

label: Teutoburgium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 F4 Teutoburgium

label: Thabraca
description: Thabraca was a maritime city of Numidia located at the mouth of the river Tusca.

label: Thala
description: Thala (Tell Halif) is a small tell located in the northeastern Negev desert, near the modern town of Lahav. The site shows signs of habitation from the Chalcolithic through the Medieval and Ottoman periods.

label: Thala
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 33 C1 Thala

label: Thalamai
description: The site of Thalamai was evidently in an area known in modern times as Svina, in the eastern portion of modern Thalames/Koutiphari on the west side of the Mani peninsula at the base of the Taygetos mountains. Evidence for human habitation here stretches back to the Neolithic. In ancient times, this Laconian/Messenian settlement was home to Spartan perioikoi and, according to Pausanias, was the site of an oracle of Ino/Pasiphae.

label: Thamugadi
description: A Roman colonial town founded in the Aurès Mountains of Algeria by the Emperor Trajan around AD 100. The city's full name was Colonia Marciana Ulpia Traiana Thamugadi. Trajan named the city in commemoration of his mother Marcia, eldest sister Ulpia Marciana, and father Marcus Ulpius Traianus.

label: Thapsus
description: An ancient settlement and port, located at modern Ras Dimass in the Tunisian municipality of Bekalta (Monastir). Habitation at the site dates to at least the 6th century BCE and continued through the Byzantine and into the Islamic period, but it appears that the main settlement itself relocated to Bekalta in medieval times.

label: Thasos (island)
description: The Aegean island of Thasos.

label: Thasos (settlement)
description: Greeks from Paros founded a colony on Thasos in the middle of the seventh century B.C.

label: The Great Pyramid
description: The Great Pyramid of Khufu was built ca. 2580–2560 B.C. during the 4th dynasty of ancient Egypt. It initially stood to a height of 146.5 meters (481 feet).

label: The Great Sphinx
description: A monumental limestone sphinx situated on the Giza plateau, likely connected with the reign of Pharaoh Khafre.

label: Theater of Dionysus Eleuthereus
description: Theatre on the south slope of the Acropolis in Athens.

label: Theatrum Marcelli
description: Theatrum Marcelli (Theater of Marcellus) is an ancient Roman theater in the Circus Flaminius. Augustus completed its construction and dedicated it in 12 BC.

label: Thebai/Thebae
description: The ancient city of Thebes in Boeotia (modern Greece).

label: Theisoa
description: An ancient settlement of Arcadia. The archaeological site of the ancient acropolis is located at and around the thirteenth century Frankish castle, just south of modern Theisoa.

label: Thelepte
description: Thelepte was a Roman city in Africa Byzacena. It achieved municipal status perhaps in the time of Vespasian and became a colonia under Trajan. The city played an important administrative role in fourth century AD north Africa.

label: Theline/Col. Arelate/Constantina
description: An ancient settlement located at modern Arles in France.

label: Theodosia
description: A Greek colony founded by Miletus in the sixth century BC.

label: Thera
description: An ancient settlement located atop the modern Messavouno mountain on the island that shared its name in antiquity (modern Thira/Santorini).

label: Thera (island)
description: An island of the southern Aegean Sea, Thera is the southernmost of the Cyclades. The island's present form is the result of a Middle Bronze Age volcanic eruption that destroyed a Minoan settlement on the island.

label: Theranda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 49 C1 Theranda

label: Therasia (island)
description: Therasia is the the second largest island of the Santorini Archipelago. It was separated from Thera by the Thera eruption.

label: Therasia?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 61 A5 Therasia?

label: Thermae Antoninianae
description: The Thermae Antoninianae, commonly known as the Baths of Caracalla, were built in Rome between AD 212 and 216.

label: Thermae Himeraeae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Thermae Himeraeae

label: Therme
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 50 C3 Therme

label: Thermon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B3 Thermon

label: Thermopylae
description: Thermopylae is the name of a narrow pass leading from Thessaly into Locris. It was the site of a pivotal battle during the Graeco-Persian wars in 480 BC.

label: Thespiai
description: Thespiai was an ancient city of Boeotia, located at the foot of Mt. Helicon.

label: Thessalia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 D4 no. 9 (Thessalia)

label: Thessalia (late Roman province)
description: A late province of the Roman empire according to the Verona List (ca. 303-324 CE), subordinate to the diocese of Moesiae.

label: Thessalonica
description: A city of northern Greece founded by Cassander of Macedon ca. 315 BCE; an important center of the Roman and Late Antique worlds.

label: Theveste
description: Theveste (modern Tébessa, Algeria) became a Roman center and, in the Imperial period, the Legio III Augusta was raised there. In later times Theveste is connected with the Donatists.

label: This
description: The capital city of the first dynasties of ancient Egypt. While the precise location of the ancient site is unclear, mainstream scholarly thought places it near ancient Abydos and modern Girga.

label: Thisbe
description: Thisbe was an ancient town of Boeotia located on the southern flank of Mt. Helicon.

label: Thmouis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 74 F3 Thmouis

label: Thoknia
description: An ancient settlement of Arcadia mentioned by Pausanias and catalogued by Stephanus of Byzantium. Long identified with ancient remains in the vicinity of modern Thoknia (previously Bromosellas/Vromosellas), but those remains seem largely to have disappeared in the course of extensive modern lignite mining in the vicinity.

label: Thorikos
description: Thorikos was a coastal deme of the tribe Akamantis, in southeastern Attica. A significant Mycenaean prescence existed at the site during the Bronze Age.

label: Thospia/Bouana/‘Ospa’/Ṭušpa
description: Ṭušpa is an Urartian fortress and settlement near the historic center of Van in southeastern Turkey. Here archaeological remains of buildings and inscribed objects of several Urartian kings starting with Sarduri I (ninth century BCE) have been found. Furthermore, the place is frequently mentioned in Urartian inscriptions in connection with the god Haldi, who is addressed as "Lord of Ṭušpa-City". Ṭupša is often referred to as the capital of Urartu, although this remains uncertain. Rather than an administrative center, it was probably a religious one. In later times the place was known as Thospia/Bouana/‘Ospa’ (BAtlas 89 F2 Thospia/Bouana/‘Ospa’). Today the ruins of the fortress are referred to as Van Kalesi (or Van Castle).

label: Thospitis Limne
description: Lake Van, the largest lake in Asia Minor, is a saline soda lake.

label: Thouria
description: Thouria is a settlement of the Peloponnese, with archaeological evidence ranging in date from the Bronze Age to the Roman period. The nature of the archaic and classical polity is debated in the sources. The ancient site is located in the vicinity of modern Aithaia/Hellenika, about 3 kilometers north of modern Thouria.

label: Thrake
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 102 E3 no. 3 (Thrake)

label: Thuburbo Maius
description: An ancient settlement with extensive archaeological remains, located north across the river Kebir from the modern city of El Fahs in Tunisia.

label: Thuburbo Minus
description: A settlement in Africa Proconsularis, mentioned in the Itinerarium Antonini and the Tabula Peutingeriana.

label: Thugga/Tokai?
description: Thugga/Tokai? (Dougga) is an ancient site in Tunisia with a rich heritage that includes Numidian-Berber, Punic, ancient Roman, and Byzantine phases. The city's Roman phase is particularly well preserved and UNESCO listed the site as a World Heritage Site in 1997.

label: Thusuros
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 34 G4 Thusuros

label: Thyamis Pr.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 54 B2 Thyamis Pr.

label: Thyrides
description: A promontory on the west side of the central southern peninsula of the Peloponnese in Greece.

label: Thysdrus
description: Thysdrus (modern El Djem, Tunisia) was a Punic and Roman city of North Africa. It flourished in the second century A.D. and built its massive amphitheater in the third century. After an abortive revolt in A.D. 238, the city was destroyed by soldiers loyal to Maximinus Thrax.

label: Tiber Island
description: An island in the Tiber River at the site of Rome.

label: Tiberiadis Mare/Gennesar Lacus
description: The Sea of Galilee, also known as the Sea of Tiberias, is the largest freshwater lake in Israel.

label: Tiberias
description: Tiberias was founded by Herod Antipas ca. 20 BC.

label: Tibur
description: A Sabine town, 30 km east-north-east of Rome, Tibur was the seat of the Tiburtine Sibyl.

label: Tichilla
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 D3 Tichilla

label: Ticinum
description: An ancient city of Gallia Transpadana, Ticinum lay along the line of the ancient Via Aemilia. Today, Ticinum is the modern city of Pavia.

label: Tienen
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 E2 Tienen

label: Tifernum Tiberinum
description: An Umbrian hilltown in the floodplain of the Tiber river north of Perusia.

label: Tigris/Diglitus (river)
description: The Tigris river, one of the two great rivers that define Mesopotamia, flows 1,850 km from the Taurus Mountains to the Persian Gulf.

label: Til/Thiloson Kome
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 B1 Til/Thiloson Kome

label: Tios/Tieion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 86 C2 Tios/Tieion

label: Tipasa
description: Tipasa was an ancient Punic trading-post conquered by Rome and turned into a strategic base for the conquest of the kingdoms of Mauritania.

label: Tiryns
description: A fortified Mycenaean center in the Argolid that flourished between 1400 and 1200 B.C.

label: Tit(i)us/Katarbates (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 C6 Tit(i)us/Katarbates fl.

label: Titane
description: An ancient settlement, long known to have been located near the modern town of Titani in Greece. It has been the subject of intensive archaeological excavation and survey only in the 21st century. The acropolis, of which significant fortification walls remain visible, is now occupied in part by the Church of Ag. Tryphon.

label: Tithorea/Neon
description: An ancient city on the southern edge of the Kephissos plain. Known in modern times as Velitsa, the Greek village overlying the ancient site changed its name to Tithorea in the 1920s.

label: Tithronion
description: An ancient city of Phocis in Greek, which according to Pausanias was burned by Xerxes. Modern consensus places its acropolis at an unexcavated paliokastro north of modern Ano Kalivia, just inside the southern boundary of the Kapenitsa-Vertzianou-Amfikleia protected area.

label: Titkois
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 77 D1 Titkois

label: Titulcia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 24 H4 Titulcia

label: Tlos
description: An ancient settlement of Lykia, located two kilometers due east of the modern village of Düğer in Turkey's Mugla province.

label: Toletum
description: Ancient Toletum, located on the Tagus River, was the main settlement of the Carpetani. The Romans captured the city in 193 B.C. In 507, Toletum became the capital of the Visigothic Kingdom, and in 711 it fell to Muslim invaders. Alfonso VI of León and Castile recaptured the city in 1085.

label: Tolosa
description: Tolosa (modern Toulouse) was a city of Gallia Narbonensis and the metropolis of the Volcae Tectosages.

label: Tomb of Cossinia
description: A Roman tomb on the right bank of the Anio discovered in 1929. The tomb dates to the first century A.D. and is associated with Cossinia, a priestess of the cult of Vesta.

label: Tomis
description: Tomis was founded as a Greek colony on the Black Sea coast ca. 600 B.C.

label: Topeiros (Paradeisos)
description: There is evidence for human habitation from the Neolithic onward In and around Paradeisos, a modern Greek village in the Nestos municipality of Kavala, Macedonia and Thrace. Long-standing scholarly consensus holds that these remains are to be identified with the well-attested ancient settlement of Topeiros, although BAtlDir registers slight hesitation (question mark).

label: Torone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B5 Torone

label: Torre de Hércules
description: A lighthouse that has served as a marker for the La Coruña harbor since the late first century AD.

label: Torre del Campo
description: A Spanish village located in the west of the province of Jaén that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today it is known as Torredelcampo.

label: Torres de Auençala
description: Torres de Auençala was a rural castle located in the west of Jaén. This type of settlement consisted of a fortified perimeter and small tower. This site belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X (thirteenth century). Today the site is known as Torre Venzalá and is located in Torredonjimeno.

label: Tou Batou
description: A monastery built by order of Emperor Justinian I. St. Catherine's at the foot of Mount Sinai in modern Egypt.

label: Toulon-sur-Allier
description: A Gallo-Roman pottery manufacturing center produdcing white clay statuettes as well as terra sigillata.

label: Touphion
description: Touphion is located on the east bank of the Nile River about 20 km south of Thebes. The ruins of a multi-period temple initially built by Sesostris I were found there.

label: Tragilos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 51 B3 Tragilos

label: Tragurium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 20 D6 Tragurium

label: Traiectum
description: Traiectum (modern Utrecht) was a fortified site along the Roman frontier (limes) of Germania Inferior. It may have been a crossing point on the Rhine river.

label: Traiectus?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F2 Traiectus?

label: Tralleis (in Lydia)
description: An ancient settlement, thought to have been located somewhere in Lydia. Not to be confused with Lydia/Seleuceia on the Maeander whose extensive site has been excavated at modern Aydın.

label: Tralles/Dia/Seleuceia ad Maeandrum/Kaisareia
description: Tralles/Dia/Seleuceia ad Maeandrum/Kaisareia was an ancient city founded by Argives and Trallians that then fell under the sway of the Persian Empire and, later, Hellenistic kings.

label: Trapezus
description: An ancient settlement of Asia Minor on the south coast of the Black Sea. Modern Trabzon in Turkey.

label: Trasumennus (Lake)
description: Trasumennus lacus (modern Lake Trasimeno) is the largest lake of the Italian peninsula and the site of a major engagement of the Second Punic War on June 21, 217 B.C.

label: Trebiae
description: Trebiae was an ancient city of Umbria (regio IV) located near the line of the Via Flaminia. It is identified with modern Trevi, north of Spoleto in Italy.

label: Tremithous
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 72 D2 Tremithous

label: Tretos? (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 60 A1 Tretos? Ins.

label: Trevignano
description: Trevignano Romano, located on the shores of Lake Bracciano, lies some 47 km from Rome. Archaeological evidence for Etruscan occupation, in the form of tombs dating to the eighth - sixth centuries B.C., has been discovered to the north of the modern town. A medieval castle was built there under Innocent III ca. 1200.

label: Trevinano
description: Trevinano is a human settlement in Italy, located in the Province of Viterbo of northern Lazio. In antiquity the site was settled by Etruscans. In the eleventh century, the powerful Boncompagni-Ludovisi family built a castle there.

label: Trichonion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 55 B3 Trichonion

label: Trident(i)um
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 I1 Trident(i)um

label: Trikorynthos
description: Trikorynthos was an ancient deme of Attica.

label: Trikrana (island)
description: An ancient island mentioned by Pausanias, it can be identified with the modern Trikeri.

label: Trileukoi (islands)
description: Small, rocky islets in Galicia located adjacent to Cabo Ortegal.

label: Tripolis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 87 D4 Tripolis

label: Tripolis
place_type: urban, theatre, fort-group, pass, cemetery, bath, church, settlement, temple, road
description: The Phoenicians established a commercial outpost at Tripolis (Tripoli) in the ninth century BC. An independent city during the Hellenistic period, Tripolis came under Roman control in 64 BC.

label: Trogitis
description: Known now as Lake Suğla, or in Turkish, Suğla Gölü, the ancient Trogitis is a lake that is located in Turkey's Konya Province.

label: Troizen
description: An ancient settlement, located in the Peloponnese.

label: Tropaeum Augusti/Alpium Tropaeum/Alpis Summa/Alpis Maritima
description: A victory monument built by Augustus (5 B.C.) to commemorate the subjugation of the tribes of the western Alps. The Romans considered the spot to be "In Alpe Maritima".

label: Tropaeum Traiani (settlement)
description: Civitas Tropaensium was a Roman castrum settled by Roman veterans of the Dacian Wars. Constantine I rebuilt the city after it was destroyed by the Goths and it survived until the Avars sacked it in A.D. 587.

label: Trysa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 C5 Trysa

label: Tucci/Col. Augusta Gemella
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 B4 Tucci/Col. Augusta Gemella

label: Tuledo (mountain)
description: A mountain in the Ligurian Apennines cited in the Sententia Minuciorum; the modern Monte Leco.

label: Tullum
description: Tullum was the capital of the civitas Leucorum.

label: Tunes
description: Tunes was a Libyan city in Africa Proconsularis. Rome prevailed in a land battle south of Tunes in 256 BC during the First Punic War.

label: Turenum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 45 D2 Turenum

label: Turicum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 A2 Turicum

label: Turkdean
description: Site of a major Roman villa complex in Gloucestershire, active from late second century CE until the end of the fourth century.

label: Turnacum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D2 Turnacum

label: Turris Libisonis
description: A settlement of northwestern Sardinia, located at the mouth of the Mannu River. The site served as a port in Phoenician, Carthaginian, and Roman phases of occupation. The modern Porto Torres stands on the site, about 10 miles distant from Sassari.

label: Tuscan Archipelago
description: A chain of islands between the Ligurian Sea and Tyrrhenian Sea.

label: Tuscana
description: An ancient city that traced its legendary origins to Ascanius, son of Aeneas. The site became an important Etruscan mercantile center and eventually achieved Roman municipal status in 88 B.C.

label: Tusculum
description: Tusculum was a Latin city of the Alban Hills in central Italy. After 381 B.C., Tusculum became the first "municipium cum suffragio".

label: Tyana/Col. Aurelia Antoniniana
description: An ancient city of Cappadocia that was the capital of the Neo-Hittite kingdom in the first millennium B.C.

label: Tylisos
description: An ancient settlement of north-central Crete. Archaeological and textual evidence indicates the site was inhabited from the bronze age through at least the early Roman empire.

label: Tyndaris
description: An ancient city on the north coast of Sicily. Modern Tindari.

label: Tyras/Ophioussa
description: A Black Sea colony founded by Miletus.

label: Tyros
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 58 D3 Tyros

label: Tyrus/Col. Septimia Severa
description: The ancient city of Tyre (modern es-Sur on the coast of Lebanon). A UNESCO World Heritage Site, in part because of its "important archaeological remains, mainly from Roman times."

label: Tẹl Ȧviv
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Ucetia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 C1 Ucetia

label: Ugernum
description: Ugernum was a waypoint on the Via Domitia located on the right bank of the Rhodanus fl.

label: Ulcisia Castra/Castra Constantia
description: A Roman fort on the Pannonian Limes, at modern Szentendre in Hungary.

label: Umbret
description: An ancient and medieval Spanish village located to the west of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Its modern name is Umbrete.

label: Umbria (region)
description: The eponymous region of the Umbri, an ancient Italic people who spoke the Umbrian language. The physical geography of the landlocked region is hilly and dominated by the Appennine Mountains.

label: Umbro (river)
description: A river of Etruria that flows from Castelnuovo Berardenga to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

label: Unnamed Gallo-Roman villa (Antone, Cm. Pierre-Buffière)
description: A Gallo-Roman site located at the Villa d'Antone was partially excavated in 1931.

label: Unnamed Gallo-Roman villa (Petit-Bersac)
description: The remains of a large Gallo-Roman villa covering some 4 ha have been identified and studied at Petit-Bersac.

label: Unnamed Villa in Castelferrus
description: An unnamed Gallo-Roman villa located in the modern French commune of Castelferrus.

label: Unnamed settlement at Sampuy
description: An extensive Roman-era settlement identified via aerial photography and archaeological survey in the modern French commune of Mérouville.

label: Unnamed villa in Martizay
description: An ancient villa located in the modern French village of Martizay.

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E2 no. 7 (Labastide d’Armagnac)

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 E2 no. 21 (Jurançon)

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G1 no. 32 (Labastide-du-Temple)

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 no. 47 (Puységur)

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G2 no. 65 (Lézat-sur-Lèze)

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G2 no. 66 (Marquefave)

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 no. 85 (Pujo)

label: Untitled
description: A fourth-century Gallo-Roman villa was excavated in 1967.

label: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 F2 no. 88 (St-Loup)

label: Ur(i)
description: A major Sumerian city-state founded during the Ubaid period, ca. 3800 B.C. In archaeological terms, Ur is particularly well known for the lavish tombs of its Royal Cemetery, its massive Ziggurat. The site served as the capital of the Ur III dynasty.

label: Urartu
description: An eastern Anatolian kingdom on the eastern shore of Lake Van. Originating from a regional collection of principalities first mentioned in the 13th century BCE, it had become a single political entity by the 9th century BCE. Urartu was a powerful rival to the Neo-Assyrian Empire. It ceased to exist sometime in the late 7th or early 6th century BCE.

label: Urba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 18 D3 Urba

label: Urgao/Vircao
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 A4 Urgao/Vircao

label: Urgellum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 G3 Urgellum

label: Urgo/Gorgon (island)
description: The northernmost island in the Tuscan Archipelago.

label: Uria
description: An ancient city of the Messapii.

label: Ursaria (island)
description: An island off the Croatian coast in the Adriatic Sea, now known as Sveti Juraj (San Giorgio).

label: Urso/Col. Genetiva Iulia
description: At the modern town of Osuna in Spain's Seville province, archaeological investigation has revealed an extensive Roman-era settlement. In 2022, an earlier "Phoenician" necropolis was discovered.

label: Uruk/Orchoe/Erech/Orikut
description: Uruk was an ancient Sumerian (and later Babylonian) city located on the Euphrates river. At its height (ca. 2900 BC), Uruk's population may have topped 50,000 people and its walls enclosed an area of more than six square kilometers, making it the largest city in the world at that point in time.

label: Usel(l)is
description: A Roman colonia in western Sardinia.

label: Userca
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G3 Userca

label: Usha
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 69 B4 Usha

label: Ustica (island)
description: An island in the Tyrrhenian Sea occupied since the middle of the second millennium B.C. when Phoenician traders were present there.

label: Utica
description: A Punic center located west of Carthage.

label: Uxacona
description: A Roman site with evidence for a series of ditched enclosures of the first century.

label: Uxama (Argaela)
description: Uxama Argaela was a Celtiberian settlement of the Arevaci. The site was subsequently conquered by the Romans.

label: Uxellodunum
description: Uxellodunum was an oppidum on the Dordogne river in the territory of the Cardurci tribe, mentioned by Caesar. Although Uxellodunum has been widely identified since the 19th century with the Gallic site at modern Puy d'Issolu (French commune of Vayrac, near the village of Saint-Denis-lès-Martel) -- and a commision of the French culture ministry officially confirmed this identification in 2001 -- a number of other sites are possible matches (see further sub "Details").

label: Uxelodu(nu)m
description: Roman fort on Hadrian's wall in Stanwix.

label: Uzalis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 32 F2 Uzalis

label: Uzita
description: Uzita was a settlement of Byzacium located south of Hadrumetum.

label: Valencihuela
description: A Spanish village located in the east of the province of Córdoba, near Jaén, that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today it is known as Valenzuela.

label: Valentia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 27 E2 Valentia

label: Valladolid
description: The site of Celtiberian and Roman settlement eventually gave way to Moorish and, later, Christian foundations. Valladolid grew rapidly during the twelfth and thirteenth centuries under the kings Alfonso VIII and Alfonso X.

label: Valley Temple of Khafre
description: The Valley Temple associated with the pyramid of Khafre. The Valley Temple is linked to the pyramid and its mortuary temple via a causeway.

label: Vani
description: Vani (7th -1st centuries BCE) is an ancient city located in the Colchis Lowlands on the western bank of the Sulori River.

label: Vasio
description: Vasio (modern Vaison-la-Romaine) was the civitas capital of the Vocontii and eventually received Roman status by the late first century BC.

label: Vatl/Vetulonia
description: The Etruscan Vatluna resisted Rome's influence in the seventh century BCE, although the city may have been the source of Rome's adoption of the curule chair and the fasces.

label: Vectis (island)
description: Vectis Ins. (the Isle of Wight)

label: Veh Ardashir/Coche/Mahoza/‘Seleucia’
description: A significant Hellenistic city that served as a capital of both the Seleucid and Parthian empires. The city was founded by Seleucus Nicator.

label: Veh Ardashir/[Bardasir]/[Govasir]
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 3 G3 Veh Ardashir/[Bardasir]/[Govasir]

label: Veh Shapur/Bishapur
description: Veh Shapur/Bishapur was an ancient city in Iran on the ancient road between Persis and Elam. This ancient and medieval town in Fārs was, in the Sasanian period, the administrative center of one of the five districts in the province of Fārs.

label: Veii
description: An important city of South Etruria located north-northwest of Rome, Veii was eventually sacked by the Romans in 396 B.C. The ancient city covered some 180 ha.

label: Velathri/Volaterrae
description: A major Etruscan city of North Etruria.

label: Velia/Elea
description: The ancient city of Elea / Velia was said to have been founded by Phocaean Greeks in the sixth century B.C. and then became an ally of Rome in the third century B.C.

label: Velitrae
description: Velitrae (modern Velletri) was an ancient Volscian settlement. In the Roman Republican period, Velitrae was attacked by Marcus Furius Camillus (379 B.C.) and again by Cincinnatus (377 B.C.); the Romans controlled the site by 365 B.C. The gens Octavia hailed from the city and a youthful Octavian spent time there.

label: Velzeke
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D2 Velzeke

label: Vendeuil-Caply
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 C3 Vendeuil-Caply

label: Venice
description: The city of Venice in northern Italy.

label: Vercellae
description: Originally a captial of the Libici, a tribe of Ligurians, Vercellae became an important Roman municipium.

label: Verneuil-en-Halatte
description: The Gallo-Roman villa is located at Bufosse in the northern part of the commune Verneuil-en-Halatte département Oise.

label: Verona
description: Verona was an ancient settlement that became a Roman colonia in 89 BC and a municipium in 49 BC.

label: Verteris
description: Roman fort in Brough, England.

label: Vervigium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 F2 Vervigium

label: Vesontio
description: Vesontion (modern Besançon) is first mentioned by Caesar in his commentaries ca. 58 BC. It is situated on a tributary of the Saône river.

label: Vesunna
description: Vesunna (Périgueux) was an oppidum of the Petrucorii that became part of Roman Aquitania.

label: Vettianus Fundus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 39 I1 Vettianus Fundus

label: Vettona
description: Vettona (modern Bettona) is an ancient settlement of Umbria located between Perusia and Mevania. Pliny the Elder lists it among the municipalities of Umbria, and it also numbered as one of the “xv Populi Umbriae".

label: Vetus Salina
description: Vetus Salina was the site of a Roman castrum on the frontier of Pannonia Inferior.

label: Vicetia
description: Vicetia (modern Vicenza) as a settlement of the Veneti in northern Italy.

label: Victoriacum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 C3 Victoriacum

label: Vicus Spacorum
description: Vicus Spacorum (modern Vigo) was an ancient settlement located on the Atlantic coast of Galicia.

label: Vidiśā
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 6 D5 Vidiśā

label: Vietri
description: Modern Vietri sul mare is the likely site of ancient Marcina, an Etruscan settlement in the ager Picentinus located 120 stades from Pompeii. It later came to be inhabited by Samnites.

label: Villa Hadriani
description: The Villa of Hadrian (Villa Adriana in Italian) is a sprawling archaeological complex at Tivoli, Italy. The villa complex was designed and used by the emperor Hadrian in the second century A.D.

label: Villa di Monte delle Colonnacce
description: A Roman villa located near Castel di Guido.

label: Villar de Brenes
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 E4 Villar de Brenes

label: Villar de don Pardo
description: A Spanish village located in the west of Jaén, near Torredelcampo, that once belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today it is known as Villardompardo.

label: Villards-d’Heria
description: A sanctuary of the Sequani at modern Villards-d'Heria in France. It is archaeologically represented by a two-part architectural complex comprising (1) north of the modern town the monumental "Pont des Arches", which supported a temple over a watercourse that supplied a large spa, and (2) at the nearby Lac-d'Antre, which supplied the majority of the water for the spa complex and also hosted additional temples along its shoreline. Plans in Vurpillot 2016 and Nouvel 2019.

label: Villevieille
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 C2 Villevieille

label: Viminacium
description: An ancient city and Roman legionary base along the Danube, near modern Kostolac (Костолац, Caştelu) in Serbia.

label: Vindasca
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 15 E2 Vindasca

label: Vindobona
description: Originally a Celtic settlement of Noricum, Vindobona (now Vienna, Austria) became a Roman military installation by the first half of the first century AD.

label: Vindocinum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 14 G1 Vindocinum

label: Vindolanda
description: A fort south of Hadrian's Wall and findspot of the Vindolanda Tablets. The earliest phases of Roman occupation date ca. 80 CE. Much of the fort was rebuilt ca. 300 CE.

label: Vindomora
description: A Roman fort at present-day Ebchester.

label: Vindonissa
description: A Roman legionary base first established ca. AD 15.

label: Vinovia
description: Vinovia was a Roman fort, now known as Binchester Roman fort, established ca. A.D. 79 to guard the crossing of Dere Street on the River Wear.

label: Vintium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 16 D2 Vintium

label: Viroconium
description: Viroconium was a large and prosperous city of Roman Britain.

label: Virosidum
description: A Roman fort at present-day Bainbridge.

label: Viroviacum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 11 D2 Viroviacum

label: Virunum
description: A Roman city, founded by Claudius, that was the capital of Noricum.

label: Vitudurum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 19 A2 Vitudurum

label: Vivarium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 17 D5 Vivarium

label: Volsiniensis L.
description: A volcanic lake of northern Latium formed by the collapse of the Vulsini volcano. Roman sources record volcanic activity at the site as late as the second century B.C.

label: Volubilis
description: A town of Mauretania Tingitana and a Roman colony.

label: Voulista Panagia
description: Described by N.G.L. Hammond writing for PECS as a fortified hill with a "circuit wall ca. 450 m long" near modern Voulista Panagia (Epirus, Greece), this site guarded a gorge leading into Central Epeiros. Hammond identified it with ancient Charadra, but Dakaris (whence BAtlas) prefers an identification with ancient Oropos.

label: Waḫšušana
description: A place from the TAVO Index

label: Withdrawn (duplicate): Lysimacheia
description: See https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/540921/

label: Xanthos/Sirbis (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 65 B5 Xanthos/Sirbis fl.

label: Xois
description: Ancient Xois was located on an island that was formed by the Sebennytic and Phatnitic branches of the Nile. It became the capital of its own nome, the Xoite nome.

label: Yassı Ada (island)
description: An island bordering the Chuka Channel in the southeastern Aegean sea; two shipwreck sites (dating to the fourth and seventh centuries A.D.) are located off its southern coast.

label: Zakythos/Zacynthus (settlement)
description: An ancient settlement on the Aegean island of the same name.

label: Zancle/Messana
description: Zancle was founded as Greek colony in the eighth century B.C. Home of the Mamertines who called for Roman assistance against Carthaginian forces in 264 B.C., sparking the First Punic War.

label: Zigana

label: Zimara
